i 31 May 2016
Inland SAR Planning Course
NOTICE TO STUDENTS
The mission of the National Search and Rescue School is to provide and 
promote standardization and professionalism in the Search and Rescue 
community. The National Search and Rescue School provides training to 
selected military and civilian personnel from around the world.
The Inland Search and Rescue (SAR) Planning course was created to 
advance the educative goals of the National SAR Plan:
• Foster a cooperative SAR network throughout the US, 
• Encourage continued development of state & local SAR facilities, 
• Educate SAR professionals on the federal government role in SAR,
• Provide sound instruction in various aspects of SAR missions, and
• Create discussion and challenge planners to improve current 
practices.
The current version recognizes the ready availability of several programs 
for the technical, hands-on aspects of search in the field, along with the 
gap in reliable materials for the less exciting but equally important aspect 
of planning how those field resources should be used. The course is 
designed to help fill that gap without undue duplication of other courses. 
The Inland SAR Planning course provides quality training to personnel 
assigned to Rescue Coordination Centers (RCC) with responsibilities for
Aeronautical and Land SAR..
The Inland SAR Planning course provides search leaders and decision 
makers from federal, state, local, and volunteer SAR agencies training on
current inland search theory. The course is intended for the people who 
need tools for use when making on-scene planning decisions: the onscene incident commander and his/her planners, operations leaders, and 
up-channel reporting chain—those people responsible for the planning and 
overall conduct of a search mission. To achieve maximum benefit from 
the course students must adopt the perspective of planners, not searchers.
This student guide contains material developed at the Air Force Element 
of the National SAR School, CG Training Center Yorktown, Virginia. 
References are listed in the Student Guide for each lesson.
