ii 31 May 2016
Introduction 
Emphasis is on the planning necessary for effective area-type searching 
during an extended search. The course presents mathematically-based 
tools that use Probability of Success (POS), rather than just a few elements 
of Probability of Containment (POC) or Probability of Detection (POD), 
to predicatively allocate limited resources to their best effect – in essence, 
what to do after the hasty search and specialty resources have not found 
the missing person or aircraft. The tools help students:
• Quantify the uncertainties in the field;
• Use information consistently throughout a search; and
• Complete planning to achieve the best possible search with 
available effort.
Additional topics help round out the course: search area development, 
effort allocation, the federal role in civil SAR, clue awareness, and other 
related subjects. The course does not teach SAR tactics or technical 
procedures.
By the end of the course, given a SAR case students should be able to:
• Obtain necessary information to activate the SAR system;
• Conduct appropriate preliminary actions (incident evaluation, 
alerting, investigation);
• Determine optimum search areas;
• Develop attainable, high-POS search plans, selecting the best 
resources and search patterns;
• Coordinate on-scene operations until the mission is terminated: 
update search plans; calculate search probabilities; assign and 
manage resources; consider logistical, family, legal, liaison, 
organizational, and other requirements
To receive a graduation certificate and be eligible to wear the SAR School 
patch/pin, the student must demonstrate adequate proficiency during 
exams and exercises.
Student progress will be evaluated by instructors using a practical 
assessment graded “Pass/Fail”, and/or a written exam requiring a score of 
70% or above. All evaluations will be open book. Students should 
receive additional on-the-job-training and local area familiarization 
before assuming duties in a SAR organization.
