Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
17 30 October 2014
Lesson 1
PRE-PLANNING
Search is an emergency with lives at stake. Victims and the public 
deserve and demand prompt, professional, well organized and effective 
responses; responses which must be prepared for and planned in order to 
be as productive as possible during the vital early stages of a search 
incident. This lesson will introduce students to concepts of SAR preplanning and some of the elements of a pre-plan.
After completing this lesson, students should:
• KNOW the elements of a pre-plan important to their SAR tasks,
• UNDERSTAND the importance of pre-planning for SAR,
• BE MOTIVATED to investigate how well their SAR agencies have
prepared for a SAR incident through pre-planning, and review their 
organizations pre-plans to improve SAR response,
• IDENTIFY areas not currently addressed in their SAR pre-plan and 
provide leadership with ideas for pre-plan improvement.
• IDENTIFY items the on-scene leadership of a SAR incident should 
have available for immediate prosecution of SAR case and state how 
those items would facilitate case execution.
The following references were used to construct the lesson:
1. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to National SAR Supplement.
2. National Search and Rescue Committee. (May 2000). National 
SAR Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual. Sec 5-17.
The major elements of a SAR pre-plan presented in this lesson are a 
starting point for SAR responsible agencies when reviewing or developing 
search and rescue pre-plans. Each student should recognize the need to 
tailor pre-plans to their own environments and requirements. Students 
should take notes on the concepts presented, how they could apply to their 
organization, and items to follow up on after completing the lesson.
Introduction 
Objectives
References 
Overview

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
18 30 October 2014
SAR Pre-Planning
According to Merriam-Webster’s Dictionary, a plan is a set of actions that 
have been thought of as a way to do or achieve something. These actions 
can be thought of as well thought-out intentions from which we may freely 
deviate as the situation warrants.
SAR pre-planning allows for rapid and flexible activation of resources in 
the event of a distress or possible distress situation. Local jurisdictions 
can increase efficiency and minimize costs by developing a SAR pre-plan. 
The pre-plan allows resource identification, recognizes hazards, creates its 
own critical review, avoids duplication of effort, and can serve as an 
orientation guide for new personnel. Pre-planning should consider the 
history of local searches, potential problems created by local terrain, legal 
constraints, etc. The pre-plan should also establish clear lines of authority.
“No plan survives first contact with the enemy.” – Helmuth von Moltke 
Why bother planning? 
• A plan is only a collection of well thought-out intended actions 
from which you may freely deviate – as the situation warrants.
• Without a good plan, you don’t know where to start deviating, how 
to deviate, or where your deviations might take you.
SAR Pre-planning benefits:
• Saves critical time, effort, and resources, especially during initial 
response,
• Frees the decision makers from side issues,
• Allows for a planned and reasoned response rather than a reaction to 
crisis events.
• Helps avoid common problems such as:
• No good starting point for response,
• Sense of urgency affects on leaders’ decision making and actions,
• Incorrect initial actions when the subject matter “expert” is not on 
duty.
SAR Pre-plan is not:
• A Search Plan or Incident Action Plan (conduct for a specific search);
• A technical manual (“How to search”); or
• A policy directive.
Preplanning 
Concepts
Pre-planning 
Benefits

