“I wish I had…”
You are the individual in charge, the “Designated Officer to Blame”, when 
you receive a telephone call in your operations center. The person on the 
other end of the line is talking hysterically about someone being missing. 
What items (particularly papers or electronic files) do you want to have 
readily available to help you handle this call and get a search incident 
started quickly? Be specific.
Now consider that you are the on-scene DOB. What additional items 
(papers and procedures, not hardware) do you wish you had readily 
available to help get on-scene operations running smoothly?
Pre-planning 
Exercise

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
20 30 October 2014
SAR Pre-Planning
Appendix C of the Land SAR Addendum to NSS has an expanded 
example of important elements of a SAR pre-plan. The example can serve 
as a starting point for an agency specific SAR pre-plan. Your pre-plan 
may include some or all of the listed elements, and your agency may need 
to include additional elements. The example in the Land SAR Addendum 
is intended to get you thinking about what you want to include in your 
SAR pre-plan. Pre-plans may include:
• Environment
• Resources
• Initial Notification
• Action Plan Development
• Support Requirements
• Post Mission Actions
Keep it simple, or no one will read or use the pre-plan. Pre-plans must be 
kept up to date. Having an out of date plan may be worse than having no 
plan because of inertia: once you start moving in a particular direction, 
even if it is the wrong direction, it is very hard to get an organization (or 
SAR response) turned around. 
You cannot rely on out-of-date information or agreements. Reviews and 
updates should be accomplished at least yearly, before and after exercises, 
and after a SAR incident.
Never plan alone. Involving others in the planning process is an important 
step that can make or break your SAR response. The planning process 
should involve every organization your plan will touch. Include them at 
each step to:
• Address their concerns;
• Tap into their expertise; 
• Reduce the risk of missing elements, needs or considerations; and
• Build vital trust between agencies which will respond to SAR incident.
Perfection is not required, however improvement is. Ensure your planning 
process has procedures for periodic reviews and improvements on at least 
an annual basis and after each use.
Successful 
Planning
Elements of 
SAR Pre-plan

