Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
22 30 October 2014
Lesson 2
LEGAL ASPECTS OF SAR
This lesson alerts students to some of the legal implications of committing 
resources to SAR. Understanding the basic legal aspects of SAR should 
motivate students to examine their agency and local laws in an effort to 
minimize legal risk and improve SAR response. None of the ideas in the 
lesson should be undertaken solely for legal reasons. The lesson content is 
not sufficient to make students experts; consult your agency legal advisor 
or state attorney general for more information and for advice on any 
situation where legal questions arise.
After completing the lesson, students should:
• UNDERSTAND the legal implications of committing SAR resources;
• UNDERSTAND basic legal terms of interest for SAR;
• INVESTIGATE their local laws related to SAR and review agency 
operations and plans to reduce legal risk;
• INVESTIGATE areas of potential risk in their organization and 
provide leadership with ideas for reducing risk;
• RECOGNIZE the need for active preparation to reduce legal risks in 
their SAR operations;
The following references were used to construct the lesson:
1. Lawson, Norman W., Jr. Legal Aspects of Search and Rescue, 
Response ’94: NASAR Conference Proceedings, Chantilly, VA; 
National Association for Search and Rescue, pp. 361-376. 
2. National Search and Rescue Committee. (May 2000). National 
SAR Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual. Chapter 7.
3. Graham, Thomas. (1995). Legal Liability in SAR. RCMP Gazette, 
57(1), 14-16
4. National Park Service. (2011). Search and Rescue Reference 
Manual (RM-59). Chapter 17
Introduction 
Objectives
References 

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
23 30 October 2014
Basics of Civil (Tort) Law
The focus of this lesson is on good SAR practices toward a prompt, 
professional response to find the search object fast. Basic legal 
terminology of interest to SAR responders and leadership is introduced. 
Common problem areas in SAR organizations and suggested actions for 
improvement or prevention are discussed. The lesson also highlights the 
legal protections available for SAR personnel, pay for rescue initiatives at 
the state level, and the effects of jurisdictional or sovereignty issues on 
SAR operations. Students are highly encouraged to contact their 
organization’s or state legal experts for information specific to their area 
of operation.
Search and rescue puts SAR resources at risk physically and legally. 
Prevention through active preparation is a good method for reducing 
vulnerability in both areas. The public expects a perfect, professional 
response for both paid and volunteer rescuers. Lawsuits tend to arise from 
a perception of expectations not being met or when negligence is 
suspected.
Negligence – A breach of a duty to act with that amount of care which a 
reasonably prudent person would use under the same or similar conditions.
• The law imposes an obligation upon every person who attempts to 
assist a person, even gratuitously, to not injure him/her by the 
negligent performance of that which he/she has undertaken.
Gross Negligence – Intentional failure to perform a manifest duty in 
reckless disregard of the consequences as affecting the life or property of 
another.
• Gross negligence involves intentional acts or failures to act, 
reckless disregard for consequences.
Vicarious Liability – Liability of an organization and its officers and 
supervisors for the acts or omissions of those whom they supervise.
Overview
Consider
Definitions

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
24 30 October 2014
Basics of Civil (Tort) Law
In order to successfully sue, a plaintiff must first prove that you have had a 
legal duty to act or to perform an act in a certain manner or to refrain 
from acting. The plaintiff must prove a legal duty existed, not a moral 
obligation. Next, the plaintiff must prove that you "breached" that duty
by not acting, acting improperly or by acting when you shouldn't have. 
Third, you must have caused some monetary loss or some loss which is 
compensable in money (may be for actual loss or for punitive purposes). 
Finally, your breach of duty must have been the proximate cause of the 
damages which the plaintiff suffered. 
• Consider whether you know the duties and limitations of those 
working for you, especially of volunteer SAR organizations you call to 
support your SAR operations.
Standard of Care is referred to or means “good and accepted practice”. 
You will likely be held to the legal standard of a reasonable professional, 
not just a reasonable person or average man on the street. Being a 
volunteer is not an excuse. 
If you say or demonstrate you can do something, you may have 
undertaken a duty to perform in the future – you may have engendered the 
reliance of the public on your performance.
• Consider how you/your organization present yourselves to the public; 
does the public expect more than you can deliver?
Consider you lead/supervise a ground SAR team. Some members of your 
organization happen to be SAR dog handlers certified by another agency, 
but canine searching is not part of what your team does. Consider the 
legal implications of:
• Using them, especially if injury or damage results;
• Using them, likely giving the public a new view of what you do;
• Not using them, when their use might have saved a life.
Consider an EMT who can perform at a higher level than your team’s 
basic first aid training. How does he/she affect:
• Liability, indemnification, and insurance coverage?
• The public perception of what you do or will do?
The answers to the above considerations vary depending on who you are 
working for, whether they requested you perform that extra service or 
capability, and how their insurance is written. 
Duty to Act
Standard of 
Care
Engendered 
Reliance
Conflicting 
Qualifications

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
25 30 October 2014
Common Problem Areas
In looking at how search and rescue organizations can get in trouble, 
Norman Lawson (see supplemental readings, section 2-A) noted several 
factors consistently emerging. Students should take actions to ensure 
these common problems don’t occur in your organization. Improvements 
in each of the six common problem areas should not only reduce your 
organizations potential for legal action, but should improve your search 
and rescue response.
• Organization’s mission is not clearly defined;
• Personnel are not trained to perform the job or mission;
• Personnel do not have equipment to perform the job;
• Organization has not established liaisons with responsible agencies 
and/or support agencies;
• Organization lacks supervision, direction or control; and
• Organization is not maintaining appropriate documentation.
Generally speaking, if you say you can do something the law expects you 
to be able to do it. A common problem is an organization has not clearly 
defined its mission, and does not have a mission statement. Lack of a 
mission statement can cause a number of problems, including:
• Public may expect more (or less) than you can deliver;
• Team members:
o May think they can/should do more or less than the organizations 
is prepared to undertake;
o May not be prepared to perform required tasks or may not 
understand the extent of their commitments;
o May make informal commitments, potentially engendering the 
reliance of the public on a capability the organization does not 
have;
o May free lance, over/under extend themselves during a mission, or 
take excessive/unreasonable risks.
Six Common 
Problems
Mission 
Problem Areas

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
26 30 October 2014
Common Problem Areas
A clear, concise, limited mission statement for an organization will 
resolve most of the problems above. Organization leadership and members 
all know exactly what their team does and does not do. The general public 
and agencies that call on you for assistance know exactly what your 
organization does. Once you have a mission statement it needs to be 
publicized both internally and externally as often as possible.
If you say you can do something the law presumes you know how and you 
will perform correctly. Typical problems related to training for SAR 
organizations include:
• Inappropriate actions i.e. doing the wrong thing;
• Errors i.e. doing the right thing poorly or incorrectly; and 
• Omissions i.e. not acting or not doing enough.
Training must be:
• Appropriate:
o Related to the stated mission and needs, local laws and 
requirements, and
o Use expert sources and standards for training.
• Complete:
o Initial, refresher and update training;
o Use evaluations, drills and exercises.
• Honest: Rigorously evaluated and documented. If someone fails, 
document re-training actions and evaluations.
Preventing 
Problems with 
Mission
Training 
Problem Areas
Preventing 
Problems with 
Training

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
27 30 October 2014
Common Problem Areas
If you say you can do something the law presumes you have the required 
equipment, know how to use it properly, and the equipment will work. 
Common equipment problems with SAR organizations include:
• Required equipment is not on hand (not appropriate or not sufficient 
for the task):
• Equipment is available but is not used;
• Equipment is used incorrectly; or
• Equipment fails.
Simply having equipment you think you need is not adequate. Consider if 
there are national equipment standards for your mission. Evaluate how 
closely linked your equipment, training, and mission are. Equipment 
should be addressed in your pre-plan. Make sure your organizations 
equipment (and your own) is:
• Appropriate for expected operations (your mission). Check for 
standards and ask recognized experts in your field;
• Safe – Check OSHA and local laws;
• Trained on/with;
• Maintained properly, including making use of checklists, inspections, 
and an accurate inventory.
Large SAR incidents frequently involve people from multiple agencies. 
How well they work together usually depends on the quality of liaisons or 
relationships built beforehand. The public and victim do not care about 
turf battles or personality conflicts; they just expect a prompt, professional 
response from everyone involved. Problems which arise from having a 
number of organizations and jurisdictions include:
• Turf battles, especially when jurisdictional boundaries are involved;
• Dissimilar methods and techniques causing confusion and wasting 
limited resources and time;
• Lack of cooperation when perception is the leader is not considering
the inputs and concerns of other agencies.
Equipment 
Problem Areas
Preventing 
Problems with 
Equipment
Liaisons 
Problem Areas

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
28 30 October 2014
Common Problem Areas
Use your pre-planning efforts. Include others in the process and know 
beforehand who will be responsible on-scene for each type of incident. 
Formalize organizational relationships in writing. Get people from 
organizations together regularly to discuss problems and foster 
cooperation, then attempt to train, practice and exercise together. Ask 
yourself:
• Who might you have to work with in the future?
• Who might you call on to help, and who might call you?
• Were they involved in crafting your pre-plan?
• Are the working relationships in your pre-plan?
• When was the last time you exercised your liaisons?
Supervisors are responsible for their organization and the actions of 
everyone in the organization, and may be held liable for failures, acts, or 
omissions by anyone on their team. Common supervisory problems 
include:
• Failure to take charge, including:
o Inadequate or delayed decision making;
o Poor coordination of search effort and all supporting activities;
o Failure to identify and correct problems.
• Failure to supervise, including:
o Not assigning properly trained people to tasks;
o Not correcting breaches of discipline or unprofessional conduct by 
members;
o Failure to set and enforce appropriate rules and standards;
o Searching, rather than supervising and managing.
Supervision 
Problem Areas
Preventing 
Problems with 
Liaisons

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
29 30 October 2014
Common Problem Areas
First and foremost, supervisors must be prepared to supervise. Individuals 
placed in supervisory positions require the personal strength of character 
to make hard choices, enforce standards, and supervise. They should not 
get distracted by the urge to go out and search, as their responsibilities 
cover the entire search effort. Supervisors should:
• Control the “sense of urgency” to maintain a level-headed sense of 
direction for the SAR effort;
• Control the urge to freelance and improvise inappropriately;
• Maintain discipline and adherence to standards:
o Be prepared for the occasional member who does not maintain 
standards or does not follow rules and procedures. Ensure your 
agency has procedures for disciplining members who do not follow 
the rules
Be sure supervision is incorporated into your SAR pre-plan to help 
accomplish some of the problems addressed above. Additionally your 
supervisor training program should address common problem areas to help 
prepare supervisors for their new responsibilities.
“The job isn’t finished until the paperwork is done.” or “If it’s not written 
down, it didn’t happen.” SAR agencies and organizations frequently suffer 
from inadequate or incomplete documentation. Areas inadequately 
documented include:
• Mission statement;
• Qualification requirements;
• Historical mission/incident data;
• Individual case logs, including why decisions were made;
• Training records;
• Equipment inspections;
• Agreements with other agencies/organizations.
Preventing 
Problems with 
Supervision
Documentation 
Problem Areas

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
30 30 October 2014
Common Problem Areas
Routine documentation should include a formal record of everything your 
agency does. Include: training, equipment maintenance, meeting minutes, 
qualifications, etc.
On scene documentation should include:
• Agency response;
• Activities, search progress, leads and follow-up actions;
• Condition, position of search object when found with photos if 
possible;
• After-action reports/lessons learned and actions taken to correct 
problems identified;
• Decisions and judgment used in making decisions;
o Why you made a decision
o What you considered as important or discarded
o Any factors that affected your decisions
The above items are not all inclusive, so review your organizational
documentation processes and requirements. Include how documentation is 
safeguarded, how to determine when documents become “records” and 
errors in a document can no longer be corrected.
Preventing 
Problems with 
Documentation

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
31 30 October 2014
Laws Protecting Searchers
Laws have been created in an effort to protect searchers from liability for 
actions taken in good faith while rendering emergency care, balanced 
against the need to protect victims from further harm. Students must 
contact their organization legal advisor for advice on laws and protections 
in their area
Laws or acts designed to protect those who choose to serve and tend to 
others who are injured, ill, in peril, or otherwise incapacitated. The intent 
is to reduce bystanders' hesitation to assist for fear of being sued or 
prosecuted for unintentional injury or wrongful death. These laws 
generally do not apply to the on-the-job conduct of medical professionals 
or career emergency responders; but some laws extend protection to
professional rescuers when they are acting in a volunteer capacity.
• Good Samaritan Laws differ by state. Contact your state Attorney 
General! Preview most Good Samaritan laws online at: 
www.cprinstructor.com/legal.htm; 
• Typically do not prohibit litigation, but may limit liability;
• May not cover SAR;
• May only cover certain people or groups, often only those who do not 
have a duty to act.
Also known as Public Law 105-19, Volunteer Protection Act, a law passed 
by the federal government in 1997 intended to protect volunteers who do 
not have protection based in a state Good Samaritan law. The Volunteer 
Protection Act is intended to give either protection when none exists in 
statutes or to give a higher level of protection.
“Volunteer of non-profit organization or government entity shall not be 
held liable for harm caused by an act or omission of the volunteer on 
behalf of the organization or entity if the volunteer meets 4 requirements.”
• Volunteer acting within the scope of their responsibilities;
• Volunteer is properly licensed, certified, or authorized;
• Harm is not caused by misconduct, gross negligence, indifference to 
rights/safety of the individual harmed; and
• Harm is not caused by volunteer operating vehicle, vessel, etc which 
requires an operator’s license or insurance.
Background
Good Samaritan 
Laws
Volunteer 
Protection Act 
of 1997

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
32 30 October 2014
Laws Protecting Searchers
The Volunteer Protection Act has not been tested in court for search and 
rescue. It appears to only protect volunteers who act in a prudent manner,
and only provides protection from damages associated with mental 
anguish, pain and suffering, acts of other team members, etc. The law only 
limits the punitive damages that may be awarded against the volunteer (i.e. 
punishment). Protection may not apply to volunteers acting under 
authority of local law enforcement or under contract with local emergency 
management, and protection may be affected by cost reimbursement 
arrangements.
Students must check for local or state regulation of SAR teams, 
specifically looking for legislated standards, equipment requirements, 
procedures to be used for search and rescue. Know the laws in your state 
and make sure you are in compliance.
Volunteer 
Protection Act 
of 1997
Local/State 
Regulations

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
33 30 October 2014
Other Legal Aspects
Non-law enforcement searchers, including Civil Air Patrol, Coast Guard 
Auxiliary, volunteer members of SAR teams, etc have the same authority 
as private citizens; none. Consider their lack of authority when making
task assignments requiring authority.
Make a determination in pre-plan whether your organization will use 
untrained volunteers who are not part of SAR teams or organizations. 
Consider the liability of using and/or not using volunteers, and the types of 
assignments you are willing to give them. Also determine if they are 
covered by insurance or indemnification plans if you make use of 
untrained volunteers in a search. Ensure you have a briefing or 
information sheet to provide volunteers which clearly spells out what to 
expect while searching, potential hazards, equipment needed, and time 
frame involved at a minimum. Contact your legal advisor for other items 
to include in a briefing/information sheet.
Questions regarding untrained volunteers you should consider before an 
incident include:
• What are the legal implications of:
o Using them, especially if an injury or damage results?
o If you use untrained volunteers, does it effect on public view of 
what your organization does?
o Not using volunteers, when their use might have saved a life either 
directly or indirectly by allowing you to better utilize trained 
personnel?
• What constitutes using or assigning an untrained volunteer?
• Once untrained volunteer is on-scene, what are your responsibilities 
toward them?
o Health and safety?
o Food, water, shelter?
o Reimbursement for expenses?
Limits of 
Authority
Volunteer 
Considerations

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
34 30 October 2014
Other Legal Aspects
SAR is not a license to trespass on or enter private property. Laws on 
trespassing and the expectation of reasonable privacy vary from state to 
state, so contact your legal advisor. In general, SAR teams:
• Should obtain the owner’s permission to enter private property;
• Must be reasonably certain SAR objective could be on the property;
• Must minimize damage and safeguard private property; and 
• Notify/involve law enforcement beforehand.
Posse Comitatus Act (18 USC 1385) prohibits the use of federal military 
assets to execute U.S. domestic law (federal, state or local). The original 
Posse Comitatus Act referred essentially to the U.S. Army. The U.S. Air 
Force was added in 1956, and the U.S. Navy and the U.S. Marine Corps
have been included by a regulation of the Department of Defense. The law 
prohibits federal military assets from direct participation in searching for 
escapees or fleeing suspects, seizure, arrest, or similar activities.
The Act does not apply to the National Guard under state (Governor)
authority from acting in a law enforcement capacity within its home.
Investigate you agency/organization workman’s compensation, 
indemnification, and medical coverage. Know exactly who is covered and 
under what conditions. Questions to ask include: What happens to 
coverage if you cross county/state/jurisdictional boundaries? Are others 
you call in for assistance covered? Does coverage extend to personnel 
when/if they are in an aircraft for searching, rescue or transport? Some 
workman’s compensation and insurance does not cover personnel in an 
aircraft if that is not a normal part of their duties.
U.S. federal policy prohibits agencies which are signatories of the 
National SAR Plan from reimbursement for SAR. However, as state and 
local agencies are not bound by the National SAR Plan the federal 
government can only discourage those agencies from charging for 
search/rescue. Considerations for why agencies should not charge for 
assistance include:
• May affect when/if victims call for help;
• May affect when/if volunteer agencies are called to assist;
• Protection under Good Samaritan statutes;
• Reimbursement and resupply procedures.
Trespass
Posse 
Comitatus Act 
of 1878
Damage and 
Injuries
Pay-for-Rescue

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
35 30 October 2014
Other Legal Aspects
The U.S. is party to a number of treaties and agreements related to search 
and rescue. In addition to prohibiting expense reimbursement for SAR 
services to citizens of other countries who are in distress, these agreements 
also set out a number of limitations or rules. The bottom line is 
international agreements, protocols, and sovereignty must be followed, 
and outweigh personal desires. If in doubt as to SAR limitations set forth 
by treaty or agreement with another country, contact the Air Force Rescue 
Coordination Center for information.
Many of the same jurisdictional issues from international SAR may also 
apply to inter-state SAR. Each state has a responsible authority for SAR 
within their borders, and typically does not allow assets from other states 
to search within their borders without coordination. 
Aside from issues of authority to search, states also have liability 
concerns; specifically who is responsible for resources from one state if 
the resource is damaged or people are injured/killed while searching in 
another state. Organization insurance and indemnification may not extend 
to another state, leaving your personnel without legal and insurance 
protection.
