Lesson 3
NATIONAL SAR SYSTEM 
This lesson is designed to introduce you to overall structure of the national 
SAR system and the role of the two aeronautical Rescue Coordination 
Centers as the coordinating element for the SAR Coordinator of the 
aeronautical SAR Region. It also provides an overview of federal search 
and rescue capabilities. 
At the end of this lesson, investigate how you and your agency fit into the 
SAR system and prepare yourself to work within the system.
After completing this lesson, you should be able to:
• Be FAMILIAR with the structure of the US national SAR system,
• Be able to SUMMARIZE the responsibilities and attributes of the key 
SAR organizational elements/roles (SC, SMC, RCC, OSC, SRU) in 
the federal SAR system,
• UNDERSTAND your position/role in the SAR system and how you 
fit into your state’s structure,
• KNOW the function and limitations of the RCCs.
The information in this lesson can be found in the following references:
1. IMO & ICAO. (2013). International Aeronautical and Maritime 
Search and Rescue (IAMSAR) Manual, Vol. II. Sec 1
2. National Search and Rescue Committee. (May 2000). National SAR 
Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual. Chapters 1, 2, 4, and Appendix A.
3. National Search and Rescue Committee. (2007). National SAR Plan.
4. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to National SAR Supplement. Chapter 1 and Appendix H.
5. National Search and Rescue Committee Interagency Agreement.
(2007).
References 
Introduction
Objectives

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
37 1 May 2015
US SAR System
The United States (US) is a participant to both the International Maritime 
Organization (IMO) and the International Civil Aviation Organization 
(ICAO). The IMO and the ICAO combined efforts to develop the 
IAMSAR Manual in order to assist States in meeting their own search and 
rescue needs, and obligations under the IMO and ICAO conventions. The 
IAMSAR Manual provides guidelines for a common aviation and 
maritime approach to organizing and providing SAR services --- it 
represents a body of knowledge from and for participating States.
• Volume 1 is for managers, provides the “big picture”, useful for high 
level organization.
• Volume 2 assists personnel who plan and coordinate SAR operations 
and exercises --- aka Rescue Coordination Centers.
• Volume 3 is primarily designed for operators, to carry on board a SAR 
facility (aircraft, vessel, etc.).
The US SAR System is composed of a cabinet level regulatory board 
called the National Search and Rescue Committee, a federal regulatory 
agreement called the National Search and Rescue Plan, and national 
guidance supplementing the IAMSAR Manual called the National Search 
and Rescue Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual.
The Land SAR Addendum to the National SAR Supplement was created 
to provide standardized guidance and information on the search and rescue 
of persons, vehicles, and missing aircraft operations.
A Search and Rescue Region (SRR) is an internationally recognized area 
of defined dimensions associated with one SAR Coordinator (SC) and one
Rescue Coordination Center (RCC). SCs are responsible for establishing 
and providing SAR services within a SRR.
An RCC is responsible for promoting efficient organization of SAR 
services and coordinates the conduct of SAR operations within a SRR. 
The US has 11 Federal RCCs:
• US Northern Command: aeronautical SRR corresponding to the 
CONUS other than Alaska; and the aeronautical SRR corresponding to 
Alaska.
• Coast Guard: all other nine (9) aeronautical and maritime SRRs. This 
includes Hawaii and federal navigable waterways of the US.
Find out how your organization fits into the U.S. National SAR structure, 
which roles you may be called upon to fill (remember, they may change as 
a mission grows or scales back), and the division of responsibilities.
What to Do
