Rescue Regions 
and RCCs

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
38 1 May 2015
US SAR System
Paragraph 8 of the National SAR Plan (NSP) specifically prohibits the 
federal government from violating the rights of the states.
All states have retained the right to perform intrastate SAR; however, it is 
still a responsibility of the federal government to ensure interstate SAR is 
performed and to provide assistance to the states when requested.
Why the confusion between aeronautical and land authorities? Planes fly 
across multiple states (jurisdictions). Missing planes in the air eventually 
become missing planes on the ground. Distress beacon notifications, 
regardless of type (ELT, EPIRB, PLB), are always received by the 
geographically responsible RCC --- not the State.
The procedures for how the federal government will assist with SAR in 
each state are established through a memorandum of agreement between 
the Inland SAR Coordinator and the Governor of each state. (NOTE: The 
Alaska SAR Coordinator has no agreement with the Alaska Governor).
Agreements (on how SAR assistance will be coordinated) are further 
defined in a memorandum of understanding between the state SAR agency 
and the commander of the RCCs.
MOA/MOU with 
the States
State SAR 
Authority

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
39 1 May 2015
Aeronautical SAR
The Commander, US Northern Command (USNORTHCOM), is the SAR 
Coordinator charged with the overall responsibility for establishing, 
staffing, equipping and managing the SAR system for the aeronautical 
region over the continental US and Alaska. USNORTHCOM has no 
resources or budget for planning and executing SAR operations. 
Consequently, USNORTHCOM coordinates with the Civil Air Patrol and 
almost 3,100 different State and Local agencies with a SAR response 
authority to plan and execute the search for missing aircraft and distress 
beacon alerts.
The Alaska and Air Force RCCs coordinate aeronautical SAR operations 
that include:
• Commercial and General Aviation aircraft on an interstate flight
• DoD aircraft in distress
• Aircraft on missions of national concern (for example, National 
Special Security Events)
The Air Force Rescue Coordination Center (AFRCC) is co-located with 
the 601st Air and Space Operations Center (601 AOC) at Tyndall Air 
Force Base, Panama City, Florida. The AFRCC coordinates SAR services 
for aeronautical and other types of land-based SAR within the aeronautical 
SRR corresponding to the continental US other than Alaska. This 
CONUS area is comprised of a multitude of state and local SAR authority 
jurisdictions: (48 states plus DC and 3039 counties in the CONUS).
In addition to the above mentioned RCC responsibilities, the AFRCC 
receives all aircraft ELT and personal locator beacon (PLB) Notices of 
Country Registration (NOCRs). NOCRs are distress alerts from beacons 
which are registered in the US, but are geographically located outside the 
US at the time of activation.
The Alaska Rescue Coordination Center is responsible for over 586,000 
square miles of the US’s most northern state. Missions in the Alaskan 
SRR are marked by challenging terrain, harsh winter conditions, and high 
risk of exposure
The Alaska Rescue Coordination Center (AKRCC) is co-located with the 
611th Air and Space Operations Center (611 AOC) at Elmendorf AFB, 
Anchorage, Alaska. Per agreement with USCG District 17, the USCG is 
responsible for coordinating aeronautical SAR operations in areas south of 
58 degrees north latitude/west of 141 degrees west longitude.
NOTE: AKRCC is the Incident Commander for SAR operations 
conducted by the Alaska Air National Guard’s 210th Rescue Wing.
