Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
40 1 May 2015
Aeronautical SAR
The RCCs are responsible for coordinating the response to COSPASSARSAT distress beacon notifications within their respective SRR.
In developing a cooperative network for SAR, the RCCs help to broker 
assistance to the States, when requested. There are some considerations 
when brokering the request:
• A valid (or perceived) distress situation must exist. These distress 
situations are normally assessed in terms of a threat to life, limb, or 
eyesight.
• Federal organizations cannot charge for SAR services, so SAR 
operations are paid for through their own agency funding sources. 
Consequently, most federal agencies (including the DoD) will only 
respond when the request does not interfere with the primary mission.
• States have retained the authority --- and thus the responsibility --- for 
providing for SAR services within their state boundary. Thus, federal 
SAR providers should ensure that state and local capabilities (to 
include commercial SAR services) have been considered and/or 
exhausted.
• The Posse Comitatus Act limits the powers of Federal government in 
using federal military personnel to enforce the state laws. Thus, if a 
search for a missing person or aircraft becomes a law enforcement 
issue, the RCCs will not broker federal capabilities to support the 
search.
• The primary emphasis of SAR operations is to assist persons in 
distress. Land and aeronautical SAR missions should not normally be 
performed for the purpose of … salvage or recovery of property when 
those actions are not essential to the saving of persons in distress. This 
includes the recovery of human remains.
SAR Assistance 
Policy

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
41 1 May 2015
Resources
Anyone can initiate a SAR incident: FAA, Law Enforcement, even 
concerned family or friends. Once notified, the RCCs uses internet and 
telephonic investigative capabilities to assist in all phases of a SAR event, 
including:
• Aircraft and distress beacon registration data
• Weather data (historical and forecasted)
• Cell phone and radar forensics
• National Alert Warning System
• Aircraft Wreckage Locator Database
Aeronautical RCCs provide support to the States or SAR authorities not 
involving aeronautical SAR (search for missing aircraft or beacon 
activations). Typical types of missions include Rescue, Mercy, SRU 
Transport, MEDEVAC, Search, and Patient Transfer. 
The Secretary of Defense directs all Services and other components of the 
US Department of Defense (DoD) to support civil SAR. DoD support to
civil SAR is provided on a not-to-interfere basis with its primary duties.
The USCG is charged with search and rescue as one of its 11 primary 
responsibilities. As such, the USCG maintains a high capable fleet of air 
and maritime vessels ready to support state and local SAR efforts. In 
addition to the US Coast Guard, other components of DHS which typically 
provide support to SAR include Customs and Border Protection (CBP) 
and the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA).
Finally, the National Park Service responds to incidents ranging from 
searching for lost hikers to performing complex technical rescues in high 
altitude, mountainous environments. 
The Civil Air Patrol (CAP), also known as the USAF Auxiliary, is a 
congressionally chartered non-profit organization --- similar to the USCG 
Auxiliary. CAP has both aviation and ground search capabilities.
