Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
42 1 May 2015
Resources
There are two sources of radar data, both of which can be directly 
requested by any RCC:
• Civil radar data comes from the FAA’s TRACON / ARTCC facilities 
through the National Track and Analysis Program (NTAP.
• Military radar data comes from the DoD’s 84th Radar Evaluation 
Squadron which provides radar data for all three US Air Defense 
Sector operations.
The Civil Air Patrol’s (CAP) National Radar Analysis Team (NRAT) uses 
its proprietary track analysis program to fuse data from radar, weather 
terrain warning, radar coverage prediction, and multiple map imagery sets, 
into one integrated display. 
CAP NRAT capabilities can only be requested through the AFRCC or 
AKRCC.
By federal statute (18 § U.S.C. 2702 (b) (8)), a cellular service provider 
may divulge the contents of a communication to a governmental entity, if 
the provider, in good faith, believes that an emergency involving danger of 
death or serious physical injury to any person requires disclosure without 
delay of communications relating to the emergency.
The Civil Air Patrol’s Cellular Forensics Team has developed a 
proprietary cellular data analysis program. Utilizing relationships and 
procedures built with all national cellular service providers, the Cellular 
Forensics Team can Collect, Analyze and Present cellular data fused with 
cellular coverage prediction and multiple map imagery sets, into one 
integrated display.
CAP Cellular Forensics Team capabilities can only be requested through 
the AFRCC or AKRCC.
