Lesson 4
COSPAS-SARSAT SYSTEM & DISTRESS BEACONS
The lesson provides an overview of the international Cosas-Sarsat system 
and an understanding of the operations and limitations of distress beacons. 
One of the major technological advantages search managers have in aiding 
their search is the Distress Beacon. Unfortunately, widespread 
misunderstanding and misuse of distress beacons hampers their 
effectiveness. 
After completing this lesson, you should be able to:
• Be FAMILIAR with the parts of the Cospas-Sarsat system,
• Be FAMILIAR with the operating characteristics of distress beacons,
• UNDERSTAND the limitations of an ELT,
• KNOW how to help locate and investigate distress beacon signals,
The following references were used to construct this lesson:
1. FAA TSO-C126b. (2012). 406 MHz Emergency Locator Transmitters.
2. Radio Technical Commission for Aeronautics [RTCA]. (1983). 
Document No. DO-183, “Minimum Operational Performance 
Standards for Emergency Locator Transmitters”
3. Cospas-Sarsat Secretariate. (2012). Cospas-Sarsat Information 
Bulletins. Available on-line at http://www.cospas-sarsat.org.
4. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to National SAR Supplement. 
5. Air Force Rescue Coordination Center. (2014). Annual Report.
This lesson presents an overview of the Cospas-Sarsat Programme and a 
discussion of distress beacons to include methods for locating them. It is 
important to treat all beacons as distress until they can be confirmed as 
non-distress. Students should take notes on the elements you need to 
check on and tell others about when you get home.
Introduction
Objectives
Overview
