Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
44 30 October 2014
Cospas-Sarsat System Overview
The International Cospas-Sarsat Programme is a satellite-based search and 
rescue (SAR) distress alert detection and information distribution system, 
best known for detecting and locating emergency beacons activated by 
aircraft, ships and backcountry hikers in distress.
The International Cospas-Sarsat Programme began as a joint effort of 
Canada, France, the United States, and the former Soviet Union in 1979.
It was formally constituted as an intergovernmental organisation in 1988 
through the International Cospas-Sarsat Programme Agreement signed by 
Canada, France, the USA and the former USSR. The Russian Federation 
replaced the USSR as Party to the Agreement in January 1992.
The Cospas-Sarsat System is composed of:
• distress radio beacons (ELTs for aviation use, EPIRBs for maritime 
use, and PLBs for personal use) which transmit signals during distress 
situations;
• instruments on board satellites in geostationary and low-altitude Earth 
orbits which detect the signals transmitted by distress radio beacons;
• ground receiving stations, referred to as Local Users Terminals 
(LUTs), which receive and process the satellite downlink signal to 
generate distress alerts; and
• Mission Control Centers (MCCs) which receive alerts produced by 
LUTs and forward them to Rescue Coordination Centers (RCCs), 
Search and Rescue Points Of Contacts (SPOCs) or other MCCs.
The Cospas-Sarsat System includes two types of satellites:
• satellites in low-altitude Earth orbit (LEO) 
• satellites in geostationary Earth orbit (GEO) 
The future Cospas-Sarsat System will include a new type of satellite in the 
medium-altitude Earth orbit (MEO) which will form the MEOSAR 
System.
Cospas-Sarsat 
Programme
Cospas-Sarsat 
System 
Overview

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
45 30 October 2014
Distress Beacons
Distress beacons are manufactured to stringent national (SARSAT) and 
international (Cospas-Sarsat) standards and are designed to operate 
anywhere in the world. There are three types:
• Electronic Locator Transmitter (ELT): for aeronautical use
• Emergency Position-Indicating Radio Beacon (EPRIB): for maritime 
use
• Personal Locator Beacon (PLB): for personal use
ELTs, EPIRBs, and PLBs all operate on the 406 MHz frequency. Upon 
activation, each 406 MHz beacon transmits a unique digital code that 1) 
identifies the individual beacon, and 2) provides approximate location data 
via satellite. That unique beacon code is linked to beacon registration 
data, which can provide information such as the beacon owner; the type of 
platform the beacon is associated with; emergency points of contact; and 
much more.
• Most beacons allow GPS-sourced location data to be integrated into 
the distress signal.
The FAA still authorizes the use of older generation ELTs for use by 
aircraft operating within the US. These beacons, transmitting on 
121.5/243.0 MHz, may be detected by nearby aircraft or ground stations 
monitoring the respective frequency. The Cospas-Sarsat satellite system 
no longer monitors these frequencies.
Register your 406 MHz beacon!! U.S. SARSAT policy mandates all 406 
MHz beacons be registered with NOAA. You should encourage all 
owners of 406 MHz beacons to register their beacons at:
http://www.beaconregistration.noaa.gov.
Since the 406 MHz beacon usually contains GPS-encoded location 
information, responders simply receive the coordinates and proceed direct 
to the area of the beacon activation.
Otherwise, searchers must apply various techniques for locating activated 
beacons. See NSS Land Addendum pg 5-30 for techniques for search 
areas based on audible reports.
Distress 
Beacons 
Overview
Locating
beacons

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
46 30 October 2014
Distress Beacons
The emergence of non-SARSAT compliant distress beacons warrants 
awareness by SAR personnel. Collectively identified by the CospasSarsat Programme as commercial emergency notification, alerting and 
locating devices (CENALD), these devices are commercially available to 
the general public and have the potential to cause confusion within the 
established system. While these devices are typically cheaper to purchase 
than a PLB, they typically require an annual subscription fee (use of 
Cospas-Sarsat PLBs is always free to the end user). Additional features 
not found on PLBs may include GPS navigation, distress alerting (“911”), 
messaging, and tracking for both emergency services and non-emergency 
communications. Notification of CENALD activation is received at a 
proprietary commercial monitoring center, which then uses a Public Safety 
Answering Point to alert the local law enforcement. However, local law 
enforcement may or may not be the agency having jurisdictional authority 
for search and rescue in that area.
Given the wide appeal in the added functionality of CENALDs, 406 MHz 
beacon manufacturers offer a subscription service linked to a PLB’s selftest function. Called 406Link, the service takes advantage of the PLB’s 
self-test function to send non-distress messages via text and e-mail. 
Further information about 406Link can be found at http://406link.com.
