Lesson 5
CATASTROPHIC INCIDENT SEARCH AND RESCUE
This lesson introduces students to Catastrophic Incident Search and 
Rescue as SAR operations carried out as all or part of the response to an 
emergency or disaster declared by the President, under provisions of the 
National Response Framework and its Emergency Support Function #9, 
Search and Rescue (ESF-9).
After completing this lesson, you should be able to:
• UNDERSTAND the unique guidance which applies for federal 
responders during a CISAR response,
• KNOW which federal agencies may be designated to support SAR 
efforts for a catastrophic incident,
• KNOW the trigger for a federal CISAR response,
The following references were used to construct this lesson:
• U.S. Department of Homeland Security. (Jan 2008). National Response 
Framework.
• Federal Emergency Management Agency. (Feb 2011). Emergency 
Support Function #9. 
• National Search and Rescue Committee. (Jun 2012). Catastrophic 
Incident SAR Addendum to National SAR Supplement. Version 3.0.
Objectives
Introduction
References

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
48 30 October 2014
Guidance and Definitions
The Catastrophic Incident SAR (CISAR) Addendum to the National 
Search and Rescue Supplement (NSS) was created to address response to 
catastrophic incidents in support of state, tribal, territorial, and local 
authorities. The CISAR Addendum does not supersede other Federal, 
State, Tribal, or Territorial SAR plans. The CISAR Addendum:
• Describes the federal government’s SAR response to catastrophic 
incidents;
• Provides guidance for federal authorities involved in response; and
• Informs states, tribes, territories, and local government what to 
expect when federal SAR responders are requested for assistance.
The Homeland Security Presidential Directive 5 (HSPD-5) directs the 
Federal Government to establish a single, comprehensive approach to 
domestic incident management. As the principal Federal official for 
domestic incident management, the Secretary for Homeland Security 
coordinates the Federal Government’s response.
The Robert T. Stafford Disaster Relief and Emergency Assistance Act
describes the programs and processes by which the Federal Government 
provides disaster and emergency assistance to State and local 
governments.
• Reflects the fact that federal resources under this act supplement state 
and local resources for disaster relief and recovery.
The Economy Act authorizes Federal agencies to provide goods or 
services, on a reimbursable basis, to other Federal agencies when more 
specific statutory authority does not exist.
The National Response Framework is a guide to how the Nation conducts 
all-hazards response. It is built upon scalable, flexible, and adaptable 
coordinating structures to align key roles and responsibilities across the 
Nation, linking all levels of government, nongovernmental organizations, 
and the private sector. It is intended to capture specific authorities and best 
practices for managing incidents that range from the serious but purely 
local, to large-scale terrorist attacks or catastrophic natural disasters. 
• DHS may act when the resources of State and local authorities are 
overwhelmed and Federal assistance has been requested by the 
appropriate State and local authorities;
Guidance

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
49 30 October 2014
Guidance and Definitions
The Emergency Support Function #9 – Search and Rescue Annex to the 
NRF rapidly deploys Federal SAR resources to provide lifesaving 
assistance to State, tribal, and local authorities, to include local SAR 
Coordinators and Mission Coordinators, when there is an actual or 
anticipated request for Federal SAR assistance.
During incidents or potential incidents requiring a unified SAR response, 
Federal SAR responsibilities reside with ESF #9 primary agencies that 
provide timely and specialized SAR capabilities. Support agencies 
provide specific capabilities or resources that support ESF #9. Federal
SAR response operational environments are classified as:
• Structural Collapse (Urban) Search and Rescue (US&R)
• Maritime/Coastal/Waterborne Search and Rescue
• Land Search and Rescue
ESF #9 capabilities include distress monitoring, communications, location 
of distressed personnel, coordination, and rescue operations including 
extrication or evacuation along with medical assistance to assist persons 
and property in potential or actual distress.
Catastrophic Incident is any natural or manmade incident, including 
terrorism, which results in extraordinary levels of mass casualties, damage 
or disruption severely affecting the population, infrastructure, 
environment, economy, national morale, and/or government functions.
Catastrophic Incident Search and Rescue (CISAR) consists of civil SAR 
operations carried out as all or part of the response to an emergency or 
disaster declared by the President under provisions of the National 
Response Framework and Emergency Support Function #9. For civil SAR 
operations to be identified as CISAR the response must be associated with 
a Presidential declaration and ESF #9 must be implemented.
Definitions

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
50 30 October 2014
Process for Presidential Declaration
An incident response begins with the establishment of a Unified 
Command and an Incident Command Post. As local responders become 
overwhelmed or lacking in needed capabilities, they notify their 
organizations/leadership. Mutual aid or other assistance can be requested 
from other counties, tribes, or the state. 
The state Governor can declare a state emergency in all affected areas and 
direct the use of state resources to meet local needs. If capabilities are 
required, the Governor can coordinate for assistance from other states via 
mechanisms such as the Emergency Management Assistance Compact 
(EMAC). If additional assistance/capabilities are required, the Governor 
can ask for a Presidential declaration of emergency/disaster via FEMA.
Once the President makes a declaration, federal response teams and 
resources can deploy. The President appoints a Federal Coordinating 
Officer to lead a Joint Field Office (JFO). For potential incidents with 
warning (hurricane, floods, etc), federal resources may be able to deploy 
in advance of an anticipated catastrophic incident.
When SAR is a requested support function, ESF #9 is established in the 
JFO. The ESF #9 response is scalable to meet the specific needs of each 
incident, based upon the nature and magnitude of the event, the 
suddenness of onset, and the capability of local SAR resources. Response 
resources are drawn from ESF #9 primary and support agencies.
The Presidential disaster or emergency declaration essentially triggers 
changes in how federal resources and capabilities are provided. For a 
comparison of applicable guidance, coordinating responsibilities, and 
command and control systems for federal SAR during a catastrophic 
incident versus routine SAR, see the CISAR Addendum to the NSS to the 
IAMSAR Version 3.0, Table 1-4-1.
Remember, the federal resources that actually deploy are probably the 
same you are used to requesting / utilizing as coordinated for by the RCCs.
Typical Process 
for Disaster or 
Emergency
CISAR vs. 
Routine SAR 
comparison

