Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
55 30 October 2014
Search Theory
Finding the target is the ultimate objective and how searchers define 
success. Search planners need to define success ahead of time, to give 
them something to base option comparisons on (how and where to search). 
Being able to compare options against a consistent measure allows the 
planner to determine which option is best, and to look at the search to see 
how well they are doing by determining how high the measure gets. 
Finding search subjects quickly saves lives, reduces search costs, and 
minimizes risk to searchers.
There are two primary elements of a successful search. You must:
• Look in the right place; and
• Be able to detect what it is you are looking for.
Therefore you must consider two related probabilities when determining 
the likelihood a search will be successful:
• Probability the search object is where you are looking; and
• Probability you can detect the search object if it is there.
Search theory is the study of mathematical methods for determining 
optimal search plans. In other words, how to most effectively employ 
limited resources when trying to find an object whose location is not 
precisely known. The goal is to maximize the chances of finding the 
object of the search in the minimum amount of time using available 
resources. Use of search theory shows the planner where to place 
available resources so the chances of finding the object in the minimum
time are maximized.
During World War II, the destruction of US ships by enemy submarines 
brought a new focus to thinking about search. Serious scientific thought, 
effort, and scrutiny were brought to bear on the problem of using limited 
resources efficiently to find and track enemy submarines with reasonable 
certainty: the beginnings of search theory.
What is search 
theory?
Defining 
Success
Elements of a 
successful 
search
History of 
search theory

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
56 30 October 2014
Search Theory 
The seminal elements of search theory were developed by the US Navy 
Antisubmarine Warfare Operations Research Groups (ASWORG), later 
known as the Operations Evaluations Group (OEG). Since the research 
was initially classified, continued research was delayed until the 1950’s 
and 1960’s. From there two branches appeared, each concentrating on one 
of the two key features required to produce a coherent search solution: 
where to search and how to search.
The “where to search” branch continued mainly as academically-oriented 
research into the theory of search, often developing elegant mathematical 
solutions to maximize the likelihood one would be searching in the right 
place to find at target under a given set of conditions and assumptions. 
Some research also developed algorithms designed to allocate search 
effort, again under a given set of conditions and assumptions.
More recently, attempts have been made to classify the types of missing 
persons (children, hunters, Alzheimer’s patients, etc.), how they act, and 
where they are likely to go relative to some last known position.
For missing aircraft, historical studies have been conducted trying to 
establish where aircraft are found relative to their expected routes of flight.
Often, however, much of the determination of where to search is based on 
a combination of local knowledge, experience, and intuition.
The “how to search” branch tended to focus on implementation: 
experimental determination of how well sensors (often the human eye) 
could detect targets in a given environment, crafting search tactics to 
achieve the goals of the academic research noted above, and turning 
theory into practice. Such experimentation is costly in terms of time, 
manpower, equipment use, and dollars. Thus, it was generally only 
conducted by, or through contracts for, the US Coast Guard or US Navy. 
Both had funding and responsibility for the success of searches in the 
water.
However, there are some useful data and techniques for estimating the 
likelihood of detecting a search target in the wilderness, which will be 
presented in later lessons.
Where to 
Search
How to Search
History of 
search theory

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
57 30 October 2014
Search Theory
Search theory studies how to find an object whose location is not precisely 
known. Handling uncertainties requires the use of probability. Bernard 
Koopman addresses the need for and use of probability in search in Search 
and Screening, 1980:
• Every operation involved in search is beset with uncertainties: it can 
be understood quantitatively only in terms of the concepts and laws of 
the scientific theory of probability…(not readily accepted by searchers 
due to) the simple nature of most of the earlier operations of search, 
the short ranges involved, and the power of the human eye at such 
ranges. These factors made a “deterministic” approximation 
satisfactory: “When a thing is there and I look at it without anything 
in front of it, I see it; otherwise I don’t.” Approximations of this sort 
are still useful, but they must be validated by more realistic analysis, 
based on probability, among other things. (Koopman, p. 17);
• “Probability”, as applied in common parlance to a surmise, indicates a 
perception of “likelihood,” “reasonability to suppose,” “chance of 
being true,” and appears in a host of similar expressions. … It always 
contains the implication that some knowledge exists bearing on the 
surmise, but not enough to determine its truth or falsity. Thus it is 
perfectly consistent for its “probability” to change as this body of 
knowledge changes, and for different people possessed of different 
knowledge to appraise it differently. … the concept of probability is 
used or implied in most practical decisions in daily life. (Koopman, 
p.277);
• Before a search is undertaken, e.g., in its planning phase, assumptions 
are always made, often implicitly; concerning the probable positions of 
the object of search…Such assumptions acquire a precise form in 
terms of the probability distribution of the target before the search (its
a priori distribution). …the concept of a probability distribution is a 
perfectly precise one and is a necessary basis of any logical deduction. 
(Koopman, pp. 17-18).
Uncertainty and 
Probability –
B.O. Koopman

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
58 30 October 2014
Interrelated Elements of Optimal Search Problem
B.O. Koopman defined the elements of the basic problem of optimal 
search:
• A priori probability density distribution on search object location (so 
the probability of containment, POC, for any subset of the possibility 
area can be estimated)
• A detection function relating search effort density (or coverage, C) and 
the probability of detecting the object if it is in the searched area 
(POD)
• A constrained amount of search effort
• An optimization criterion of maximizing probability of finding the 
object (probability of success or POS) subject to the constraint on 
search effort
These elements allow investigation of the optimal search problem: finding, 
for the limited amount of available search effort, the allocation (time, 
place, and amount) over that portion of the search area that maximizes the 
probability of finding the search object (probability of success). The 
solution to this problem tells the search planner the sub-area(s) where 
search effort should be placed and how much effort should be placed in 
each.
For years searchers have been taught variations of the following tools for 
deciding where to put their limited number of searchers and for 
determining how well the search has been conducted:
• Where the missing person is most likely located (high POC)
• Where that likelihood is most densely concentrated (high POC per 
square foot, or high probability density (Pden))
• How likely you are to detect the object (POD)
• Intuition
Koopman shows these are important parts of the problem but are not 
sufficient for good decision making.
Essential 
Elements of an 
Optimal Search 
Problem
Decision Tools 
of the Past

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
59 30 October 2014
Interrelated Elements of Optimal Search Problem
Koopman notes the requirement for a detection function allowing 
determination of POD. But, is concentrating on high POD enough?
Imagine walking along a street one night and seeing a slightly drunk 
person on his hands and knees searching for his keys under a street light. 
After helping search for several minutes, you ask “I don’t see any keys 
here. Where exactly did you drop them?” “Over there,” he replies, 
pointing to a dark area across the street. “Well, then why are you looking 
over here?!” “Because this is where the light is.” He replies.
Our drunk can search all night under the light, and he will not find his 
keys; he is looking in the wrong place. This vignette illustrates that high 
probability of detection (POD) does not equal success unless you are 
looking in the right place (and not even always then).
Koopman also requires a probability density function, allowing for POC. 
Imaging you know with certainty the missing person is in the Great 
Smoky Mountains National Park. How well can your 100 member search 
team search those 800 square miles of forest? How likely are you to 
detect and actually find the missing person?
High POC (right place) does not equal success, unless your searchers are 
able to detect the target.
Of course, none of the above matters if you have enough searchers to 
effectively search the entire search area in sufficient detail to find the 
search object. Do you ever have enough trained searchers? So reality 
validates Koopmans’ third element; a constrained amount of search effort.
The fourth element of Optimal Search Problem is an optimization 
function; something you will try to maximize. Probability of Success 
(POS) is what is maximized for optimal search. To find what you are 
searching for, you should craft a plan which yields a high POS. Achieving 
a high POS requires balancing the need to search where the target is 
against the need to search in enough detail to detect the target if it is where 
you are searching.
High Probability 
of Detection 
(POD)
High Probability 
of Containment 
(POC)
Limited 
Resources 
(Searchers)
Optimization 
Function

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
60 30 October 2014
The Goal of Search Planning
“Balance? What balance? We’ll just hit our high POC regions in a way 
that generates high POD…that should do it!” Searching is not so simple. 
Recall the two primary elements of a successful search: you must look in 
the right place and be able to detect what it is you are looking for. 
Probability of Containment (POC) and Probability of Detection 
(POD) are inversely related. The actions you can take to improve POD 
very often decrease the POC for the search; high POD implies 
concentrating limited resources in a smaller area and decreases the 
chances what you are looking for is actually in the smaller area. High 
POD by itself does not guarantee success because what you are searching 
for must be in the physical area you are searching. 
Conversely, things you can change to increase POC searched often 
decrease POD. A high POC with limited search resources implies 
spreading resources out across a larger area, which decreases the chances 
of detecting the search object. High POC does not guarantee success, 
because you must also be able to detect the search object. 
An optimal search plan must balance the requirement to look in the right 
place against the requirement to look in enough detail to detect the object 
of search. The goal is to get the best mix of POC and POD in order to 
maximize the chances of finding the search object; the Probability of 
Success (POS). Finding the optimum balance (and maximum POS) 
requires the use of mathematics.
Balance 
Interrelated 
Elements

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
61 30 October 2014
The Goal of Search Planning
The goal of search planning is to deploy the available search resources in a 
manner that increases the chances of locating the object of search at the 
maximum rate. This minimizes the mean time required to find the object 
of search. Since searching involves uncertainty (you don’t know where 
the search object is), a search plan must be developed that will handle the 
uncertainties optimally. 
A search plan at a minimum consists of: the location and dimensions of 
the search area and search sub-areas, the assignment of available Search 
and Rescue Units (SRUs) or resources to their corresponding sub-areas 
along with track spacing (and search altitude for aircraft). When planning 
a search, one is always concerned with obtaining the “best” plan or the 
optimal plan. In a SAR context, a plan is considered optimal if it 
maximizes the Probability of Success (POS). Two quantities must be 
considered: The Probability of Containment (POC, also known as 
Probability of Area) which is the likelihood that the search object is 
contained within the boundaries of some area; and, the Probability of 
Detection (POD) which is the probability of detecting the search object (as 
a function of the effort expended in that area) given that the search object 
is in the area searched.
The interrelated elements can be written mathematically:
𝑷𝑶𝑺 = 𝑷𝑶𝑪 𝒙 𝑷𝑶𝑫
While the equation is deceptively simple, search planners must take care 
to consider the effects of operational considerations, available resource 
distribution, time, effort, etc. to craft search plans. Balance is the key. 
Remember why you are taking this course: you are the person 
responsible for planning and/or guiding a search. You are NOT here as 
a searcher. Search leaders/planners and searchers have very different roles 
in a search, different sets of information requirements, and two very 
different mindsets. Both are important, but they are different.
The searcher’s role is to search: go where they are told, search how they 
are told, and report back what they found.
The planner’s role is to plan: to craft a search plan that makes the best use 
of the available searchers. “Best use” implies generating the highest 
likelihood of success, of finding the target, no matter the nature of the 
target.
Planning vs.
Searching
The Goal of
Search 
Planning…
Bayes Theorem 
solved for 
Search 
Planning

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
62 30 October 2014
The Goal of Search Planning
For searchers, search probability is binary: they either find the target or 
they did not find the target. 100% success or 0% success.
For planners, search planning involves managing the uncertainties 
inherent in the search, represented as probabilities:
• The uncertainty of the location of the target: if you knew where the 
missing person/aircraft/vehicle was, there would be no search; and
• The uncertainty of detection: in reality, searchers do not always see 
everything within sight.
