Lesson 7
OVERDUE AIRCRAFT INCIDENTS
An important search step, before and after committing search resources, is 
actively investigating to confirm distress/non-arrival and to determine and 
narrow the search area. Purposeful investigative actions must be taken 
and the results evaluated in order to increase your search effectiveness.
After completing this lesson, you should be able to:
• SUMMARIZE the steps, timing, and actions taken by the FAA to 
locate overdue aircraft.
The following references were used to construct this lesson:
1. Federal Aviation Administration. (Mar 2013). Order 7110.10, Chapter 
8 (Search and Rescue).
2. National Aeronautics and Space Administration. (1990). NASA 
Contractor Report 4330, Current Emergency Locator Transmitter 
(ELT) Deficiencies and Potential Improvements Utilizing TSO-C91a 
ELTs.
3. National Search and Rescue Committee. (May 2000). National SAR 
Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual.
4. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to National SAR Supplement. 
5. Federal Aviation Administration. (2006). FAA Air Circular 
AC150/5190-7.
This lesson presents several considerations for missing aircraft searches 
including; FAA and AFRCC PRECOM and EXCOM procedures, radar 
data, and airspace restrictions. It explains the role of the FAA in searches 
for overdue aircraft and describes the investigative actions taken before 
you are called on to search (as well as investigative actions that continue 
during the search).
