Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
64 30 October 2014
Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) Responsibilities
The FAA is responsible for:
• Assuring that SAR procedures will be initiated if an aircraft becomes 
overdue or unreported; 
• Attempting to locate overdue or unreported aircraft by information 
request (INREQ) and alert notice (ALNOT) communications search;
• Cooperating in the physical search by making all possible facilities 
available for use by the searching agencies.
The FAA defines an aircraft “overdue” based on type of flight plan aircraft 
is operating under and the time elapsed from the Estimated Time of 
Arrival (ETA).
(NSS LA pp 4-9 thru 4-10)
Flight plans is specified information, relating to the intended flight of an 
aircraft, that is filed orally or in writing with an air traffic control facility. 
Flight plans include basic information such as:
• Route info: departure / arrival points and estimated time en route,
• Alternate airports (in case of bad weather),
• Type of flight rules (instrument or visual flight rules),
• Information on the pilot and the number of people on board, and 
• Capabilities and configuration of the aircraft.
To fly under Instrument Flight Rules (IFR), the FAA mandates:
• Pilots be trained, certified and current for IFR flight; 
• Aircraft be equipped and certified for IFR flight; and
• Pilots follow specific IFR procedures during flight.
An IFR flight is similar to a business trip: other people know about it, and 
it has a well planned itinerary from which deviations must have FAA 
approval.
IFR overdue policy. An aircraft on an IFR flight plan is considered 
overdue when neither communications nor radar contact can be 
established and 30 minutes have passed since its expected time of arrival 
over a specified or compulsory reporting point or at a clearance limit. The 
30 minute window allows for minor route and speed deviations, as well as
a reasonable time after landing for the pilot to contact the FAA.
Flight Plans
IFR Flight Plan
FAA Authority & 
“Overdue” 
Definition

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
65 30 October 2014
Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) Responsibilities
The FAA requirements for aircraft and pilots flying under Visual Flight 
Rules (VFR) are not as stringent as IFR. A VFR flight is similar to a trip
to Grandma’s house: somewhat planned, deviations in route and timing 
are likely, and people notice your untimely absence but not quickly.
VFR overdue policy. An aircraft on a VFR flight plan is considered 
overdue 30 minutes after estimated time of arrival to the destination.
• Why only to final destination? There are no requirements for the pilot 
to report deviations, intermediate landings, etc.
Aircraft operating under visual flight rules are not required to file a flight 
plan; most general aviation (GA) aircraft flight do not file a flight plan. 
These flights are similar to a Sunday drive: no pre-identified plan or
route, no declared time schedule, no official notifications, and no one 
tracking your arrival or departure.
“No flight plan” overdue policy. An aircraft not on a filed flight plan is 
considered overdue at the actual time a reliable source (e.g., family or 
friends) reports it to be at least one hour late at its destination.
• Why one hour? Likelihood of deviations en route, destination, time.
The FAA provides services to airmen through two main facilities. An 
Automated Flight Service Station (AFSS) is an air traffic facility that 
provides en route communications and VFR SAR services, assists lost 
aircraft in emergency situations, and originates Notices to Airmen.
The AFSS is a central point for collecting and disseminating info on 
overdue or missing aircraft not on an IFR flight Plan.
An Air Route Traffic Control Center (ARTCC) is an FAA facility 
providing air traffic control services principally during en route flight to 
aircraft operating on IFR flight plans within controlled airspace.
ARTCCs are central points for collecting information, coordinating with 
RCCs, and conducting communications search by distributing alert 
notices.
A fixed-base operator (FBO) is a commercial business granted the right by 
the airport sponsor to operate on an airport and provide aeronautical 
services such as fueling, hangaring, tie-down and parking, aircraft rental, 
aircraft maintenance, flight instruction, etc. 
FBOs are not a segment of the FAA’s ATS system. However, FBOs are 
valuable sources of information concerning overdue aircraft.
