Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
66 30 October 2014
FAA Policy for Overdue Aircraft
If the aircraft has not been located within 30 minutes after the FAA 
classifies it as overdue, an Information Request (INREQ) message is 
transmitted to the departure facility, all military bases of operation 
(BASOPS), and all FSSs and ARTCCs along the route.
• Emergency Phase: Uncertainty
• Investigation Search: Preliminary Communications (PRECOM)
• Area to be investigated: Check all airports and facilities along the 
filed or suspected route of flight that could accommodate the aircraft.
If the replies to the INREQ are negative, or if the aircraft is not located 
within 1 hour after transmission of the INREQ, whichever occurs first, an 
Alert Notice (ALNOT) will be transmitted to the FAA Regional Office 
and those facilities within the search area. The search area is normally 
that area extending 50 miles on either side of the proposed route of flight 
from the last reported position to the destination. The search area may be 
expanded to the maximum range of the aircraft at the request of the RCC 
or by the ALNOT originator.
• Emergency Phase: Alert
• Investigation Search: Extended communication and record search
• Area to be investigated: Check airports and facilities within 50 miles 
on either side of the filed or suspected route of flight
When the RCC receives either a COSPAS-SARSAT distress beacon alert 
message and/or an audible beacon notification (airborne or ground), the 
RCC investigation should be expanded as necessary to aggressively 
pursue the cause of each alert and dispatch SAR resource(s) to assist.
When a distress beacon location correlates to the route of flight of a 
missing aircraft, the RCC will advise the FAA.
Uncertainty 
Phase: 
Information 
Request
Alert Phase: 
Alert Notice
Distress 
Beacon Alerts

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
67 30 October 2014
FAA Policy for Overdue Aircraft
If the extended communication and record search fails to locate the 
aircraft, or if one (1) hour has elapsed since the ALNOT transmission, 
whichever occurs first, the ALNOT originator (the FAA ATC facility) will 
notify the RCC.
Only an RCC can initiate the start of the Distress Phase. The RCC will 
accomplish this by opening an active mission and coordinating for SAR 
capabilities and operations.
• Time:
• A distress situation is confirmed;
• Investigation fails to confirm non-distress no later than two (2) 
hours after the ALNOT transmission;
• One or more distress beacon notifications correlate to the filed or 
suspected route of flight; or
• Radio or radar coverage drops off in an area of known radio or 
radar coverage.
• Emergency Phase: Distress Phase
• Investigation Search: Continue EXCOM actions, ALNOT remains 
open until RCC either suspends or closes the SAR mission
• Area to be investigated: Based on the search area developed by the 
SMC or IC.
Upon opening a SAR mission, the RCC should:
• Review the lead and supporting SMC responsibilities;
• Alert the appropriate State SAR authority(s) and other responsible 
agencies per the Federal-State agreement,
• Coordinate use of any Federal SAR assets such as DoD, CAP, Coast 
Guard, or ICE facilities,
• Coordinate Federal non-aircraft capabilities
