Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
69 30 October 2014
Coordinating for Airspace
The primary purpose of the Air Traffic Control (ATC) system is to prevent 
a collision between aircraft operating in the system and to organize and 
expedite the flow of traffic. Pilots comply with very strict FAA general 
operating and flight rules, including the FAA’s important “see and avoid” 
mandate. In support of your SAR operations, you should be able to:
• Recognize the type(s) of airspace in which your SAR operations are 
being conducted
• Know how to establish a Temporary Flight Restriction supporting your 
SAR operations
• Deconflict airspace operations over your search area
FAA air traffic control services are provided to pilots flying in controlled 
airspace (A, B, C, D and E). There are various minimum weather, pilot 
certifications, and aircraft equipment requirements for operating in these 
types of airspace.
In uncontrolled airspace (G), ATC has no authority or responsibility to 
control air traffic. Pilots should remember there are visual flight rules 
(VFR) and weather minimums to obey.
Special use airspace or special area of operation (SAO) is the designation 
for airspace in which certain activities must be confined, or where 
limitations may be imposed on aircraft operations that are not part of those 
activities. The special use airspace depicted on aeronautical charts 
includes the area name or number, effective altitude, time and weather 
conditions of operation, the controlling agency, and the chart panel 
location. 
Examples include Prohibited Areas, Restricted Areas, Warning Areas 
Military Operating Areas (MOAs), and Alert Areas.
“Other airspace areas” is a general term referring to the majority of the 
remaining airspace. These airspace areas may or may not be depicted on 
aeronautical charts. 
Examples include Military Training Routes (MTRs), Parachute Jump 
Aircraft Operations areas, published VFR routes, Terminal Radar Service 
Ares (TRSAs) and National Security Areas.
