Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
70 30 October 2014
Coordinating for Airspace
The safe conduct of aircraft conducting SAR operations is a major concern 
to the SMC. If no airspace reservations are provided, SAR aircraft are 
responsible for complying with all FAA and ICAO requirements. 
During large-scale searches, the SMC normally obtains a SAR airspace 
reservation from ATC. When ATC facilities are unable to provide airspace 
reservation for search aircraft, the SMC and OSC will normally provide 
safety and alerting services. All aircraft within the area will maintain their 
own VFR separation.
How can you deconflict flying activities in your search area?
• Coordinate with the local ARTCC / FSS. Ensure your activities are 
communicated.
• Coordinate with all aircraft in the search area. Ensure both lateral 
boundaries and altitude restrictions are understood.
Coordinate with the OSC / IC. Ensure the utilized airspace meets the 
needs of the search plan.
Temporary Flight Restrictions (TFRs) are tools used by the FAA to 
restrict aircraft operations within designated areas. Historically, TFRs 
have been used by air traffic management as a means of separating “nonparticipating” aircraft from those engaged in certain activities, such as 
firefighting, rescue, and law enforcement operations. A TFR can be 
established for any SAR incident (air or maritime).
TFRs are designated to:
• Protect persons and property from a hazard when the presence of lowflying aircraft might increase the danger.
• Provide a safe environment for the operation of disaster relief aircraft.
• Prevent an unsafe congestion of sightseeing aircraft above an incident 
or event that may generate a high degree of public interest.
You may someday have a need to establish a Temporary Flight Restriction
to minimize interference during search & rescue flight operations (e.g. 
high media interest).
Generally, a TFR will only be approved for a small area (5 nm radius, 
below 2000’ AGL).
Temporary 
Flight 
Restrictions
Airspace Deconfliction

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
71 30 October 2014
Coordinating for Airspace
An FAA Air Traffic Control (ATC) facility is designated in the TFR 
NOTAM as the Coordination Facility. The Coordination Facility serves as 
the coordination and communication focal between the SAR incident 
response and the aviation community. Find the controlling ATC facility:
• identified on the back of the VFR Sectional legend; or
• using agencies listed in FLIP AP/1B Area Planning.
Typically the FAA Coordination Facility is the ARTCC or TRACON 
which controls the airspace that contains the TFR. When the TFR is close 
to an airport with an air traffic control tower, the air traffic control tower 
may be designated as the FAA Coordination Facility.
• Determine if flight operations are planned in any areas or on any 
routes that might conflict with the search operation, 
• Get any required approvals to search in special use airspace areas,
• Request the controlling/using agencies close sections of their airspace 
or routes,
• At a minimum, set up a procedure to de-conflict (perhaps by time or 
altitude) the search flights from the special use operations,
• Coordinate to build a Special Use Airspace NOTAM,
• When operations are complete, be sure to de-alert all agencies 
involved, including canceling the NOTAM through the ATC.
A Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) will be issued by the FAA ATC facility to 
inform the flying public about a TFR. The NOTAM will begin with the 
phrase “FLIGHT RESTRICTIONS” followed by the location of the 
temporary restriction, effective time period, area defined in statute miles, 
and altitudes affected. The NOTAM will also contain the FAA 
coordination facility and telephone number, the reason for the restriction, 
and any other information deemed appropriate. Pilots are required to 
check NOTAMs as part of flight planning.
• Further information on procedures for establishing a TFR can be found 
in the National SAR Supplement, Appendix C.
How To Get 
Airspace

