Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
74 30 October 2014
Exercise on Clues
This lesson concentrates on what searchers should be aware of so they will 
be able to complete the process of detection. As discussed in later lessons, 
the searcher focus is quite different from the planner focus on the clues to 
design the search plan around. Even if resources are spaced based on the 
likelihood of finding a large target, the searchers must be aware of and 
alert to the many other possible smaller clues available to them on scene.
There is a big difference between planning a search specifically to find 
small clues and being ready to detect small clues (clue aware).
This lesson concentrates on physical, on-scene clues and your 
responsibility to educate the searchers on what to look for and how to 
search for that evidence. Off-scene clues are equally important sources of 
information that must be treated with the same caution and evaluation as 
on-scene clues. 
Describe, sketch, and share with the students near you … what does 
an overdue aircraft look like?
Descriptions Sketches
