Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
75 30 October 2014
Searching for Clues
What are your searchers looking for?
• The aircraft – the target or object of the search, or 
• Evidence that could help narrow the search area and indicate the 
direction follow-on searches should take.
It is important to not only search for the missing aircraft, but also for clues 
related to the missing aircraft. There are five categories of clues:
• Physical (metal, aircraft, debris)
• Recorded (flight plan)
• People (eyewitness, family, friends, point last seen)
• Event (flare, fire, signal)
• Analytical (from reasoning)
Some clues are transient in nature (footprints, smoke, flares, etc.). Some 
clues are found through investigative methods off site (intended route of 
flight, flying habits, etc.).
It is easy to be led astray by expectations or “finding what you’re 
searching for.” The error, here, is in searching only for what you expect to 
find based on what you think happened. While investigating the clues that 
fit into your scenario do not neglect the remaining portion of the search 
area or route of flight. You must continue to search the entire route of 
flight based on the multiple scenarios of what may have happened to the 
aircraft. By limiting your search to one specific area based on 
expectations could result in disaster. This is usually a subconscious act 
since people rarely decide consciously to ignore clues, however the effect 
can still be disastrous. 
Consider the following search problem. Notice that answers are only 
provided to the questions asked:
• An aircraft is overdue on a long, three-leg flight. No one has reported 
seeing it at “B” or “C” so the team believes it is most likely on the “AB” leg and solicits (through media interviews and such) leads between 
“A” and “B.” Of course, that’s where all of the clues led investigators: 
they got what they asked for but didn’t find the aircraft that crashed 
just short of “C.”
CAUTION! 
