Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
77 30 October 2014
Physiology and Psychology of Detection
…as many as it takes to find the missing aircraft.
The investigation should continue until the target is found. The 
investigation must also include all of the reasonably possible scenarios.
What pictures do the clues paint of the incident?
• Could these pictures be wrong or misleading?
Is it a single picture or has it several possibilities (scenarios)?
• Do the negative clues support the same picture?
• Are there other reasonable pictures (scenarios) you’ve not yet 
investigated?
Do some of the clues not fit the picture? Are they red herrings, or how 
would the picture (scenario) have to change for them to fit?
Sensation, perception, and detection are not the same things:
• Sensation is when the eyes receive enough light energy to be 
stimulated,
• Perception requires the brain to organize the light image,
• Detection implies recognition of the object as something requiring 
further investigation: identification. In SAR it must take place under 
marginal conditions in the field.
Images courtesy of Dave Landrigan at the University of Massachusetts Lowell, 
“http://dragon.uml.edu/psych/organize.html”
You can readily see (sense) the blobs above. It takes time for your brain 
to organize the blobs into recognizable words. It takes even more time to 
determine if the words you think you see are really what the images are 
conveying to you – as it would to determine if the object a searcher sees 
and recognizes in the field is related to the missing person or aircraft.
As Many As It 
Takes
Evaluate Clues 
as a Group
Detection of 
Clues

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
78 30 October 2014
Physiology and Psychology of Detection
An illustration of how the brain tries to make sense of what the eye sees:
• Have you ever noticed, for example, when you approach the dinner 
table that the shapes of the plates do not change? When you look at 
them from some distance away from the table, the shapes of the round 
plates are elliptical on your retina. The only time that the image of a 
round plate is approximately round on your retina is when you look at 
it straight on.
• Yet your brain tells you they are always circular – you see what you 
expect to see – just like in the field on a SAR.
To delay, not prevent detection.
• People can detect nearly anything if they look at it long enough.
• Camouflage requires the brain to take time to work harder with the 
expectation that the observer will have shifted his/her view before the 
mental process of detection is completed.
A good set of mental pictures (expected images) can speed up the brain’s 
work sifting through the visual clutter.
One common view of the brain is as a pattern fitter. Thus, a purpose of 
the brain is to remove the need for further thought by fitting what you are 
experiencing into a previously held pattern. Then, you can act out of habit 
and avoid actively thinking about what you are doing, seeing, or 
experiencing.
Take the Kanizsa figure above, for example. Most people will “see” the 
complete edges of the triangle, even though they are not defined or drawn 
beyond the corner notches (or Pac-men).
Searching, your brain will likewise complete the pictures of what your 
eyes take in, absorbing the collage of reality and trying to fit it to a 
previously recognized pattern. How many clues will you miss?
Shape 
Constancy
Camouflage
Pattern 
Recognition
