Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
79 30 October 2014
Physiology and Psychology of Detection
Once you have them, they tend to stay with you. For instance, with the
two common examples of illusions below, you might have difficulty 
seeing both of the women’s faces (ex.1) or both the vase and the faces 
(ex.2). Yet, once your brain spends the time to organize the images and 
build the appropriate mental pictures, you will likely be able to see which 
ever you desire without difficulty or time delays.
So it is in the field: good mental pictures allow your brain to recognize 
and detect images more quickly; hopefully before your eyes have moved 
on to other images.
• If you couldn’t think of what to write for any of your “what does an 
overdue aircraft look like” descriptions, perhaps the descriptions won’t 
be sufficient to build good mental pictures in the minds of the 
searchers.
Images courtesy of Dave Landrigan at the University of 
Massachusetts Lowell, “http://dragon.uml.edu/psych”
