Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
80 30 October 2014
Interviewing for Clues
The purpose of communication is to get your message across to others 
clearly and unambiguously. Doing this involves effort from both the 
sender of the message and the receiver. And it’s a process that can be 
fraught with error, with messages often misinterpreted by the recipient. 
When this isn’t detected, it can cause tremendous confusion, wasted effort 
and missed opportunity.
The three ways messages are communicated:
• Verbal – the words we choose
• Paraverbal – how we say the words
• Nonverbal – our body language
During your interviews, the words you use and the way you say them are 
critical to the success of the interview.
There are inhibitors or barriers that can affect your message:
• Interrupting – This is the result of undeveloped active listening skills. 
A common example of this is not allowing the sender to complete their 
sentences because you have a preconceived idea of what they are 
going to say.
• Lack of confidence – This is normally the result of insufficient 
training or lack of experience, but may include some personal issues. 
Two common results of a lack of confidence include reluctance to
make a decision and a failure to act.
• Environmental conditions – These are physical factors that could 
impact the ability to effectively deliver a message, such as poor 
weather conditions, noise, condition of the platform, etc.
• Emotional responses – Emotional responses are most frequently 
caused by personal or professional influences as a result of stress. 
Many factors could trigger an emotional response, including verbal 
abuse, physical assault, vulgarities, lack of confidence, or a lack of 
patience. Emotional responses are undesirable, unprofessional, and 
are not acceptable.
• Anger/frustration – Anger and frustration can result from nearly any 
type of stimulus. It may manifest itself in the form of emotional 
responses, an overbearing attitude, or cause an intense amount of 
stress. If unmanaged, anger and frustration can quickly lead to an 
inappropriate outburst or emotional shut down (flight or fight).
Communication 
Skills
Barriers

