82 30 October 2014
Lesson 9
RESOURCES AND PROCESSES
SAR leaders must identify the resources available for use in the search 
area, coordinate their use to provide the most appropriate and capable 
response to a SAR mission, and employ them to the best advantage. It is 
important that search leaders and planners be familiar with the operational 
capabilities of all air based search and rescue units (SRU) in their area.
After determining where to search, the search leader must decide how to 
search. A major part of the “how” is in assigning the search resources into 
safe, easy to follow, effective search patterns that produce the best chances 
of finding the search object.
After completing this lesson, you should be able to:
• UNDERSTAND the interrelationships between scenarios, clues, 
search areas, search vehicles, and detectors,
• Be MOTIVATED to REVIEW local pre-plans, SEARCH OUT all 
resources available in the area, and TRAIN WITH those resources to 
learn about their capabilities and limitations,
• SELECT the best search pattern or combination of patterns to use for 
the particular incident and circumstances,
• DISCUSS the interrelated factors affecting search pattern choice.
The following references were used to construct this lesson:
1. National Search and Rescue Committee. (May 2000). National SAR 
Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual. Para 1.18, G-18, Chapter 2, and 
Appendix H.
2. IMO & ICAO. (2013). IAMSAR Manual, Vol II. Chapter 2, Chapter 5,
and Appendix G
3. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to National SAR Supplement. 
4. LaValla, et al. (1999). Search is an Emergency. 95-108. Downloaded 
from http://www.eri-intl.com
