Considerations for Selecting Resources
This lesson will introduce you to some of the types of SRUs you might 
have available and some of the information you may need to acquire about 
those SRUs. It is designed to help you consider the “who, what, where, 
when, and why” of the incident to select the “best” search tactics to use as 
the mission progresses and to recognize the interrelated nature of the 
factors that affect your tactic selections.
Consider how each resource is best employed:
• When during the search effort: early, late, throughout?
• In what role? (Active or passive search, support, …)
• In what environment and conditions: weather, light, terrain, 
vegetation, accessibility, distance, location, altitudes, …?
• In groups or individually?
• In conjunction with other resources or separately?
• In a structured pattern, in general areas, randomly?
• For which types of search objects or targets?
• In which types and sizes of search areas?
• What affects their abilities and usefulness?
• Range, speed, visibility, …
• Availability, response time, …
• How does the search urgency affect your choices?
• What limitations make it less than perfect for you?
