Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
89 30 October 2014
Lesson 10
PROBABILITY OF CONTAINMENT FOR AIR SEARCH
This lesson introduces a method to establish a reasonable search area and 
calculate Probability of Containment (POC) values for a missing aircraft 
search. This method utilizes historical (statistical) data collected for a 
study correlating planned route of flight and crash locations.
After completing this lesson, students should:
• INTERPRET statistical information for aircraft crash locations 
collected in the 2009 NASA World Wind SAR Visualization Program
study
• EVALUATE and APPLY the statistical information to establish an 
appropriate search area
• CALCULATE the Probability of Containment (POC) for a search 
area or portion of a search area, using the NASA study statistics
• UNDERSTAND the usefulness and limitations of current missing 
aircraft location statistics and be motivated to collect data on crash 
locations within their area of responsibility.
The following references were used to construct the lesson:
1. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to National SAR Supplement. Chapter 5
2. “Data Collection and Analysis for NASA World Wind Search and 
Rescue Visualization Program”, National Aeronautics and Space 
Administration (NASA) Search and Rescue (SAR) Office, 
Goddard Space Flight Center, study by Robert J. Koester of dbS 
Productions LLC, February 2009. Statistical tables by Robert J. 
Koester.
A 2009 NASA study examined missing aircraft incidents and the 
relationship between the planned route of flight and the location of aircraft 
wreckage. Students are shown how to use data from the NASA study to 
craft a search area and calculate POC for the search area; and how to 
calculate POC when searching only a portion of the search area.
