Objectives
References 
Overview

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
90 30 October 2014
NASA SAR Visualization Program Study Overview
NASA published the “Data Collection and Analysis for NASA World 
Wind Search and Rescue Visualization Program” study in February 2009. 
The purpose of this work was to perform data acquisition and analysis that 
aids in the development of an improved search management tool that 
blends results from an analysis of statistically significant past search data 
with aircraft radar track, terrain, and weather information. 
One task was to determine the radar track offset based upon radar 
information versus route information. The study was also tasked to 
examine the distance traveled from the last recorded radar position. The 
results of this portion of the study are called the Air Search Area 
Definition (ASAD).
Missing aircraft searches account for a small percentage of SAR missions;
however, they account for a disproportionately larger expenditure of 
resources and funds. The challenge of finding a missing aircraft is 
immense, especially when a distress signal or other location data has not 
been received. One of the most powerful tools to assist search managers 
and planners focus search efforts is radar track data collected by the 
Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) and Department of Defense 
(DoD) radars. Radar data can help generate “areas of highest probability 
density” where missing aircraft may have crashed. However, radar data 
may not be available for every missing aircraft search.
Search mission managers and planners need advanced methods for 
determining “areas of highest probability density” for where missing 
aircraft may have crashed. Identification of high probability density areas 
helps search managers concentrate search assets and efforts in areas with 
high likelihood of containing the search object, thereby minimizing the 
time to search and potentially saving more lives.
Goal of the 
NASA 
Study
Why use 
historical data 
to focus search 
efforts?

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
91 30 October 2014
NASA SAR Visualization Program Study Overview
Route offset” and “along the route” crash location data are two statistics 
used to help define values for Probability of Containment (POC). If radar 
data is unavailable these statistics are often the only meaningful way to 
limit the size of the search area. 
Two studies have been conducted previously which examined route offset 
and along route crash location percentages:
• Canadian New Two Area Method (NTAM) in 1987, examining 68 
incidents; and
• Study published in 2000, examining 62 search incidents in the U.S. 
during 1999 using data from the AFRCC (Desmarais, John).
This NASA study examined data for 238 incidents. The results for the 
2009 NASA study generally fell between the results of the two earlier 
studies. 
The median (or 50%) of the aircraft were found within 4.5 nm (nautical 
miles) offset of the planned route and within the first 63% of the aircraft’s 
intended route length. Area One under the NTAM and CAP system is 
defined by a 10 nm box around the entire intended route. The NTAM 
study suggested 79% of aircraft are found within this area, the CAP study 
suggested 63%, and the NASA study found 68% found within this area. 
The NASA study did differ from previous studies in finding that 95% of 
aircraft were found within 30 nm of the intended route. There are no 
significant differences for percentage of route between all three studies.
For all three studies, type of aircraft, type of flight plan, and terrain appear 
to be important factors affecting where aircraft were found. The most
significant factor was type of flight plan. None of the studies were able 
to provide useful statistical data for cases where the intended route is not 
known or when the intended route only consists of departing and returning 
to the same airfield. Additional studies are required for these instances.
NASA Study 
Findings

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
92 30 October 2014
Using NASA statistical data
This NASA study data is most likely to be useful in developing a 
reasonable search area during the early stages of a missing aircraft search. 
Search managers and planners can use the NASA study data to help 
determine where to search, even when radar data is sparse, non-existent, 
or not yet available. Use NASA data when all four of the following have 
been determined:
• A missing or overdue aircraft
• A point of origin or Last Known Point (LKP)
• An intended or expected route of flight
• A destination, distinct from the origin or LKP
The NASA Study notes that additional work needs to be done to provide 
useful statistics when the route is not known or the route only consists of 
taking off and landing at the same airfield.
Using the NASA Study data allows you to get your search started based 
on a meaningful search area while marshalling investigators, gathering 
radar data and other clues, and working toward a consensus based area 
search plan. The NASA Study data is not fine enough to stand alone as a 
firm basis for detailed decisions on which parts of the search area to 
search, but is useful for setting an initial search area based on where most 
missing aircraft are found.
Probability of Offset (PO) is the probability that the aircraft is within a 
given distance (equally left and right) from the centerline of the intended 
route of flight. 
Probability Along Track (PT) is the probability that the aircraft is between 
the LKP and a point (as a percentage of intended route length) along the 
route of flight. The data is presented as a cumulative probability from the 
LKP:
• Example: For a 60 nm expected route of flight (LKP to intended 
destination), PT to a point 45 nm along the route would be the PT
for 75% of the route, since the 45 nm point is 75% of the distance 
from LKP to the intended destination (45 / 60 = .75 or 75%)
• For a 100 nm expected route of flight (LKP to intended 
destination), PT to a point 45 nm along the route would be the PT 
for 45% of the route, since the 45 nm point is 45% of the distance 
from LKP to the intended destination (45 / 100 = .45 or 45%).
Probability of 
Offset (PO)
Probability 
