Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
94 30 October 2014
Using NASA statistical data
POC is calculated by multiplying the probability of offset by the 
probability along track, or:
POC = Probability of Offset (PO) 𝑥 Probability Along Track (PT)
Or
POC = PO 𝑥 PT
To calculate Probability of Containment for a search area based on a 
known LKP, route of flight, and destination using NASA study data
provided in “Probability of Offset and Probability Along Track” tables in 
Appendix A:
1. Select correct table based on type of flight for missing aircraft: All 
Flight Types, IFR, or VFR.
2. Determine Probability of Offset (PO) value for distance offset from 
track to be searched. Values are based on equal likelihood missing 
aircraft is left or right of track.
3. Determine Probability Along Track (PT) value based on percentage 
of planned route to be searched. Percentages begin at LKP and 
increase toward intended destination i.e. first 10% of route, first 
20% of route, etc.
4. Multiply the value for PO times PT to calculate POC.
When calculating POC for an intended search area, the search area has 
been extended 10 nm prior to the LKP and 10 nm after the intended 
destination. Searching this additional area is included because data from 
all three studies indicate a more the trivial likelihood the missing aircraft 
could be located in this area. Both studies prior to the NASA study 
recommend adding these extensions as part of the search area.
Using “All Flight Types” table in Appendix A, calculate POC for the 
following search areas: 1) Entire route of flight with 5 miles offset; 2)
Entire route of flight with 10 miles offset; and 3) Entire route of flight 
with 15 miles offset.
