Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
95 30 October 2014
Using NASA statistical data
The NASA Study data is most useful as a means to get a search started 
while additional information needed to work on a consensus-based area 
search plan is being gathered. NASA Study data should be considered for 
crafting a reasonable search area either following or during common hasty 
search actions such as detailed ramp checks, electronic searches, hasty
route search, etc.
The NASA Study data is not fine enough to stand as a firm basis for 
detailed decisions on which parts of the search area to search. However it 
is useful for setting an initial area based on where most aircraft are found.
• Using a 10-mile offset ASAD box for all flight types contained 
67.7% of the aircraft found in the NASA study – good odds in a 
relatively small area. For IFR flights 73.9% found, for VFR flights 
63.8% found in the 10-mile offset ASAD box.
The NASA Study data works with very small numbers in many portions of 
a search area. The method can provide a good estimate of POC during the 
initial phases of a search, but should be superseded by a consensus-based 
POC as investigation to include radar forensics finds information relevant 
to the specific pilot, flying the specific flight, in the specific environment, 
on the specific day.
Some additional considerations:
• In most cases, the 5-mile offset yields the highest Probability of 
Success (POS);
• If you are searching for a survivor who can signal you, you may be 
able to effectively search a much larger area (NTAM instructs 
search managers to search “Area One” (10 NM offset) first)
• There may be weather, operational, investigative, or other reasons 
to not use NASA statistics
Use of radar data is extremely valuable in limiting the search and 
prioritizing locations to search. This NASA study also determined: 
• The median (or 50%) of all crash sites are located within 0.8 
nautical miles of the last radar plot.
• The median (or 50%) of all aircraft were found within 0.4 nm of 
the last projected heading (given the last two radar plots).
Additional 
Considerations
Considerations 
for using NASA 
Study data

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
96 30 October 2014
Using NASA statistical data
Analysis of the NASA data provides some interesting points to consider:
• In probability along track, the first 10% and the last 10% of the 
track (along with the data before the LKP and after the destination) 
contains 41% of the probability
• Jets and single engine aircraft had a larger offset and have 
accidents during the early portions of the route
• IFR aircraft offset was the smallest, and 26% of the crashes were 
found within 5 miles offset in the last 10% of the route (plus the 
data just beyond destination).
• For “All Flight Types”, a search area 10-mile offset for just the 
first 10% and last 10% of route (plus extension before LKP/after 
destination) contained 27.1% of located aircraft. Increasing to last 
20% of route increases the number to 33.8% of the located aircraft.
• For “VFR flight”, a search area with 10-mile offset for first 10% 
and last 10% of route (plus extensions) contained 19.7% of located 
aircraft. Increasing to last 20% of route increases the number to 
27.6%.
• For “IFR flight”, a search area with 10-mile offset for first 10% 
and last 10% plus extensions contained 43.2% of located aircraft. 
Expanding to include the last 20% of route increases the number to 
47.5% of located aircraft.
Other findings 
of the study

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
97 30 October 2014
Limitations of the NASA World Wind study
The data in the NASA study was reported in large “chunks”:
• Data determined in 5 nm increments for offset i.e. 0-5 nm, 5-10nm, 
10-15nm, etc.)
• Data determined in 10% increments along track i.e. 0-10%, 10-
20%, 20-30%, etc.)
The data provided in this student guide is NOT the same. Data has been 
interpolated linearly between the study cells. Interpolation of the data 
allows calculation of POC estimates for regions of virtually any size, but 
they are estimates with assumptions of constancy and linearity not 
established in the actual study report.
This study is based on historical data on where aircraft were found in the 
past. The pilot/aircraft you will search for is NOT in the database, so by 
using NASA data you are assuming your pilot acted in a manner similar to 
those in the study.
The crash site data may have a bias since cases where the crash site was 
not found are not included. Also, incidents in which the aircraft landed at 
an improved runway (regardless of distress or non-distress) were 
excluded. Incidents with conflicting information which could not be 
reconciled were also excluded.
This NASA study is a statistical analysis of crash site position relative to 
intended track. Therefore, it is meant to apply in cases when there is little 
else to go on other than an LKP and a destination. Any additional 
information on a particular search should be used by the planner to modify 
the search areas or create new one.
The study assumes no knowledge of the purpose of the flight, pilot habits 
or intentions, weather, or other factors that might affect where the pilot 
would fly, how the pilot would deviate from his or her original plan, or 
what might cause and emergency landing. Such information should be 
used to establish a Subjective/Deductive Search Area and move beyond 
NASA statistical data to developing a consensus-based POC.
With little information and a search to conduct, these statistics give the 
planner a tool to formulate a logical search area. As more information is 
gathered, the search may move beyond this NASA study statistics.
