Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
98 30 October 2014
Calculating POC for a Sub-Area
A statistical-based search area entailing search of the missing aircraft’s 
entire route from LKP to destination, plus extensions before LKP and after 
destination with 10 miles offset left/right of track generates a .677 (67.7%) 
POC for all flight types, .739 (73.9%) POC for IFR flights, and .638 
(63.8%) POC for VFR flights. Search areas often must be subdivided into 
sub-areas for jurisdictional considerations, physical boundaries or features, 
large changes in terrain and vegetation, etc. POC from statistical data can 
help planners determine which sub-areas to search first, how to distribute 
limited search resources, and where to expand searching as additional 
resources become available.
To calculate POC using NASA statistics for a sub-area (or segment) which 
1) is only a portion of intended route of flight, 2) does not include the LKP 
or destination, and/or 3) extends out to unequal distances offset on each 
side of track centerline (or both sides of search sub-area are on one side of 
centerline):
Step Action
1 Define the sub-area/segment boundaries along the aircraft intended/expected track.
2 Measure the left and right offset distances (distance from track center line to left and 
right edges of the region, working from LKP toward destination).
3 Using “Probability of Offset” column in tables for the correct flight type, determine 
POFFSET for the left and right offsets and divide each number by 2 (remember, data 
provided in tables assumes both sides of centerline with equal likelihood on either side).
4 If the two sides of the sub-area or segment are on the same side of track centerline, 
subtract PO NEAR SIDE from PO FAR SIDE to calculate POFFSET:
PO SUB-AREA = PO FAR SIDE – PO NEAR SIDE.
If the two sides of the sub-area or segment are on opposite sides of track centerline, add 
PO LEFT SIDE and PO RIGHT SIDE to calculate POFFSET; 
PO SUB-AREA = PO LEFT SIDE + PO RIGHT SIDE.
5 Measure the distance from the LKP to the search sub-area or segment start point and 
distance from LKP to search sub-area or segment end point in nautical miles (nm).
6 Divide the start and end point distances from the LKP by the entire length of the intended 
route of flight. Numeric result should be a decimal. Multiply decimal numbers by 100 to 
calculate percentage along intended track for sub-area/segment start and end points.
7 Using the percentage numbers from step 6, use “Probability Along Track” column in 
tables for correct flight type to read the PT END and PT START values.
8 Calculate PTRACK. Subtract the PT START for the sub-area/segment start point from the PT 
END for the sub-area/segment end point to yield PT SUB-AREA, the probability along track or 
likelihood the missing aircraft is along the track between the sub-area/segment start and 
end points. PT SUB-AREA = PT END – PT START
9 Calculate POC for the sub-area or segment; multiply the probability of offset (step 4) 
times the probability along track (step 8) to yield the POC for that sub-area. 
POCSUB-AREA = PO SUB-AREA x P T SUB-AREA
