Calculating POC for a Sub-Area
The following is an example of calculating POCSUB-AREA for a search subarea. Sub-area begins 100 nm along intended track from LKP and ends 
150 nm along intended track from LKP. The length of intended route of 
flight from LKP to destination is 250 nm. Intended search sub-area
extends to 8 nm offset left of intended track and 3 nm offset right of 
intended track.
The following is an example of calculating POCSUB-AREA for a search subarea. The sub-area begins 100 nm along intended track from LKP and 
ends 150 nm along intended track from LKP. The length of intended route 
of flight from LKP to destination is 250 nm (the same as in example 1). 
Intended search sub-area is limited to the left side of the centerline of the 
intended route of flight, extending from 3 nm offset left of intended track 
to 8 nm offset left of intended track (i.e. the first 3 miles left offset from 
centerline will not be searched and no searching right of centerline).
Example 1
PT SUB-AREA = PT END - PT START = .487 - .375 = .112
PO SUB-AREA = PO LEFT SIDE +/- PO RIGHT SIDE = .312 + .206 = .518 
(add PO values when sub-area sides are on opposite sides of centerline, 
subtract when on same side of centerline)
POCSUB-AREA = PO SUB-AREA x PT SUB-AREA = .518 x .112 = .058 or 5.8%
Example 2
PT SUB-AREA = PT END - PT START = .487 - .375 = .112
PO SUB-AREA = PO LEFT SIDE +/- PO RIGHT SIDE = .312 - .206 = .106
(add PO values when sub-area sides are on opposite sides of centerline, 
subtract when on same side of centerline)
POCSUB-AREA = PO SUB-AREA x PT SUB-AREA = .106 x .112 = .012 or 1.2%

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
100 30 October 2014
Summary
This NASA statistical data may be most useful to the search planner 
during the initial stage of planning a missing aircraft search. Planning 
searches based on historical data (for example, extending from 10 miles 
prior to the LKP to 10 miles after the destination, out to 10 nm offset both 
sides of intended route) may be useful after the hasty search is complete 
and no clues (or limited clues) are found. NASA data may also assist the 
planner when no radar track information is available, or only limited radar 
track information is available. 
This NASA study provides a tool to create a quick and easy search area 
based on historical data; this data can assist planners in determining where 
to search. The use of NASA data also allows the planner to make 
predictions regarding the likelihood of a find (Probability of Success) for a 
variety of search effort allocation options; and select the option with the 
best overall effect.
Investigative efforts should have begun either before or shortly after 
notification of a missing/overdue aircraft. As the investigation and 
searching continues, additional information and clues should become 
available to the search planner which will help focus the search area and 
possible scenarios for what happened. As specific information for a search 
becomes available, searching may include spot searches to investigate 
clues, emergency locator transmitter signals, possible wreckage sightings, 
etc. As additional information becomes available search area and POC 
values will be determined using a consensus process (rather than the 
NASA data). Consensus will be covered in a later lesson.
