Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
101 1 Nov 2016
Lesson 11
PROBABILITY OF DETECTION FOR AIR SEARCH
Search managers and planners must decide how to use available search 
resources and effort to the best effect in the search area. Two important 
considerations in assigning limited resources are: 1) the amount of 
physical area the resources can search; and 2) the likely results of the 
searching or how likely searchers are to find the search object if it is in the 
area searched. Planners need to understand and apply the concepts of 
“searchable area” and “probability of detection” to make optimum 
progress toward the desired outcome; a successful search.
After completing this lesson, students should:
• RECOGNIZE factors that affect searcher’s ability to detect search 
objects
• Be MOTIVATED to survey their areas of search responsibility to 
identify variables which will affect detection during searches
• ESTIMATE the resources, time, and spacing required to search a 
given search area;
• ESTIMATE the size of search area that can be searched in a given 
amount of time by the available search resources
• DISCUSS and EVALUATE the trade-offs that must be considered in 
developing search action plans (confinement versus active searching, 
area covered versus quality of coverage, etc)
• DETERMINE the area that can be searched, search parameters 
(search speed, spacing, altitude, etc.), and the expected probability of 
detection
The following references were used to construct the lesson:
1. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to the National SAR Supplement. Chapter 5.
2. IMO & ICAO. (2013). IAMSAR Manual, Vol. II. Section 4.6 and 5.10.
3. Frost, J.R. (1999). Principles of Search Theory, Part I and II.
Response, 17, 1-15.
4. National Search and Rescue Committee. (May 2000). National SAR 
Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual. Chapter 5. 
Introduction 
Objectives
References 

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
102 1 Nov 2016
A Mathematical Model for SAR Resources
This lesson introduces a means of estimating how much physical area can 
be searched with a limited number of search resources, or the concept of 
searchable area. Students will also see how the same tool can help
estimate factors such as track spacing required, resources needed, and time 
to search. We will then examine Probability of Detection (POD), how 
search planners can estimate POD, and how POD is affected by resource 
allocation choices made by search planners. 
As a philosophical note, Probability of Detection as presented is useful for 
search planners, not searchers. The search planner’s job is to craft the best 
possible search plan, one that makes the best use of available search 
resources and effort. The searchers job is to execute the plan. Search 
resources must search as though their assigned search segment is the only 
one that matters. Probabilities are and should be meaningless to searchers; 
some planners withhold this data from searchers. Consider the possible 
effect on searchers’ mental state and consequent searching if they are told 
their search segment only has a very small chance of containing the search 
object, or there is only a very small likelihood of being able to detect the 
search object in the search segment.
One of Koopman’s four inter-related elements of a search is the limited 
resources typically apportioned for a search. Since the goal of search 
planning is to maximize the chances of finding the search object in the 
minimal amount of time, we must be able to mathematically relate the 
apportioned SAR resources to the search area.
The size of a physical area which can be searched is a function of speed, 
spacing, time, and number of SRUs available. The size of the area can be 
estimated for any SRU that searches in roughly straight, parallel tracks 
with a generic equation:
𝑨𝒓𝒆𝒂 (𝑨) = 𝑽 𝒙 𝑺 𝒙 𝑻 𝒙 𝑵
“A” is the area to be searched.
“V” is the speed of the SRU while searching. IAMSAR Manual charts are 
calculated using 90 kts speed for the search aircraft.
“S” is track spacing; the distance between legs of the search pattern (or 
between SRU tracks if more than one in the search segment).
“N” is the number of resources of the same type. For example, the 
number of light aircraft sorties at the same search speed for the same 
length of time. For multi-period searches, the number of resources may 
more accurately mean the number of sorties.
Overview
Mathematically 
Modeling SAR 
Resources

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
103 1 Nov 2016
Mathematically Modeling SAR Resources
“T” is time during a search period spent actively advancing the search 
pattern; this quantity of time does not include the time required to start, 
taxi and takeoff (STTO), to fly enroute to/from the search area, etc. This 
value of time must also discount time spent maneuvering and investigating 
sightings during the active search.
Calculate each of the following, and chose the limiting value for time:
• T = Time on Search Pattern = Fuel Endurance x 0.85
o Multiplying Time in Segment by 0.85 to correct for fuel 
consumed outside of the search area during maneuvering or 
repositioning.
• T = Time on Search Pattern = Daylight available x 0.85
o Multiplying available daylight by 0.85 allows for daylight time 
lost while aircraft is maneuvering or repositioning and not 
actively searching.
• T = Time on Search Pattern = Observer Endurance x 0.85
o Multiplying Time in Search Segment by 0.85 allows for time 
lost on search pattern while scanner/observers are taking 
breaks/resting their eyes. If scanners/observers will take breaks 
when the aircraft is maneuvering and turning to align with track 
legs, there is no requirement to make this adjustment.
Solve the formula for “S” to calculate the track spacing required to 
complete a search of a desired area with a given number of SRUs 
searching for a given time at a given search speed. Required track spacing 
should be provided to the SRUs, and will be used when calculating 
Coverage (C) and Probability of Detection (POD).
