Manipulating the formula A=VxSxTxN is a tool to help the search planner 
estimate resources needed, time needed to search, track spacing, and area 
that can be searched with a given number of resources. The equations are 
based on the physical size (area) of a search area, and do not account for 
the dimensions of the search area. The results of calculations do not 
necessarily indicate the plan can be accomplished, so the planner must
check for reasonableness.
For example, one very important check is to determine the number of full, 
complete search tracks.
Partial tracks complicate the search for both planners and searchers. If the 
number of tracks includes a decimal or a fraction, round the number of 
tracks to an appropriate whole number of tracks; the number of full tracks
the SRU can complete. DO NOT round up the number of search 
tracks for aircraft without checking with the air branch or aircrew to 
ensure the search aircraft and aircrew have the capability to search 
for the extra time required through rounding up.
The number of tracks (or legs) an SRU must make to complete an 
assignment is calculated with the following formulas:
𝐿𝑒𝑔 𝐿𝑒𝑛𝑔𝑡ℎ = 𝑆𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑐ℎ 𝑎𝑟𝑒𝑎 𝑙𝑒𝑛𝑔𝑡ℎ
𝑁
𝑁𝑢𝑚𝑏𝑒𝑟 𝑜𝑓 𝑇𝑟𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑠 = 𝑉 𝑥 𝑇
𝐿𝑒𝑔 𝐿𝑒𝑛𝑔𝑡ℎ
After rounding the number of tracks off to a whole number, the planner 
must adjust the time required for the SRU to complete the task. Adjust the 
time required by solving for Time (T):
𝑇𝑖𝑚𝑒 (𝑇) = 𝑇𝑟𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑠 𝑥 𝐿𝑒𝑔 𝐿𝑒𝑛𝑔𝑡ℎ
𝑉
After adjusting the Time Required (T), correct the Track Spacing 
Required (S) using the new value for Time Required.
