4. Since search aircraft do not plan to fly a partial number of tracks, 
calculate the time required for a whole number of tracks:
• Time test up: (round up 3.9 tracks to 4.0 tracks):
𝑇𝑖𝑚𝑒 (𝑇) = 𝑇𝑟𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑠 𝑥 𝐿𝑒𝑔 𝐿𝑒𝑛𝑔𝑡ℎ
𝑉
= 4 𝑡𝑟𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑠 𝑥 60𝑛𝑚
90𝑘𝑡𝑠 = 2.67ℎ𝑟𝑠
NOTE: 2.67 hrs represents an increase of 4 minutes of search time.
• Time test down: (round down 3.9 tracks to 3.0 tracks)
𝑇𝑖𝑚𝑒 (𝑇) = 𝑇𝑟𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑠 𝑥 𝐿𝑒𝑔 𝐿𝑒𝑛𝑔𝑡ℎ
𝑉
= 3 𝑡𝑟𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑠 𝑥 60𝑛𝑚
90𝑘𝑡𝑠 = 2.00ℎ𝑟𝑠
NOTE: 2.0 hrs represents a decrease of 36 minutes of search time.
Check with the Planning Branch Chief or aircrew to ensure aircraft can 
accommodate an increase of 4 minutes in the search area.
• If yes, fly 4 tracks and use T=2.67 hours to re-compute area 
searchable (𝐴 = 𝑉𝑥𝑆𝑥𝑇𝑥𝑁).
• If no, fly 3 tracks and use T=2.00 hours to re-compute area 
searchable (𝐴 = 𝑉𝑥𝑆𝑥𝑇𝑥𝑁).
5. Calculate how much area you can search, adjusted for reasonable 
search time (in this example, we select 2.67 hours (from step 3) to 
complete 4 tracks):
𝑆𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑐ℎ𝑎𝑏𝑙𝑒 𝐴𝑟𝑒𝑎 (𝐴) = 𝑉𝑥𝑆𝑥𝑇𝑥𝑁
= 90𝑘𝑡𝑠 𝑥 1𝑛𝑚 𝑥 2.67ℎ𝑟𝑠 𝑥 4 𝑎𝑖𝑟𝑐𝑟𝑎𝑓𝑡
= 961𝑛𝑚2
• This is the size of the area you can search with 4 aircraft using 1 
nm track spacing and 2.67 hours searching per aircraft. This is 
approximately 20 percent of the desired search area.
