Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
108 1 Nov 2016
Probability of Detection (POD)
The example above uses mathematics to understand how limited resources 
impact our search options. Now the question a search planner must ask is 
“How well can these resources search?”
Recall the two primary elements of a successful search: you must search 
where the search object is located and you must be able to detect the 
search object given you are searching in the right location. The lesson on 
Probability of Containment provides a methodology for identifying likely 
locations; but how do you determine how well the searchers are able to 
detect the search object? Probability of Detection is the answer.
The IAMSAR Manual glossary defines Probability of Detection as:
“The probability of the search object being detected, assuming it was in 
the areas that were searched. POD is a function of coverage factor, 
sensor, search conditions and the accuracy with which the search facility 
navigates its assigned search pattern. POD measures sensor effectiveness 
under the prevailing search conditions.”
For a search, POD answers the question “If the search object is/was in the 
searched area at the time of the search, what is/was the probability of 
detecting it?”
Koopman noted that POD is a function of the amount of search effort
expended in that search area, the size of the area covered, and search 
object “detectability”. Some of his most important work was defining 
these three functions and their relationship to POD.
Effort is the total distance traveled by searchers while searching in their 
portion of the search area. Since distance is the product of the speed of the 
searcher and the time spent in the search area, the formula for effort becomes:
𝐸𝑓𝑓𝑜𝑟𝑡 (𝑧) = 𝑆𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑐ℎ 𝑆𝑝𝑒𝑒𝑑 𝑥 𝑇𝑖𝑚𝑒 𝑡𝑜 𝑆𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑐ℎ 𝑥 #𝑆𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑐ℎ𝑒𝑟𝑠
= 𝑉 𝑥 𝑇 𝑥 𝑁
Area covered is defined as the size of the physical area over which the 
searching effort is approximately uniformly spread.
