Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
109 1 Nov 2016
Probability of Detection (POD)
Detectability is a state of how easy or hard it will be to detect a particular 
object with a particular type of resource (sensor) in a particular 
environment. 
Detection by any sensor is affected by three classes of factors:
• Search object. Size, color, contrast to surroundings, etc.
• Environmental conditions. Terrain, amount of ground cover, lighting, 
visibility/weather, etc.
• Searcher/sensor. Type, search speed, training/experience, fatigue, etc.
The ease or difficulty of detecting the search object is measured by a 
quantity called “Effective Sweep Width”.
Effect Sweep Width (or just Sweep Width) is a measure of the effectiveness 
with which a particular sensor can detect a particular object under 
specific environmental conditions. The quantity is an objective measure 
of how easy or difficult it is to detect a specific search object in a specific 
environment with a specific sensor.
It is important to understand that Effective Sweep Width (or Sweep 
Width) recognizes the likelihood of not detecting objects near to the 
sensor, along with the likelihood of detecting objects at a longer range 
from the sensor. Sweep Width does not indicate the maximum distance at 
which an object might be detected, nor that an object would assuredly be 
detected within a range. NOTE: It is possible to detect a search object 
at distances greater than the Effective Sweep Width (W)!
Effective Sweep Width can only be determined through experimentation,
during which the number of detections and extinctions (misses) are 
counted for a large number of sensors (searchers) at a wide variety of 
distances from objects.
When a sensor is tested in a variety of environments, tables and correction 
factors can be constructed to make sweep width more widely applicable. 
The US Coast Guard has performed extensive experimentation during air 
searches on the visual detection for large aircraft (above 12,500 lbs), small 
aircraft (below 12,500 lbs), vehicles and people. The resulting Sweep 
Width tables can be found in the IAMSAR Manual, Vol II, Appendix N.
For instructions on calculating Sweep Width using the IAMSAR Manual 
charts, see Appendix B in this Student Guide; or, refer to the example 
problem on page 113.
Effective Sweep 
Width
Determining 
Effective Sweep 
Width
Detectability

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
110 1 Nov 2016
Probability of Detection (POD)
By itself, Effective Sweep Width is of little interest to the searcher, for it 
does not tell how far away a sensor should be able to detect a search 
object. However, Sweep Width does allow for comparison of the 
effectiveness of different sensors against different targets in different 
environments. Remember, Effective Sweep Width is a function of the 
search object, the sensor, and the environment.
POD is a predictive tool useful when planning a search period by:
• Quantitatively relating the ability of tasked SRUs to search the search 
area
• Determining the effort required to search the search area
POD is a retrospective tool useful for analyzing the search by:
• Measuring the effectiveness of individual searches and the progress of 
the overall search effort
• Determining when to re-search or when to refocus the search effort 
into additional areas
Sweep Width is a vital element for determining how well an area is 
searched. It is a factor of Coverage, which in turn allows determination of 
Probability of Detection for a given search sensor or team in a given 
search segment. Effective Sweep Width is the key to improved search 
planning and execution because it allows search planners to objectively 
relate POD to Effort expenditure, and improves effort allocation through 
the use of proven techniques.
Coverage is a measure of search quality or effectiveness. It relates 
searcher capability with searcher employment to determine how well the 
search area has been covered. Coverage can be thought of as a measure of 
how much search effort is expended per unit of area, or “effort density”.
When calculating Coverage for air searches, we assume parallel sweep 
search patterns:
𝐶𝑜𝑣𝑒𝑟𝑎𝑔𝑒 (𝐶) = 𝑆𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑐ℎ𝑒𝑟 𝐶𝑎𝑝𝑎𝑏𝑖𝑙𝑖𝑡𝑦
𝑆𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑐ℎ𝑒𝑟 𝐸𝑚𝑝𝑙𝑜𝑦𝑚𝑒𝑛𝑡 = 𝑆𝑤𝑒𝑒𝑝 𝑊𝑖𝑑𝑡ℎ (𝑊)
𝑇𝑟𝑎𝑐𝑘 𝑆𝑝𝑎𝑐𝑖𝑛𝑔 (𝑆)
• Sweep Width is a measure of how well a sensor should perform, 
without regard to how it is actually employed. If a sensor is used 
differently on two different searches, the detection results should also 
be different.
• Coverage factor is the result of comparing how a sensor should 
perform generically with how it is employed on a specific search.
Use of Effective 
Sweep Width
Coverage

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
111 1 Nov 2016
Probability of Detection (POD)
Coverage may be thought of as “effort density” or how much searching 
effort is expended per unit of area in a given locale. The search planner 
can control and make decisions about how the available search resources 
are assigned and used. The search planner decides how much of the 
available effort should be allocated to each section of the search area.
• Coverage of one (C = 1.0) indicates no overlap of gaps between 
the sensor capability and the track spacing employment. Coverage 
less than one indicates gaps between detection capability; coverage 
greater than one indicates overlap in detection capability.
• There is a direct relationship between effort and coverage: 
Doubling the coverage factor of a search segment requires 
doubling the effort assigned to that search segment
• Any increase in POD requires an increase in coverage with a 
corresponding increase in effort
For a given level of available search effort, larger areas or more search 
segments can be searched with a lower coverage, smaller areas or fewer 
search segments can be searched with higher coverage, or a “mixed bag” 
approach can be used where some search segments receive high coverage, 
some a moderate coverage, some a low coverage and some segments may 
not be searched at all. 
Koopman postulated that the exponential detection function best 
represented the random detection profile of a search pattern. “Random” in 
this context contains the restriction that the effort be uniformly distributed 
over the area being searched. The relationship between Coverage (C) and 
POD is depicted in the chart on page 116, and in the following equation:
𝑃𝑟𝑜𝑏𝑎𝑏𝑖𝑙𝑖𝑡𝑦 𝑜𝑓 𝐷𝑒𝑡𝑒𝑐𝑡𝑖𝑜𝑛 (𝑃𝑂𝐷) = 1 − 𝑒−𝐶
In this equation, “e” is the base of the natural logarithms (approximately 
2.718282) and “C” is the coverage factor.
Some subjects (like hikers) may move considerably from the Initial 
Planning Point. Provided the subject can be contained, this can be 
beneficial as it increases the relative speed between subject and searcher. 
When using the exponential detection function, assume that the motion of 
the target of your search:
• Is independent of the searcher
• Is not specifically directed towards escaping/eluding detection
This means that this curve should not be used to estimate POD when 
searching for persons like runaways or persons evading capture from law 
enforcement. The function is still appropriate for non-responsive persons 
such as autistic children, persons with dementia, despondent persons, etc.
Calculating 
Probability of 
Detection
Impact of 
Coverage

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
112 1 Nov 2016
Probability of Detection
Properties of the exponential detection curve include:
• The shape of the detection profile does not affect POD
• Perfectly straight, equally spaced, parallel tracks are not required.
• When splitting a given amount of effort into two parts and then 
performing two searches, the cumulative POD is the same as doing a 
single search with all effort
Bottom line, all detection profiles (all searches, no matter how variable or 
random) perform equally (at the same coverage) when significant random 
variations in the search parameters occur —as long as Effort is uniformly 
spread over the search area. 
POD is affected by many variables as already discussed. Effective Sweep 
Width (W) attempts to account for factors which affect how well a sensor 
(usually the human eye for aircraft search) can detect a given target in a 
given environment. Coverage factor (C) measures the effectiveness or 
quality of search by accounting for the assigned track spacing. POD can 
then by determined directly from the Coverage factor.
