Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
122 30 October 2014
Aircraft Allocation Using ASAD
Choose to allocate search segments to SRUs based on the relative 
proportions of mileage each SRU will contribute to the search.
Step Action
1 Determine how far each aircraft can fly on the search pattern 
(velocity x search endurance) 
[Remember, if endurance is based on fuel or daylight, search endurance is 
only 85% of the time the aircraft can stay in the search area, after subtracting 
the time to fly to/from the search area. This may or may not be a factor if 
time on the search pattern is limited by the scanners/observers.]
2 Sum the results of Step 1 to determine total miles.
3 Divide each aircraft’s mileage by the total mileage: yields the 
percent of the total each aircraft contributes.
4 Multiply each aircraft’s percent contribution by the search area 
length (route + 20): yields the amount of the search length each 
aircraft should be assigned.
Note: yields the same results as the previous example when time on the 
search pattern is controlled by the effective time of the scanners/observers 
or daylight i.e. when all aircraft are assigned the same amount of time on 
the search pattern.
Advantages:
• Fairly quick/easy to calculate and assign search aircraft;
• All aircraft use the same track spacing for equivalent POD;
• Takes advantage of full capability of search aircraft.
Disadvantages:
• Same as previous example except accounts for SRU differences.
