Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
123 30 October 2014
Air Effort Allocation (ASAD) Worksheet
The “Keep it Simple” methods just discussed do not address many 
questions the search planner needs to answer. Consider:
• How much offset from route centerline should you search?
• What track spacing should be flown?
• What POD will or should be achieved?
• What POS is expected?
• When should the search be widened?
The Air Effort Allocation (ASAD) Worksheet can help answer those 
questions, as well as allowing a great deal of experimentation to assist 
search planners in examining the effects of effort allocation choices they 
are considering.
Line-by-line instructions for the worksheet are provided in Appendix C of 
this student guide.
Sections A and B of the worksheet merely set up the problem, entering 
what is known about the search area and search resources.
Calculations determine the mileage each search aircraft can contribute, 
their portions of the search area length (segments), and the number of 
tracks they can fly within their segments. Sections A and B do not 
consider width of the search area, POC, or POS.
Section C of the worksheet allows experimentation with varying search 
area widths to allow search planners to examine the trade-offs associated 
with operationally reasonable assignments. For each search area width 
planners are considering, the worksheet will guide them through 
calculating track spacing, POD, POC (based on ASAD) and POS.
The planner may not want or be able to search the entire search area at the 
same time. Section D allows for calculation of ASAD-based POC for any 
subsection of the search area. Section D is also useful when the search 
area is broken up by jurisdictional boundaries, significant sweep width 
changes, or other conditions exist that prevent uniform coverage over the 
entire search area.
