Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
125 30 October 2014
Lesson 13
CLUES, RESOURCES, AND PROCESSES
When asked what they are searching for, searchers often respond with 
answers like “a missing 12-year old boy.” Nearly as often, that is also 
exactly what the searchers have keyed their brains and eyes to find – the 
mental pictures they’ve developed. Unfortunately, missing people 
frequently do not look like a typical person on the street. The search 
object may generate a large number of additional clues that can be easily 
overlooked if the searchers are not consciously looking for them. 
SAR leaders must identify the resources available for use in the area, 
coordinate their use to provide the most appropriate and capable response 
to a SAR mission, and employ them to the best advantage. It is important 
that search leaders and planners be familiar with the operational 
capabilities of all air based search and rescue units (SRU) in their area.
After determining where to search, the search leader must decide how to 
search. A major part of the “how” is in assigning the search resources into 
safe, easy to follow, effective search patterns that produce the best chances 
of finding the search object.
After completing this lesson, you should be able to:
• UNDERSTAND searchers’ needs for good sets of mental images of 
search objectives and be MOTIVATED to BUILD photographic and 
descriptive libraries of the same for local teams,
• Be MOTIVATED to TEACH detection to searchers,
• VALUE the need for continued investigation during any SAR mission 
and CHECK local procedures for how that is ensured.
• UNDERSTAND the interrelationships between scenarios, clues, 
search areas, search vehicles, and detectors,
• Be MOTIVATED to CHECK local pre-plans for completeness, 
SEARCH OUT all resources available in the area, and TRAIN 
WITH those resources to learn about their capabilities and limitations,
• SELECT the best search pattern or combination of patterns to use for 
the particular incident and circumstances,
• DISCUSS the interrelated factors affecting search pattern choice.
Introduction
Objectives

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
126 30 October 2014
Overview
The following references were used to construct this lesson:
1. Koopman, B.O. (1980). Search and Screening: General Principles 
with Historical Applications. Appendix E. Pergamon Press: New 
York. 
2. Kaiser, Peter. The Joy of Visual Perception: A Web Book. Downloaded 
in 2001 from http://www.yorku.ca/eye/
3. Landrigan, David. Illusions Gallery. Downloaded from 
http://dragon.uml.edu/psych/
4. LaValla, et al. (1999). Search is an Emergency. 92-94. Downloaded 
from http://www.eri-intl.com
5. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to National SAR Supplement. Chapter 5.
6. National Search and Rescue Committee. (May 2000). National SAR 
Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual. Para 1.18, G-18, Chapter 2, and 
Appendix H.
7. IMO & ICAO. (2013). IAMSAR Manual, Vol II. Chapter 2, Chapter 5, 
and Appendix G
There is a difference between planning a search specifically to find small 
clues and being ready to detect small clues (clue aware). This lesson 
concentrates on physical, on-scene clues and your responsibility to educate 
the searchers on what to look for and how to search for that evidence. 
Off-scene clues are equally important sources of information that must be 
treated with the same caution and evaluation as on-scene clues. 
This lesson will introduce you to some of the types of SRUs you might 
have available and some of the information you may need to acquire about 
those SRUs. It is designed to help you consider the “who, what, where, 
when, and why” of the incident to select the “best” search tactics to use as 
the mission progresses and to recognize the interrelated nature of the 
factors that affect your tactic selections.
References
Overview

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
127 30 October 2014
Overview of Clues
Describe, sketch, and share with the students near you ….
What does a missing person look like?
Descriptions Sketches
Where, when, and how you search affects which clues you find. Consider:
• A glint from an aircraft windscreen is affected by sun angle, position 
of the searcher, and the direction the searcher is traveling,
• Electronic signals are affected by temperature, terrain, air density,
• Clues may be eroded by wind, rain, snow, and time; or obscured by the
physical environment, lack of contrast, or distance,
• Time of day, season, terrain, wind, and more affect scent clues.
Negative clues:
• If a person had walked through soft soil, you would expect to find 
tracks left behind. If you find no tracks, can you conclude that the 
person did not pass by there? Does this lack of an expected clue help 
you narrow your search area and redirect your resources?
Cautions
Environmental 
Effects on 
Clues

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
128 30 October 2014
Overview of Clues
• Do not follow the advice of some that, given the 100’s of clues a 
person must leave behind by walking through an area, the chances 
of not finding at least one of the clues is so small that the 
probability of detecting at least one is very high. The math behind 
that claim requires independent clues – something that doesn’t 
hold up on a search where each of the target’s footsteps is very 
dependent on the previous footstep.
Clue reliability and value:
• How certain are you the clue was generated by the person you’re 
looking for? If made by someone else, how do you determine 
who?
• What does this clue tell you about the location, condition, and 
intention of the subject? Should it affect your search plan?
Verification - This is particularly important for negative information:
• Who or what else could confirm your information?
• Sources independent of and unrelated to the original source.
• Did the searchers search the area well enough to conclude there are 
indeed no clues there, or should you send in another resource from a 
different angle?
• Family, friends, and witnesses are notorious for providing one-sided 
and incomplete information. How else can you confirm their inputs?
False clues:
• Out of every 100 clues you find on a search mission (either through 
investigation or active searching), how many are false – that is, how 
many do not lead to the search object?
• How do you tell which clues will lead to your objective and which 
won’t?
How many clues do I need and what do I do with them? How can we 
validate or eliminate some of the possibilities?
• If the missing person had done X, then we’d expect to see Y.
• If we don’t see Y, can we conclude the person did NOT do X?
• Could someone else have produced Y? How can we find out?
If a scenario satisfying your set of clues is true,
• What additional evidence would you expect to find that would help 
validate the scenario and focus your search?
If the scenario is not true,
• What clues (positive and negative) could be out there to help us 
discover the true picture and the missing person/object?
Predictive Logic
Cautions

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
129 30 October 2014
Overview of Clues
Continue searching for and collecting clues throughout the search, adding 
new clues to the group and periodically evaluating the pictures they paint 
and the search plan they indicate. Clue awareness is a learned skill, and 
must be practiced in order to develop detection capability with a minimal 
amount of info. Try using pictures to train searchers in clue awareness as 
practiced in class.
Resource considerations --- what makes one the “most appropriate”? 
Includes people, animals, vehicles, and equipment.
Range and endurance:
• Once on-scene, how long before the team needs rest, resupply;
• In an assigned search area, how long/far can the team search?
Transportation requirements:
• Between home and the search base;
• To/From search assignments.
Weather and terrain, including the effects of weather:
• Cold, heat, snow, rain, mud, washed out roads, fire dangers;
• Effects on the searchers, vehicles, sensors;
• Effects on the clues and search area that affect the ability of the 
resources to accomplish their assignments.
