Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
131 30 October 2014
Search Pattern Basics
Objectives come first! Objectives lead to strategies and strategies to 
tactics. Not the other way around.
• The search pattern you choose must support your overall search 
objectives and the tactical objectives of the individual operational 
period.
• The search pattern must be matched with the skills and characteristics 
of the search resource.
However you employ your search resources, all patterns should follow a 
few basic guidelines. Some are to build your confidence in the search 
results; some are to build searcher confidence in you, some are to allow 
you to quickly move into the next operational period.
• Ease of performance – the searchers must be able to search where 
assigned:
• Easy to navigate,
• Simple for searchers to find and stay within their assigned 
boundaries,
• Simple for searchers to stay properly spaced in order to cover their 
area consistently,
• Safe.
• Ease of change:
• Easy to reassign resources based on LKP update or clues,
• Easy to re-search, especially in a way that lets searchers see clues 
from a different perspective (a different spacing, different 
direction, etc.),
• Easy to expand.
• Ease of evaluation:
• Covers the search area in a manner which allows the search leaders 
to determine how well the area was searched.
General
Considerations

