Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
134 31 May 2016
Lesson 14
DEFINING THE SEARCH AREA
This lesson looks at the concept of a “search area”. A search area must be 
determined before the search planner can begin considering how many 
resources are needed or how to allocate available search effort. After the
search area has been determined the search planner can begin to consider 
and plan how to actually search in the search area. This lesson is designed 
to provide students with a means to help determine a search area which is 
likely to contain the search object (person, vehicle, etc.).
After completing this lesson, students should be able to:
• UNDERSTAND the main types of search areas and select the most 
appropriate for their intended purpose;
• ESTABLISH a search area that is highly likely to contain the search 
object;
• ESTABLISH AND UPDATE a LKP based on available information 
and clues;
• EXAMINE AND ASSESS scenarios to describe the range of what 
might have happened and predict where the search object might be 
located;
• IDENTIFY likely routes the search object may have traveled and 
locations within the search area where the search object is likely to be 
found; and
• UNDERSTAND the need to subdivide the search area into Regions
based on the search object and Segments based on search resources.
The following references were used to construct the lesson:
1. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to National SAR Supplement. Chapter 5.
2. National Search and Rescue Committee. (May 2000). National SAR 
Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual. Chapter 5. 
3. IMO & ICAO. (2013). IAMSAR Manual, Vol II. Sec 4.3 and 4.6.
Introduction 
Objectives
References 

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
135 31 May 2016
Search Area
The lesson begins with the concept of search area as defined by the Land 
SAR Addendum to the National SAR Supplement. Three different types 
of search areas and the uses of each for the search planner will be 
discussed. We will consider the importance of Last Known Position 
(LKP), scenario development, and likely routes and locations for the 
search planner when determining search area boundaries. Finally the 
lesson will introduce Regions and Segments as subsections of the search 
area and their use for search planners.
Throughout this student guide, “area” means the measure of a portion of 
ground in square miles, square kilometers, etc. “Search area” means the 
territory or piece of ground, determined by the planner that is to be 
searched. Be as precise as possible when using these two terms to avoid 
confusion or misunderstanding. “Area” with any modifier other than 
“search” is used to mean the measure of the identified territory. For 
example “region area” means the size of a search region.
The Search Area is:
• The territory or piece of ground within which you are essentially 
certain the missing object is currently located;
• The territory or piece of ground beyond which you do not believe 
you must search in the absence of clues leading past the current 
search area boundary; and
• The territory or piece of ground you believe you must search (and 
search well) before being willing to consider suspending the search 
if you do not find the search object.
These characteristics do not mean you may not change the boundaries of 
the search area.
The search area is where you need and plan to search. Without a search 
area, where are you searching and when do you stop? You must carefully 
define and limit the search area while avoiding one which is:
• Too large; may increase the time to locate the search object and 
may cause searchers to be too spread out to find it, or
• Too small; may decrease the likelihood the search object is in the 
search area.
Overview
“Area” and 
“Search Area”
Why Define a 
Search Area?
Search Area 
Character

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
136 31 May 2016
Search Area
“The point where the search object was last seen by a witness, or captured 
on video at a specific time and locations” (NSS Land Addendum, p. xviii, 
Nov. 2011)
“The last substantiated position based on clues or evidence belonging to 
the missing subject and indicating that the missing subject was known to 
be at that location; or, last witnessed, reported or computed position of a 
distressed person or craft.” (NSS Land Addendum, p. xviii, Nov. 2011)
LKP is similar to but more all encompassing than Point Last Seen (PLS), 
which implies a visual sighting.
Without an LKP/PLS you don’t have a search. An LKP/PLS is the 
starting point for determining where to search and the size of the intended 
search area. As with any clue, incorrect LKP or PLS information can lead 
to searching in the wrong place. Check all clues including LKP/PLS for 
reliability and if possible verify by an independent or unrelated source.
The search planner is always working against the clock, but must avoid 
hasty or nervous decisions. While it is possible investigative efforts alone 
(without searching) may eventually shrink a search area down to a very 
small size or even locate the lost or missing person/object, such efforts 
have definite limitations. For example, following the initial report, 
completion of a lost person questionnaire, and some initial investigative 
effort, the flow of new information often slows down considerably. 
Because searching is necessarily performed in a low-data-rate 
environment, it is essential for the search planner to make the best use of 
the information that is available. Even after the search area has been made 
as small as the available information will allow, there still exists 
significant uncertainty about the lost person’s whereabouts. Searching is 
then the best or only alternative for finding the missing person so they can 
be rescued and delivered to a place of safety.
Methods are provided in this lesson for defining and refining the search 
area using:
• The maximum theoretical distance the person or vehicle could 
have moved during the time since last known to be safe;
• Statistics based on studies of lost person behaviors and where 
people were actually found in previous searches; and
• Subjective evaluation and deductive reasoning from the known 
facts and scenario analysis. 
A detailed description of each of these methods can be found in the Land 
SAR Addendum, p5-20 through 5-24.
Defining the 
Search Area
Last Known 
Position (LKP)
Starting Point
Point Last Seen 
(PLS)

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
137 31 May 2016
Search Area
“The area, determined by the search planner, which is to be searched. 
…may be sub-divided into search sub-areas for the purpose of assigning 
specific responsibilities to the available search facilities.” NSS Land SAR 
Addendum, Nov 2011.
On a map, lay out the extent of all the scenarios the planner decides need 
to be followed up with active searching: all the places where the planner 
thinks the search object is reasonably likely to be located. The planner 
will have a line on a map enclosing the territory which encompasses all 
the possible scenarios. The boundaries should be based on the search 
object. The search planner should consider:
• What would have influenced the search object’s decisions?
• What would have directed, restricted, or prevented the person’s 
movements?
• Why would the search object not be likely to have travelled 
beyond a certain distance?
For the search planner, given the clues and information currently 
available, the territory enclosed by the line contains essentially 100% 
POC. In the absence of additional information or clues leading you to 
search beyond the search area boundary, there is no good reason to search 
outside of the search area boundary.
Defining the boundaries of the search area allows you to consider the 
search problem and plan rationally for searching beyond the initial hasty
search response.
Check your boundaries for any evidence of passage that may indicate a 
need to expand or change your search area, and keep checking the 
boundaries throughout the search. Find tactics to prevent the missing 
person from leaving the search area or direct the missing persons toward 
you in the event they make it to your search area boundary. If a person 
has crossed, you have a new clue which could result in a new LKP, 
direction of travel, and a possibly a new search problem. Be willing to 
consider alternative scenarios as more information becomes available, 
then develop action plans to confirm or disprove them as quickly as 
possible. Then take appropriate actions based on the new situation.
THE Search 
Area
“What if I’m 
wrong?”

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
138 31 May 2016
Search Area
You have determined the search area after considering Theoretical, 
Statistical, and Subjective/Deductive Search Areas, but it is still too large 
to search all at once in enough detail to ensure you will find the search 
object with the available search resources. The search object is probably 
not equally likely to be found just anywhere in the search area; some 
portions or spots are more likely than others to contain the search object. 
Where should you search first? You will need to break the search area up 
into smaller pieces to allow determination of where and how to search.
A region is a defined subset of the search area within which there is a 
nearly uniform distribution of the likelihood of containing the search 
object. (NSS Land SAR Addendum., p. 5-10, Nov. 2011) In other words, 
the search object is equally likely to be at any point within a given region.
Regions and region boundaries are based on factors that affect the 
search object, not factors affecting the searchers or how you want to 
search.
Regions form the basis for the initial probability map or picture of where 
search leaders believe the search object is located, which in turn helps 
form the basis for search priorities. Regions will form the basis of the 
planners’ Probability of Containment (POC) calculations. Building 
regions requires the search planners’ to consider each of the viable 
scenarios separately. 
For each scenario:
• Consider all available information and add reasonable assumptions to 
fill in information gaps
• Identify likely routes of travel and likely locations based on that 
scenario
• Put yourself in the place of the missing person. What would he/she 
see, experience, or encounter and how would those things influence 
the missing persons’ choices and location?
• Question: If the search object is not found on the likely routes or at 
likely locations, where would it be?
• Develop reasonable region boundaries based on changes in the 
likelihood the search object is on one side or the other of a region 
boundary. Regions must be fully enclosed by a line completely around 
each region on the map.
Making the 
Search Area 
“Searchable”
Regions
Regions and 
POC

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
139 31 May 2016
Search Area
After considering region boundaries for each of the scenarios, the planner 
must develop a single set of regions for the overall search incident. The 
outermost boundary should be the boundary of the current search area. 
“Stack” the regions for the scenarios to check that region boundaries are 
consistent. Sometimes regions for different scenarios will overlap; 
consider adjusting the region boundaries slightly to line them up and avoid 
very small regions between larger main regions. Some scenarios may 
have regions that do not exist for other scenarios. That just means those 
regions will have a POC value of zero for those other scenarios.
Regions are broken into segments to make the regions (and the search 
area) searchable based on the factors that affect the searchers, not the 
search object. A segment is a delineated portion or subset of the search 
area bounded and sized to be searchable by the assigned SRU.
In contrast to regions of probability, segments are (usually smaller) sub 
divisions of the search area that are based on the logistical and operational 
issues associated with conducting the search itself. Although segments 
have associated POC values by virtue of being a portion of the search area, 
segment boundaries and sizes are not based on concerns about where the 
search object may be located. A segment should be small enough that it 
can be searched by the intended type of resource with a reasonable 
coverage in a specified amount of time. For ground teams, segments 
should be searchable within one “operational period,” including transit 
time to and from the segment plus meal and rest breaks while in the 
segment. 
The purpose of having segments is: first to make operational search 
resource assignments, and, second to evaluate the results achieved by 
those assignments. Good segmentation of a search area can help you:
• Plan and track the effectiveness of search teams in terms of POC, 
POD, and POS
• Assure complete and adequate coverage of the search area
• Employ and manage your resources effectively
• Set tactics that can be accomplished during an operational period
Segments

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
140 31 May 2016
Search Area
Segment characteristics:
• Boundaries clear and easy to find in the field
• No internal barriers such as highways, rivers, chasms, etc., 
(consider making separate segments to deal with these)
• Uniform vegetation and terrain to preclude mental readjustments 
for searchers and to ensure consistent tactics and POD
• Sized to be searchable by the desired resource
• Shaped and oriented to be searchable by the desired resource
Segments should account for any required specialty methods:
• Treat trails, roads, boundaries, and likely routes separately
• Treat unique features (caves, underwater) as separate segments
Segments have associated POC values by virtue of being a portion of the 
search area. Segment POC values are the portion of the Region POC 
contained within that segment. Segment POC values are calculated using 
the ratio of each segment’s area to the area of the region the segment is 
part of, multiplied by the POC value of the region the segment is part of:
𝑃𝑂𝐶𝑆𝑒𝑔𝑚𝑒𝑛𝑡 = 𝐴𝑟𝑒𝑎𝑆𝑒𝑔𝑚𝑒𝑛𝑡 𝑥 𝑃𝑂𝐶𝑅𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑜𝑛
𝐴𝑟𝑒𝑎𝑅𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑜𝑛
For example, if a segment contains one-third of its region’s area, then the 
segment is assigned one-third of the region’s POC.
Segment POC is an essential part of your search plan. In following 
lessons we will see how segment POC can help determine which portions 
of the search area should be searched next and how tracking changes in
segment POC can help show the progress of the search.
Probability Density (pDen) is POC per unit area. By definition, the search 
object is equally likely to be located anywhere within a given region. That 
means the POC per square mile (or per square foot, or per measure of 
area) is constant throughout any region. Each footfall a searcher makes 
within a region is equally likely to step on the search object.
𝑝𝐷𝑒𝑛 = 𝑃𝑂𝐶𝑅𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑜𝑛
𝐴𝑟𝑒𝑎𝑅𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑜𝑛
Probability density provides the means to compare segments for efficient 
allocation of effort. All things being equal, a smaller area is easier to 
search. A smaller area results in a higher probability density.
Segment 
Characteristics
Segment POC
Probability 
Density (pDen)

