Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
142 30 October 2014
Lesson 15
Probability of Containment for Ground Search
As students have seen in the aeronautical search lessons, POC values are a 
required element when trying to determine an optimal search plan. The 
next step after determining a desired search area and making the search 
area “searchable” by subdividing it into regions and segments is to 
determine Probability of Containment values. POC values are determined 
using a consensus process.
Given a SAR case, students will:
• CONSTRUCT, EXAMINE, and ASSESS scenarios to describe the 
range of what may have happened and PREDICT where the search 
object is likely located;
• ESTABLISH a search area and regions within which they are 
essentially certain the search object is located;
• CALCULATE the probability the search object is in each region 
(POC) using consensus and build a probability density map;
• DIVIDE the search area into searchable segments and CALCULATE 
segment POC.
The following references were used to construct the lesson:
1. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to National SAR Supplement. Chapter 5.
2. National Search and Rescue Committee. (May 2000). National SAR 
Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual. Chapter 5. 
3. IMO & ICAO. (2013). IAMSAR Manual, Vol II. Sec 4.3 and 4.6.
Introduction 
References 
Objectives

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
143 30 October 2014
Overview 
This lesson begins with a brief exercise. Students will discuss a range of 
possible scenarios for a notional search case, and then craft a search area 
and regions based on one scenario. Students will be introduced to 
concepts for conducting and using a consensus, and will practice 
conducting a proportional consensus as a class. Students will see how 
consensus results can be used to determine “weights” for possible 
scenarios, and how the consensus process is used to determine POC values 
for search regions and segments.
Exercise
Missing: 9-year old boy dressed in jeans, 
dull green T-shirt, and white tennis shoes.
LKP: Picnic area X at the end of the park 
access road, just after 12:30.
Park boundaries: major roads to west and 
north, high chain-link fence with barbed 
wire at top at forest edge to east and 
residential area to south. 5 mile radius.
Colors:
Light gray: semi-dense hardwood forest 
with light undergrowth and lots of leaves 
on the ground.
White: grassy, open meadow; 2.5’ tall.
Dark: shallow inlet with steep bank.
Other people: 2 families at playground 
(“P”) area at end of other access road.
Time: time now 2:00pm, sunset 6:00pm.
Family search: No clues found at picnic or 
playground, no promises broken, no ideas.
