Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
144 30 October 2014
Developing POC By Consensus
A consensus is a general agreement or judgment arrived at by most of 
those present (Webster’s Dictionary).
A consensus operates on the following principles:
• Several opinions/judgments are better than one when making 
subjective conjectures;
• Experts will make conjectures based upon rational judgment rather 
than merely guessing;
• Experts who can agree on a plan, even though it is not the plan 
they alone would have preferred, are more likely to support it.
During search incidents it is desirable to collect the experience, judgments, 
and expert opinions of search leadership. Advantages include:
• Ensure all important perspectives (including “loyal opposition”) 
are considered and none are lost or ignored;
• Ease the conflicts that can arise over strongly help opinions;
• Build trust and confidence in your plan and leadership team; and
• Design a plan reflecting the participants’ combined expert 
knowledge and intuition.
Consensus is used to obtain input from expert individuals and aggregate 
opposing judgments in order to make more fully informed and considered 
decisions. The consensus process allows the search leadership team 
members to apply their experience, judgment, and knowledge of the 
situation to assign priorities to various parts of the search area. Use of 
consensus should be focused toward building the best (most reasonable) 
plan to find the search object fast.
Use consensus when needed to combine varied opinions and judgments, 
including:
• Developing and weighting scenarios;
• Developing regions;
• Establishing or updating POC;
• Evaluating clues and how they affect the search.
Why Use 
Consensus?
When to Use 
Consensus

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
145 30 October 2014
Proportional Mattson Consensus
The Proportional Mattson Consensus method is a variation of the wellknown Mattson Consensus method, modified to better ensure 
proportionality in the results. The goal is a set of numbers reflecting the 
leadership teams’ combined view of the relative likelihood or preferences
of the available options. Proportionality is key; you must ensure the 
results reflect the proportion, ratio, and relative amount of probability you 
want to assign to various options. For example, your team believes there 
is a 50% probability the missing person followed the creek, a 25% chance 
he followed the trail, and a 12.5% chance he struck out cross-country. 
Always check the results against your judgment.
The steps for conducting a Proportional Mattson Consensus:
Step Action
1 List and discuss (without intent to sway opinion) all of the 
options (these may be scenarios, regions, etc.).
2 Each person (4-6 recommended) individually and privately 
assigns points to each of the options in the following manner:
a Assign 100 points to the most likely option.
b
Assign points to other options in proportion to most likely: 
 1/2 as many points (50) to options that are 1/2 as likely, 
 2/3 as many points (66) to options 2/3 as likely, etc.
c Continue until all options have points assigned.
d Check that points really are assigned proportionally and say 
what you mean.
e Sum the points used on all options.
f Divide the number assigned to each option by the total. This 
is that individual’s result in percent. (Sum should equal 1.0)
3 For each option, sum the individuals’ percent numbers.
4 Divide the option sums by the number of participants.
This is the consensus result/weight in percent. (Sum should equal 1.0)
5 For multiple steps (scenarios and regions), multiply the step 4 
region weight of each region by the step 4 scenario weights.
6 Sum results for a region across all scenarios to yield region POC.
Thanks to Don Cooper, PhD, Chief Deputy, Ohio Department of Commerce, State Fire Marshal’s Office for 
providing this concept, importance, and an example of proportionality (Cooper and Frost, 1999), from which 
the well-known Mattson Consensus method has been modified without introducing additional weighting errors 
or problems with vote inequalities.
Proportional 
Consensus

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
146 30 October 2014
Proportional Mattson Consensus
You can use proportional consensus to combine multiple reasonable 
scenarios into a single integrated search plan in order to concentrate 
efforts to find the search object fast. The results are consensus scenario 
weights.
The following is an example of conducting proportional consensus to 
determine scenario weights. Consider 3 people discussing 4 alternative 
scenarios: 
• The missing person went:
• Downhill;
• Uphill;
• Cross-slope left; or 
• Cross-slope right.
Step Action
1 All 4 scenarios are discussed so the participants know what is meant and included.
2 a-e Each participant assigns points individually.
Down Up Left Right Total
Rick 100 75 25 10 210
Dan 100 50 15 5 170
Mark 75 100 10 10 195
In this case, 
Rick thought it most likely he went downhill, but uphill was also very likely (3/4), left 
was 1/4 as likely (1/3 as likely as up), and right was 1/10th. 
Dan agreed that downhill was most likely but thought uphill was only 1/2 as likely, left 
was a little less than 1/3 as likely as uphill, etc.
Mark thought uphill was most likely, but down was 3/4 as likely, going cross-slope either 
direction was only 1/10th as likely as up and 1/7th as down.
Notice how you can check for proportionality between any of the options to ensure your 
own results are all consistent with each other. For instance, Rick is also saying uphill is 3 
times as likely as left, left is 2.5 times as likely as right, down is 10 times as likely as right 
and 4 times as likely as left, etc. 
Looking at the numbers from both directions in this way can help ensure the numbers really 
are proportionally assigned and reflect what you really mean.
When to Use a 
Proportional 
Consensus
Consensus 
Scenario

