Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
148 30 October 2014
Developing Regions of Uniform Likelihood
Recall a search region is a subset of the search area within which there is a 
nearly uniform distribution of likelihood of containing the search object; 
that is, the search object is equally likely to be at any point in a given 
region. Different regions may have a different probability of containment.
Regions and region boundaries are based on the factors that affect the 
search object. A region boundary means you think there is a reason why 
the search object is more likely to be on one side of the boundary than the 
other. Regions form the basis of your Probability of Containment 
calculations, so your boundary decisions must be based only on the 
missing person.
First, examine each scenario independently. Assume it is the correct and 
only scenario:
• Identify likely routes of travel and likely locations based on that 
scenario.
• Put yourself in the place of the missing person; what would he/she 
see and encounter and how would that influence their choices and 
direction of travel.
• If the search object is not found on likely routes or in likely 
locations, where would he/she be? Determine reasonable region 
boundaries based on the search object and features that may affect 
the search object’s travel or decisions.
Each region must be completely enclosed by a line on your map. Repeat 
the process for each of the scenarios you believe have a non-trivial chance 
of being the correct scenario.
Then develop a single set of regions for the entire search effort by 
“stacking” the scenarios to check region boundaries for consistency and 
making adjustments to the boundaries if needed.
Go back to the exercise map on page 142. Draw regions based on the 
most likely scenario selected by the class during our earlier proportional 
consensus.
Use all the regions on the combined map you produced. Consider the 
scenario (or each scenario separately if more than one); use the consensus 
method to establish each expert’s view of POC for each region.
Definition of 
Region
Region 
Boundaries
