Developing Regions of Uniform Likelihood
Step Action
1 For a single scenario, review the boundaries of all regions. In this case, the DOWNHILL 
scenario from earlier example (with a scenario weight of .483)
2 a-e Each participant assigns points individually.
Region A Region B Region C Region D Total
Rick 25 100 75 0 200
Dan 10 75 100 0 185
Mark 15 100 50 0 165
In this case, 
Rick thought the search object was most likely be located in Region B, was 3/4 as likely 
to be located in Region C, and only 1/4 as likely in Region A.
Dan thought Region C was most likely; B was 3/4 as likely, and A only 1/10th.
Mark thought that Region B was most likely but thought Region C was only 1/2 as 
likely, and Region A even less likely (1/7 as B and 1/3 as C).
Region D was thought to be unlikely enough to not need searching under this particular 
scenario; it is here because of another reasonable scenario. 
2f Each participant divides individual option numbers by his/her total:
Region A Region B Region C Region D Total
Rick .125 .500 .375 0 1.000
Dan .054 .405 .541 0 1.000
Mark .091 .606 .303 0 1.000
A good check is to add up the decimals: they should equal 1.000. If they don’t you should 
adjust the rounding somewhat. 
3-5 Sum the inputs for each scenario (step 3) and divide by the number of participants (step 4). 
Then, multiply by the scenario weight (in this example, .483) (step 5):
Region A Region B Region C Region D Total
Rick .125 .500 .375 0 1.000
Dan .054 .405 .541 0 1.000
Mark .091 .606 .303 0 1.000
3 -> Total .270 1.511 1.219 0
4 -> Region Weight .090 .504 .406 0 1.000
5 -> Scenario POC .044 .243 .196 0 .483
Region weights should sum to 1.000 and Scenario POC should sum to the scenario weight.
6 Add up the Region A Scenario POC values for all scenarios, the Region B values, etc., to 
yield the initial POC of the regions for the overall search. They should sum to 1 (100%)

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
150 30 October 2014
Developing Regions of Uniform Likelihood
The steps above will yield POC values for each region. If there is more 
than one scenario being considered you will have region POC values for 
each scenario. For each scenario, multiplying each region POC by the 
scenario weight yields a scenario weighted region POC. To determine 
region POC values for the entire search based on all the scenarios under 
consideration, simply add the scenario weighted POC values for each 
region.
Scenario consensus results (region POC values):
Regn A Regn B Regn C Regn D Total
Scenario 1 0.090 0.504 0.406 0.000 1.000
Scenario 2 0.000 0.047 0.530 0.423 1.000
Scenario 3 0.083 0.000 0.457 0.460 1.000
Scenario 4 0.530 0.423 0.000 0.047 1.000
The region values should sum to 1.000 for each scenario, as before.
Scenario results multiplied by scenario weights yield weighted POC:
Weights ↓ Regn A Regn B Regn C Regn D Total
S1: 0.483 0.044 0.243 0.196 0.000 0.483
S2: 0.388 0.000 0.018 0.206 0.164 0.388
S3: 0.086 0.007 0.000 0.039 0.040 0.086
S4: 0.043 0.023 0.018 0.000 0.002 0.043
1.000
POC 0.073 0.280 0.441 0.206 1.000
Given the relative likelihood of the various scenarios and the likelihood of 
location within each scenario, these POC values reflect the combined 
expert judgment of the team: the search object is most likely to be found 
in Region C (44.1%), a little more than 1/2 as likely to be found in Region 
B (28%), just a little less than 1/2 as likely to be found in Region D 
(20.6%), and only 1/6 as likely to be found in Region A (7.3%).
Recall from lesson 14 that segments have associated POC values by virtue 
of being a portion of the search area. Segment POC values are calculated 
using the ratio of each segment’s area to the area of the region the segment 
is part of, multiplied by the POC value of the region the segment is part of:
𝑃𝑂𝐶𝑠𝑒𝑔𝑚𝑒𝑛𝑡 = (𝐴𝑟𝑒𝑎𝑠𝑒𝑔𝑚𝑒𝑛𝑡 𝑥 𝑃𝑂𝐶𝑟𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑜𝑛)
𝐴𝑟𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑜𝑛
For example, if a segment contains one-third of its region’s area, then the 
segment is assigned one-third of the region’s POC.
