Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
152 30 October 2015
Lesson 16
POD FOR GROUND SEARCH
Lesson 11 introduced Probability of Detection and the concept of sweep 
width. Search managers and planners must decide how to use available 
search resources and effort to the best effect in the search area. Two 
important considerations in assigning limited resources are: 1) the amount 
of physical area the resources can search; and 2) the likely results of the 
searching or how likely searchers are to find the search object if it is in the 
area searched. Students need to understand and apply the concepts of 
“probability of detection” to make optimum progress toward the desired 
outcome; a successful search.
At the completion of this lesson, students should:
• Be able to ESTIMATE resources, time and spacing required to search 
a given search area, and be able to ESTIMATE the size of search area 
that can be searched in given time by available searchers;
• RECOGNIZE the factors that affect the ability of searchers to detect 
search objects in the field;
• UNDERSTAND the application and limitation of Average Maximum 
Detection Range and the Range of Detection methods for estimating 
sweep width;
• Be MOTIVATED to survey their areas of SAR responsibility to 
identify the varieties of terrain, vegetation, and other variables that 
will affect detection during searches; and
• Be able to CALCULATE Effort, Coverage, and POD for searching a 
given area.
The following references were used to construct the lesson:
1. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to National SAR Supplement. Chapter 5.
2. National Search and Rescue Committee. (May 2000). National SAR 
Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual. Chapter 5.
3. IMO & ICAO. (2013). IAMSAR Manual, Vol II. Sec 4.6 and 5.10
4. Potomac Management Group, Inc. (30 Dec 04). Sweep Width 
Estimation for Ground Search and Rescue.
5. Potomac Management Group, Inc. (20 May 2006). A Simple Guide to 
Conducting Ground Search and Rescue Detection Experiments. Vol I.
Introduction 
References 
Objectives

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
153 30 October 2015
How to Mathematically Model SAR Resources
In the U.S., more than 80% of searches are completed within the first 12 
hour operational period and over 90% within the first 24 hours. The 
Oregon State Sheriff’s Association (Kim Family Search Review, 2007) 
reported that 94% of search missions in Oregon lasted less than 24 hours. 
This lesson focuses on POD as it applies for area/sweep searching during 
extended ground search incidents (those searches that continue beyond 
24 hours or the first few operational periods). A brief review of how to 
mathematically model SAR resources is presented. Effective Sweep 
Width (W) concepts are reviewed. Average Maximum Detection Range
(AMDR) and Range of Detection (Rd) methods are introduced as a useful 
substitute for calculating Effective Sweep Width when the sweep width 
information is not available. With an understanding of sweep width, 
students will see how to determine Effort, Coverage, and POD for ground 
searching.
The same equation used to mathematically model our limited resources for 
an air search applies to all types of search resources and to all employment 
tactics (search patterns) that search segments, including grid or sweep 
searching, purposeful wandering, etc. Review Lesson 11 (POD for Air 
Search) for discussion on desired search area, searchable area, number of 
resources required, and time to search.
𝑨𝒓𝒆𝒂 (𝑨) = 𝑽 𝒙 𝑺 𝒙 𝑻 𝒙 𝑵
NOTE: For the purposes of this lesson, the units of measurement for 
ground search resources are reflective of units of measurement found on a 
topographic chart (vice the aeronautical chart used to plan searches from 
the air). Be sure to convert units of measurement when planning searches 
for aircraft and ground searchers simultaneously. Examples include: 
distance (statute miles vice nautical miles), distance again (miles vice 
feet), and speed (miles/hour vice knots).
The equation above “assumes” a nominally square segment. Resources 
can be applied from any boundary of the segment with identical results. 
For example, consider that you want to search a square 1 x 1 mile (1 mi2) 
segment with 100 searchers searching at .29 mph. If the operational 
search period is 3.5 hours, searcher spacing is: 
𝑆𝑝𝑎𝑐𝑖𝑛𝑔 (𝑓𝑡) = 𝐴𝑟𝑒𝑎 (𝑠𝑞 𝑚𝑖) 𝑥 5280 (𝑓𝑡⁄𝑚𝑖)
𝑆𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑐ℎ 𝑆𝑝𝑒𝑒𝑑 (𝑚𝑝ℎ) 𝑥 𝑇𝑖𝑚𝑒 (ℎ𝑟) 𝑥 #𝑆𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑐ℎ𝑒𝑟𝑠
= 1 𝑚𝑖2 𝑥 5280 𝑓𝑡⁄𝑚𝑖
