Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
154 30 October 2015
Impact of Segment Shape on Searcher Capability
Search segments in nature are rarely, if ever, symmetrical. Thus search 
planners must analyze the boundaries of each segment to determine the 
appropriate deployment of searchers. This decision can affect both the 
minimum time required to search the segment and the coverage (which 
directly affects POD). To compare options, analyze the segment baseline, 
segment length, and team tracks.
In an air search a single search aircraft is often assigned to search a 
segment by flying multiple parallel tracks, offset by the desired track 
spacing. Ground search teams can use similar tactics. To estimate the 
number of team tracks (#Tracks):
#𝑇𝑟𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑠 = 𝑇𝑖𝑚𝑒(ℎ𝑟)𝑥 𝑆𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑐ℎ 𝑆𝑝𝑒𝑒𝑑(𝑚𝑝ℎ)
𝐿𝑒𝑛𝑔𝑡ℎ
Round number of tracks to an appropriate whole number (full tracks) 
rather than leave a small portion of a segment unsearched. Next, adjust 
the time required to search the segment (see Lesson 11). 
Segment Baseline is the side of the segment along which the searchers or 
search teams will be spaced to start their search. Baseline is important for 
estimating the spacing of the searchers:
𝑆𝑝𝑎𝑐𝑖𝑛𝑔(𝑓𝑡) = 𝐵𝑎𝑠𝑒𝑙𝑖𝑛𝑒(𝑓𝑡)
