Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
156 30 October 2015
Impact of Segment Shape on Searcher Capability
Option 2: If search planners establish the 2.0 side as the baseline,
searchers walk for 0.5 miles. Spacing is now 105 ft, and Minimum Time 
in is Segment 1.7 hr. This option takes 1/2 as long as square segment but 
results in only 1/2 of the coverage.
Option 3: In this option, the search planner established a baseline on both 
0.5 mi ends of the search segment. Searchers walk for 1.0 mi towards the 
center. Spacing is 53 ft , and Minimum Time in Segment is 3.5 hrs. This 
option takes the same time and has the same coverage as a square 
segment.
Option 4: Finally, the search planner employs searchers from the first 
mile of the 2.0 mile baseline. Searchers walk for 0.5 miles, and then shift 
to the other half of the 2 mile side and walk 0.5 miles back. (This is an 
example of multiple team tracks.) Spacing is 53 ft, and Minimum Time in 
Segment is 3.5 hrs. This option takes approximately the same time and 
has the same coverage as a square segment.
Analysis: Option 1 generates the highest level of coverage; it also takes 
the longest amount of time to search the segment once. Option 2 searches 
the segment fastest, but results in ½ the coverage. Options 3 and 4 
provide similar results as the 1.0 mile square segment. As with the airrelated equations in Lesson 11, these equations provide a good starting 
point to help search planners and leadership understand employment 
options. Bottom line: care must be taken to check the results for 
reasonableness and consider search objectives, strategies, and operational 
constraints. 

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
157 30 October 2015
Determining Effective Sweep Width
Recall the two elements of a successful search: you must be searching 
where the search object is located and you must search well enough to 
detect and recognize the search object. Lessons 14 and 15 should help 
identify likely locations for your ground search incident, but how do you 
determine how well the searchers are searching? Just like in Aeronautical 
Search (Lesson 11), Probability of Detection is part of the answer.
The IAMSAR Manual glossary defines Probability of Detection as:
“The probability of the search object being detected, assuming it was in 
the areas that were searched. POD is a function of coverage factor, 
sensor, search conditions and the accuracy with which the search facility 
navigates its assigned search pattern. (POD) Measures sensor 
effectiveness under the prevailing search conditions.”
In other words, POD is a function of the level of search effort expended in 
that search segment, the size of the segment, and how easy or hard it is to 
detect the object of the search. The ease (or difficulty) of detection is, in 
turn, a function of the sensor capability (e.g., the unaided eye), the nature 
of the object of the search (size, color, contrast), and the environment 
(terrain, vegetation, weather, time of day).
Understanding POD requires an understanding the search area and the 
concepts of Sweep Width, Effort, and Coverage.
One of Koopman’s greatest contributions to search theory is quantifying 
the concept of sensor “detectability” he called Effective Sweep Width, or 
just Sweep Width (W). Sweep Width is: “A measure of the effectiveness 
with which a particular sensor can detect a particular object under 
specific environmental conditions.”
It is important to understand that Effective Sweep Width (or Sweep 
Width) recognizes the likelihood of not detecting objects near to the 
sensor, along with the likelihood of detecting objects at a longer range 
from the sensor. Sweep Width does not indicate the maximum distance at 
which an object might be detected, nor that an object would assuredly be 
detected within a range. It is possible to detect a search object at 
distances greater than the Effective Sweep Width.
By itself, Effective Sweep Width is of little interest to the searcher, for it 
does not tell how far away a sensor should be able to detect a search 
object. However, Sweep Width does allow for comparison of the 
effectiveness of different sensors against different targets in different 
environments. Remember, Effective Sweep Width is a function of the 
search object, the sensor, and the environment.
Review of POD
Effective Sweep 
