Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
158 30 October 2015
Determining Effective Sweep Width
Sweep Width is a vital element for determining how well an area is 
searched or the Coverage factor, which in turn allows determination of 
Probability of Detection for a given search sensor or team in a given 
search segment. Effective Sweep Width is the key to improved search 
planning and execution because it provides a means for search planners to 
objectively (mathematically) relate POD, effort and area.
“Sweep Width Estimation for Ground Search and Rescue” (Potomac 
Management Group, 30 Dec 2004) compared searchers’ estimated POD 
calculations with actual POD values obtained from field experiments. The 
most common result was for searchers to over-estimate their detection 
skills (48%); the second most common result was under-estimating (30%). 
The remaining 22% of searchers were able to estimate within plus/minus 
10% (a range of 20%); random chance can account for the percentage that 
fell within this range. Additionally, results indicate the higher the 
searcher’s predicted POD the worse their actual performance. Finally, the 
error difference between predicted POD and actual POD did not improve 
with field experience.
What is the lesson to be learned? Search planners should not make 
subjective POD estimates without reliable data to base their estimates, nor 
should they depend on subjective estimates by field resources. Only a 
carefully designed and executed scientific experiment should be used to 
predict Sweep Width.
Effective Sweep Width can only be determined through extensive field 
experimentation during which the numbers of detections and misses are 
counted for a large number of sensors (searchers) at a wide variety of 
distances from objects. Sweep width is very specific and dependent upon 
the conditions experienced during the search. For instance, visibility, type 
of object, vegetation, and terrain may inhibit detecting the object.
The NSARC has published a detection experiment called “A Simple Guide 
to Conducting Ground Search and Rescue Detection Experiments” 
(Potomac Management Group, 20 May 2006). This two volume guide 
(which includes an integrated detection experiment spreadsheet to perform 
all necessary calculations) assists searchers in planning and conducting 
and effective sweep width experiment.
Download the detection experiment guide on the USCG NSARC website: 
http://www.uscg.mil/hq/cg5/cg534/nsarc/Land_SAR_reports.asp
