Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
159 30 October 2015
Determining Effective Sweep Width
Average Maximum Detection Range (AMDR) is a technique that has been 
used to calculate approximate sweep width values. It is typically used to 
establish the boundaries of the sweep width experiment. Many search 
planners use it (in the absence of time and money required) to conduct the 
sweep width detection experiments. Students should note that the 
experimentation conducted to date neither validates AMDR experiment 
results, nor correlates the resultant values to Effective Sweep Width. This 
lesson uses AMDR as described by “A Simple Guide to Conducting 
Ground Search and Rescue Detection Experiments” (Potomac 
Management Group, 20 May 2006).
AMDR is the average of the distances at which a searcher can barely detect 
an object throughout a 360 degree arc around the object; or, the distance at 
which the searcher can consistently and reliably detect the object.
Based on data from six Effective Sweep Width experiments (Potomac 
Management Group, Inc., 30 Dec 04), a relationship between Sweep 
Width and AMDR has not be determined. Some results clustered around a 
one-to-one relationship, and the remaining results indicated Sweep Width 
was twice AMDR. If AMDR is utilized by search planners, we 
recommend using the conservative assumption (one-to-one relationship); 
it will lead planners to underestimate the effects of their searchers (rather 
than overestimate).
𝑊 =� 𝐴𝑀𝐷𝑅
The cost of underestimating detection capability is searching a segment is 
increasing effort (time or #searchers) more than necessary. The risk for 
overestimating detection capability would be to move to another segment 
while it still contains a high likelihood of containing the search object.
Equating Sweep Width and AMDR is an assumption that is intuitively 
appealing and appears reasonable to some, but that cannot be guaranteed. 
Limitations to using AMDR include:
• Not a true measure of detectability. AMDR only measures the average 
maximum distance at which an object can be detected. AMDR does 
not provide any information about detection as a searcher passes by 
the object (closest point of approach).
• Small data sample. The data sample AMDR uses is not as statistically 
significant as the sample collected for Effective Sweep Width 
experiments.
• Alerted searcher. AMDR measures sensors which are alerted to the
presence, appearance, and exact location of the object --- conditions 
that do not exist with searchers in the field.
