Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
162 30 October 2015
Developing POD
Important concepts to remember include:
• There is a direct relationship between effort and coverage: 
Doubling the coverage factor of a search segment requires 
doubling the effort assigned to that search segment;
• Higher coverage produces higher POD, lower coverage produces 
lower POD; and
• Any increase in POD requires an increase in coverage with a 
corresponding increase in effort.
For a given level of available search effort, a larger search area will result
with a lower coverage, and visa versa. Searchers may elect to use a 
“mixed bag” approach, allocating effort to ensure some search segments 
receive high coverage, some a moderate coverage, some a low coverage 
and some segments may not be searched at all.
POD is a function of coverage. The Coverage – POD relationship is 
determined by calculating the cumulative effects (based on lateral range 
curves, see figure below) of a theoretically infinite number of searchers at 
various spacing. Each possible value for spacing generates one Coverage 
value and a corresponding POD.
The chart and corresponding equation below (Fig 2) is extracted from the 
IAMSAR Manual, Vol. 2, figure N-10.
