Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
164 30 October 2015
Developing POD
Everything you do in search planning is interlinked. One example is the 
linkage between how well a team can search a segment (POD) with how 
much a team can search (area):
• Changing spacing between searchers impacts the size of territory that 
can be searched (area), and visa versa;
• Changing spacing impacts the likelihood searchers will detect the 
search object (POD); thus
• Changing the size of the segment changes the segment POD.
Balancing how much to search and how well to search is not intuitive, but 
finding the right balance is very important in terms of benefit to the 
missing person. The results of this lesson coupled with POC from Lesson 
15 form the foundation elements for a valuable decision aid using 
Probability of Success (POS).
