Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
165 30 October 2014
Lesson 17
POS, PSR, AND GROUND EFFORT ALLOCATION
The next step (in Koopman’s terms) to crafting a good search plan is the 
“optimization function”; how to maximize the likelihood of actually 
finding the search object. Probability of Success allows the search planner 
to measure search effort allocation options against each other to determine 
an “optimal” allocation.
After completing this lesson, students should be able to:
• UNDERSTAND the purposes, uses, and validity of maximizing POS 
as a goal in search planning;
• UNDERSTAND Probable Success Rate (PSR) and how PSR values 
can aid the search planner when making effort allocation decisions;
• UNDERSTAND and EXPLAIN how optimal search planning is not 
intuitive, i.e. intuitive search effort allocation frequently yields 
substantially lower POS than mathematically based planning;
• UNDERSTAND the need for planning ahead into later search periods;
• DEFEND operationally significant modifications to optimal search 
plans, even when modifications result in reduced POS;
• Given a SAR case:
• EVALUATE search plan options,
• CALCULATE each option’s expected results,
• SELECT a single search plan based on probability of success and 
operational considerations;
• DEVELOP rational follow-on search plans expected to yield high 
POS; and
• TRACK search progress in terms of expected search effectiveness.
Objectives
Introduction 

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
166 30 October 2014
Overview 
The following references were used to construct the lesson:
1. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to National SAR Supplement. Chapter 5.
2. National Search and Rescue Committee. (May 2000). National SAR 
Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual. Chapter 5.
3. IMO & ICAO. (2013). IAMSAR Manual, Vol II. Sec 4.
4. Koopman, B.O. (1980). Search and Screening: General Principles 
with Historical Applications. Pergamon Press: New York.
5. Frost, J.R., and Stone, L.D. (Sep 2001). Review of Search Theory: 
Advances and Applications to Search and Rescue Decision Support. 
U.S. Coast Guard Research and Development Center.
6. Stone, L.D. (1999). Advances in Search Theory.
Based on material presented in “Introduction to Search Theory” (lesson 6)
and building on Aeronautical Search lessons, students will learn about 
Probable Success Rate (PSR) and using PSR as an aid when deciding
where and how to allocate available search effort during a search. 
Students will learn how to use a “PSR-Based Effort Allocation 
Worksheet” to determine the search effort that searchers can provide and 
trade-offs for different search effort allocation choices. Students will see 
how the worksheet can aid in computing realistic track spacing, POC, 
POD, and POS values for ground search.
Search Theory
Remember from the “Introduction to Search Theory” lesson the two 
primary elements of a successful search:
• You must be searching in the right place; and
• You must be able to detect what you are searching for.
Therefore you must consider two related likelihoods or probabilities when 
determining the likelihood a search will be successful:
• Probability the search object is where you are searching (POC); 
and
• Probability you can detect the search object if it is there (POD).
References 
Overview
Recall…

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
167 30 October 2014
Optimizing Probability of Success
Koopman defined the elements of the basic problem of optimal search:
• An A priori probability density distribution on search object 
location;
• A detection function relating search effort density (Coverage) and 
Probability of Detection;
• A constrained amount of search effort; and 
• An optimization criterion of maximizing the probability of finding 
the search object (POS) subject to the constraint on search effort.
Using these elements allows the search planner to investigate the optimal 
search problem i.e. finding the best allocation of limited search resources 
to maximize the likelihood of finding the search object. POS is what is 
maximized for optimal search. Attaining the highest POS with limited 
resources available for searching requires the planner to balance the need 
to search where the search object is located against the need to search in 
enough detail to detect the search object if it is there. The interrelated 
elements are written mathematically by:
POC x POD = POS
The search planners’ goal is to search an area large enough to likely 
contain the search object, but also small enough that your search resources 
will be able to search in sufficient detail to be likely to detect the search 
object. Based on the formula above, it might seem the optimum allocation 
of search effort would place the resources with the highest POD into the 
search segments with the highest POC. In fact, that should result in a 
good allocation of search effort but not necessarily the best allocation. 
That is because these simple terms often mask the effects of the important 
factors that comprise them. For instance:
• The number of search resources in a segment or the physical 
capability of the resource in a segment (search speed, time on 
search, etc.) affects the spacing between resources or search tracks;
• The spacing between resources or tracks affects their POD in the 
search segment;
• But, spacing or tracks affects the number of resources being used 
and therefore the number of resources available to search other 
search segments;
• Which in turn affects the tracks, spacing, and POD of the other 
search segments;
Optimal Search 
Problem
Maximize POS

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
168 30 October 2014
Optimizing Probability of Success
Using only the equation for POS does not lead search planners to consider 
breaking search teams into smaller groups in order to split them between 
more search segments. Failing to divide some resources up may result in 
some search segments being searched more thoroughly than initially 
necessary before search effort is allocated to other likely search segments. 
POS may be increased, but is not increasing a rapidly as possible.
Using only the equation may not lead search planners to consider their 
control over how much search effort to expend in a search segment or how 
the conditions in a segment can affect sweep width, both of which will 
affect POD and POS. When using POC x POD = POS search planners 
must be careful to consider the effects of all the operational considerations 
and their effects on POC, POD, POS to craft search plans with greater 
understanding.
The single factor search leadership and planners have the most control 
over is the amount of search effort they allocate to the search segments. 
Whether the effort is in the form of searchers or searcher-hours searching 
on the ground or distance travelled while searching in the search segment 
for aircraft, the amount of effort assigned to a segment is under the control 
of the search leadership and search planners.
In all effort allocation assignments, a key and essential assumption is that 
each search segment searched is searched essentially equally well 
(uniformly) throughout:
• Searchers do not miss large chunks of a search segment; and
• Searchers do not excessively cross and re-cross their own search 
paths such that some of the segment is searched much more than 
other parts.
Turn to the “Ground Search Labs” section of this student guide. The 
“Ground Effort Allocation Exercise” will be completed as a class.
