Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
170 30 October 2014
Probable Success Rate
A segment’s PSR value, standing alone, is not very useful and is not very 
intuitive. However when the PSR values for all search segments are 
computed and compared, the segment with the highest PSR value is the 
segment where the greatest return of investment from the first 
increment of search effort can be produced in the shortest time. 
If the search segments are sorted in descending order of PSR values, the 
segments are listed in order of the most productive to least productive in 
terms of expected search results. By allocating available search effort (i.e. 
searchers) to segments starting with the most productive (highest PSR) 
and working toward the least productive (lowest PSR), the highest 
possible POS can be achieved.
In 1958 two scientists, A. Charnes and W.W. Cooper,. published a paper 
in Management Science called “The Theory of Search: Optimum 
Distribution of Search Effort”. Charnes and Cooper found that the best 
distribution of effort was the one that leveled the PSR playing field as 
much as possible with the available effort. This is most easily illustrated 
with a bar graph that displays PSR values as the heights of columns (see 
the Land SAR Addendum to the NSS, p. 5-44 through 5-46).
In the context of search effort allocation, the optimal search plan is the 
plan that produces the highest possible POS for the given conditions and 
given number of searchers. The optimal search plan occurs when the 
after-search PSR of all segments searched this period are:
• approximately equal; and
• not less than the PSR of any segments not searched this period.
If all search segments are rank-ordered from highest PSR to lowest PSR, 
enough searchers would be allocated to the first segment to bring its PSR 
down to the level of the next segment. Then, searchers would be allocated 
to the first two segments to bring them down to the third highest PSR, and 
so on until all available searchers are allocated (based on Stone, Lawrence 
D., Theory of Optimal Search, 2nd Ed., Operations Research Society of 
America, 1989).
No mathematical method can be allowed to take the place of good 
judgment in the field. The mathematics in this student guide provides 
valuable decision aids, but cannot make your decisions for you. It only 
captures what you put into it and will routinely not include important, 
operationally significant realities. 
Use mathematics as a guide, not as the answer.
What Does PSR 
Mean?
Optimal Means 
