Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
172 30 October 2014
Optimal Allocation
PSR is a valid planning basis for subsequent searches in the same way it is 
for the initial area searches. On the worksheets, the entire top portion 
remains the same for subsequent searches with two exceptions: 
• Line 8: replaced by POC Remaining from previous search Line 18.
• Line 12: replaced by the Line 19 PSR After This Search, 
calculated with the new POC value.
POS and POC adjustments greatly simplify the math and record keeping.
The ground search effort allocation worksheet assumes everything stays 
the same during the search. That may not be accurate, so decision makers 
must periodically question their beginning assumptions.
How might the following change your search plan, regardless of the math?
• Search Object: What are you looking for?
• How well should you have to search to find them?
• Is the condition of the object likely to have changed; for 
instance, from responsive to unresponsive?
• Are the transient clues (smoke, scent, sign, footprints) likely to 
be gone?
• Urgency changes, alternative scenarios, and issues of survivability: 
• Are there other likely areas where you might find the target, 
areas you need to check before survivability decreases too far?
• If the missing person were still moving, are there parts of your 
search area boundary he/she could have escaped through or 
new territory they could have moved into?
• Clues: 
• Taken together, what picture do the clues paint, where do they 
point? Consider any lack of clues in various areas.
• SRUs: 
• Are you likely to uncover more or different clues if you research a segment with a different type of resource? (for 
instance, following a sound sweep with dogs or grid searchers) 
