Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
176 30 June 2016
Lesson 18
POS AND HOW LONG TO SEARCH
According to research and SAR Coordinators from several states, the 
average missing person is found during the first operational period. This 
implies search planners do not need to plan for or consider subsequent 
searches very often. If planners simply assume the missing person will be 
found and do not plan ahead, at the end of the first operational period they 
will be significantly behind and may jeopardize the missing person’s life 
by their lack of preparation for continued searching. Search planners must 
plan ahead for subsequent searching.
After completing this lesson, students should:
• Be able to DISCUSS the merits and limitations of the various 
methods for tracking search progress,
• Be MOTIVATED to establish a standardized method for tracking 
search progress on returning home.
Given a SAR case requiring subsequent searches:
• EXPLAIN the factors considered during re-search/expansion 
decisions during subsequent search periods;
• CALCULATE and TRACK search progress in terms of 
cumulative POS, cumulative POD, and decreasing POC for all 
search segments: and
• DEVELOP attainable search action plans for each operational 
period based on the expected and/or actual results of previous 
search periods and on new clues and investigative information.
The following references were used to construct the lesson:
1. National Search and Rescue Committee. (Nov 2011). Land SAR 
Addendum to National SAR Supplement. Chapter 5.
2. National Search and Rescue Committee. (May 2000). National SAR 
Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual. Chapter 5.
3. IMO & ICAO. (2013). IAMSAR Manual, Vol II. Sec 4.
4. Koopman, B.O. (1980). Search and Screening: General Principles 
with Historical Applications. Pergamon Press: New York.
5. Frost, J.R., and Stone, L.D. (Sep 2001). Review of Search Theory: 
Advances and Applications to Search and Rescue Decision Support. 
U.S. Coast Guard Research and Development Center.
6. Stone, L.D. (1999). Advances in Search Theory.
