Introduction 

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
177 30 June 2016
Cumulative POD 
A traditional method of tracking search progress is through calculating the 
accumulated effects on POD; cumulative POD or PODcum. POD is 
calculated for individual segments. You cannot combine POD values of 
different segments and calculate an “average” POD of the search area.
The cumulative POD in a search segment over many searches is found 
through its opposite; i.e. the cumulative probability the search object 
would not have been detected during any of the search periods. PODcum 
will never reach a value of 100%. The formula for calculating PODcum for 
searching a segment over any number of searches is:
𝑃𝑂𝐷𝑐𝑢𝑚 = 1 − [(1 − 𝑃𝑂𝐷1) 𝑥 (1 − 𝑃𝑂𝐷2) 𝑥 … 𝑥 (1 − 𝑃𝑂𝐷𝑛)]
where “n” is the number of searches in the segment.
For a particular segment, the POD of search 1 is 35%, and the POD of 
search 2 is 30%. Determine PODcum.
𝑃𝑂𝐷𝑐𝑢𝑚 = 1 − [(1 − 𝑃𝑂𝐷1) 𝑥 (1 − 𝑃𝑂𝐷2)]
= 1 − [(1 − 0.35) 𝑥 (1 − 0.30)]
= 1 − [0.65 𝑥 0.70] = 1 − 0.455 = 0.545 𝑜𝑟 55%
PODcum can also be estimated using a chart like the one below, which was 
developed from the above formula. The chart is quicker than using the 
equation; however, rounding error makes the chart is less precise.
Given the same POD values for searches 1 and 2 used in Example 1, use 
the chart to calculate PODcum.
1. Enter chart on vertical axis with “Previous Cumulative POD” row. In 
this example POD of search 1, which is 35%;
2. Enter chart on horizontal axis with “POD for This Search” column, in 
this example POD of search 2, which is 30%;
3. Read estimated PODcum value at the intersection; PODcum = 55%.
