Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
179 30 June 2016
Adjusting POC 
When a segment is searched but the search object is not found, the 
likelihood the search object is still in the segment is less than before the 
search. How much POC have you “searched out” of the segment? An 
amount equal to the expected success: the POS of the search in that 
segment. Thus, a revision of the segment POC (after the search) is 
appropriate. 
We use Bayes’ Theorem to calculate this reduced likelihood of the
probability that the search object was contained in the area when it was 
searched. The segment POC is reduced by an amount proportional to the 
search effort, or segment POD:
𝑃𝑂𝐶𝐴𝑓𝑡𝑒𝑟 = 𝑃𝑂𝐶𝐵𝑒𝑓𝑜𝑟𝑒 𝑥 (1 − 𝑃𝑂𝐷)
= 𝑃𝑂𝐶𝐵𝑒𝑓𝑜𝑟𝑒 − (𝑃𝑂𝐶𝐵𝑒𝑓𝑜𝑟𝑒 𝑥 𝑃𝑂𝐷)
= 𝑃𝑂𝐶𝐵𝑒𝑓𝑜𝑟𝑒 − 𝑃𝑂𝑆
It is important to adjust POC values after each search. Determining where 
to place the effort for the next search, predicting the POS for the next 
search, and computing the cumulative POS for all searching done to date 
all depend on updating the POC values to reflect the results of previous 
searching.
Over successive searches, the POC remaining in the segment decreases, 
which implies that after each search there is a decreasing chance the 
search object is contained within the segment.
As POC remaining decreases, the results of searching (POS) also 
decreases. Over successive searches, POC remaining in the segment 
decreases at a decreasing rate. 
Given a search segment with POC = 80%, calculate the POC after 
searching the segment one time with POD = 30%:
1. Calculate the segment POS:
𝑃𝑂𝑆 = 𝑃𝑂𝐶 𝑥 𝑃𝑂𝐷
= 0.8 𝑥 0.3 = 0.24
2. Calculate the POC (after the search) for the segment:
𝑃𝑂𝐶𝐴𝑓𝑡𝑒𝑟 = 𝑃𝑂𝐶𝐵𝑒𝑓𝑜𝑟𝑒 − 𝑃𝑂𝑆
= 0.8 − 0.24 = 0.56 𝑜𝑟 56%
Adjusting POC 
Example 4

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
180 30 June 2016
Adjusting POC and Cumulative POS
Over a succession of searches, POC remaining decreases toward zero, but 
in ever-smaller steps. even though the effort applied to each search is 
constant (POD=30%). Thus, searching again and again produces smaller 
and smaller amounts of POC removed out of the segment during each 
successive search. Graphing POC Remaining in a segment over 10 search 
periods would yield:
The goal of a search is success – finding the search object fast. POD 
accounts for the likelihood of detecting the search object if it were there 
and able to be found. POC accounts for the likelihood the search object 
was there. Both are required for success: searching in the right place in a 
way that allows detection. The same is true for accumulated effects over 
time. POS provides a measure of search effectiveness because it considers 
both POD and POC. 
POS adds across search segments and across search periods. The basic 
equation can be modified to fit several specific circumstances, but the 
additive nature of POS remains:
• POS of a given search segment after several searches
• POS for a given search region (or the entire search area) during a 
single search period
• POS for all searching done during several search periods
Measure of 
Overall Search 
Effectiveness
POC Remaining

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
181 30 June 2016
Overall POS and Cumulative POS
Overall POS (OPOS). OPOS is the accumulated probability of finding the 
search object with all search effort expended during a search period.
𝑂𝑃𝑂𝑆 = 𝑃𝑂𝑆𝑠𝑒𝑔 1 + 𝑃𝑂𝑆𝑠𝑒𝑔 2 + … + 𝑃𝑂𝑆𝑠𝑒𝑔 𝑛
where “n” is the number of searches in the segment
Cumulative POS (POScum). POScum is the accumulated probability of 
finding the search object with all search effort expended over all searches 
to date.
𝑃𝑂𝑆𝑐𝑢𝑚 = 𝑃𝑂𝑆𝑐𝑢𝑚 𝑜𝑓 𝑝𝑟𝑒𝑣𝑖𝑜𝑢𝑠 𝑠𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑐ℎ𝑒𝑠 + 𝑃𝑂𝑆𝑐𝑢𝑟𝑟𝑒𝑛𝑡 𝑠𝑒𝑎𝑟𝑐ℎ
NOTE: Cumulative POS can never exceed 100% even with a 100% POD 
search. Since POC is adjusted by POS after each search period, and the 
next POS is based on the POC remaining, POScum will approach but never 
reach or exceed the original POC.
Cumulative POD, POC remaining, and cumulative POS all exhibit the 
effects of decreasing returns:
• Doubling effort by searching again does not double the likelihood of 
actually finding the search object
• As a search continues, the same level of search effort produces less 
and less return (likelihood of finding the search object in that period)
• As a search continues, it takes increasingly large amounts of search 
effort to produce significant increases in the likelihood of finding the 
search object
From example 4, continue to search a segment with an initial POC=80% 
and POD=30% over 10 searches. POC remaining and POScum are:
Search (n) POD POC POS POScum 
