Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
182 30 June 2016
Overall POS and Cumulative POS
Note that a lower POS is achieved on each successive search, even though 
the same amount of effort is expended during each search. Thus, the 
incremental increase in POScum is smaller and smaller as the search 
progresses. As POC remaining decreases, POS for the individual search 
periods decrease toward zero while POScum increases toward the original 
POC (or 100% for the entire search area). Plotting POS for individual 
searches and POScum:
POScum
POS

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
183 30 June 2016
How Long Will you Search?
Recall that cumulative POS (POScum) is the accumulated sum of all POS
values for all searching done to date. As the search goes on, all segment 
PSRs fall lower and equalize. Each successive search period produces a 
low POS no matter how you search, because POC Remaining is very low. 
Cumulative POS (POScum), which is the accumulated sum of all POS 
values for all searching done to date, reaches a high value with 
diminishing gain each successive search. When it reaches a high value but 
the search object remains un-located, the value of the information used to 
plan the search has been nearly exhausted. 
High Cumulative POS and low POC remaining are leading indicators 
that the search object is not in the search area, and/or the search object is 
not able to be detected in the search area. At this point, all aspects of the 
case need to be carefully re-evaluated:
• Ensure no plausible scenarios are overlooked, all available information 
is correctly interpreted, and all assumptions are reasonable.
• Ensure all estimates of POC and POD are as accurate as possible.
• Ensure the search area is defined to include all plausible scenarios and 
clues.
• Reassess employment of strategies, deployment of search resources 
and use of tactics.
• Reassess search area coverage: is PODcum sufficiently high throughout 
all segments?
When case reevaluation yields no new clues or scenarios, POScum and 
POC remaining are the leading indicators of when to consider suspending 
a search; when the effort required becomes unreasonably high and is no 
longer in line with the expected benefits. Mathematically, the diminishing 
rate of increase in POScum indicates that the benefits of continued 
searching become unreasonably small regardless of the level of effort 
applied.
Interpreting 
POC Remaining 
and POScum

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
184 30 June 2016
Changing the Search Area
Often, clues or information from either on- or off-scene sources can 
change the entire picture of the search, so much so that search leaders 
want to reevaluate where they believe the target is located. Sometimes, 
the team is just no longer comfortable with the defined search area and reevaluates the clues available to decide if changes are needed.
Re-consensus on POC may be a reasonable method to update the search 
planning effort. As necessary,
• Discuss alternative scenarios, particularly from the perspective of 
how the new information challenges or changes the assumptions 
within each of the scenarios
• Carefully redraw the search area and regions
• Use a consensus process to establish a current set of POC values 
and update the probability map and the search plan
When starting over, there are two options for re-consensus:
• Option 1: Re-consensus with the results of all previous no-find 
searching taken into account; or
• Option 2: Re-consensus without taking any previous searching 
into account.
Re-consensus is accomplished with conscious consideration of all of the 
segments already searched. The consensus participants use that 
knowledge to establish where they believe the search object or missing 
person is currently located and the associated POC. It seems reasonable to 
assume the participants will intuitively adjust their POC assignments 
based on previous searching. If a current scenario would lead to a region 
containing 50% POC, but it had been searched extensively already, one 
would expect the participants to assign significantly less than 50% to that 
region.
Since the POC has been adjusted intuitively, no further mathematical 
adjustments are necessary. The consensus POC values represent the best 
judgment of the leadership team taking into account all relevant factors.
Starting Over
Consensus 
Options
Option 1 -
Considering All 
Previous 
Searching

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
185 30 June 2016
Changing the Search Area
Re-consensus is accomplished consciously ignoring the fact that some 
search segments and regions have already been searched. The effect of 
previous searches is taken into account after the consensus process. 
Consensus participants make their judgments based only on clues and 
information currently available. Once a consensus is reached, POC can be 
adjusted using POC adjustment equations already presented. For each 
segment:
𝑃𝑂𝐶𝑐𝑜𝑟𝑟𝑒𝑐𝑡𝑒𝑑 = 𝑃𝑂𝐶𝑛𝑒𝑤 𝑐𝑜𝑛𝑠𝑒𝑛𝑠𝑢𝑠 𝑥 (1 − 𝑃𝑂𝐷𝑐𝑢𝑚)
It is questionable whether consensus participants can actually distance 
themselves from the knowledge of previous search efforts sufficiently to 
arrive at honest POC judgments in this manner. If participants cannot, this 
method would over-correct POC by double counting the effects of 
previous searches; once intuitively, then again mathematically.
If the search object is moving, planners may elect to reestablish where the 
search object will be during each successive search period. In other 
words, planners will recalculate POC (by consensus) each search period 
because the search object is moving. This accounts for a missing person 
who is ambulatory and could wander back into segments which have 
already been searched.
With a moving target scenario, the effect of previous searching has no 
impact on the current POC. Re-consensus ignores the fact some segments 
and regions have already been searched. The resulting consensus POC is 
not “corrected” for previous POD. In addition, PODcum, POScum, and 
adjusted POC are not valid in a moving search object case. POC, POD, 
POS, and PSR values only have meaning for individual search periods.
As discussed in the lesson on POC and Consensus, check the consensus 
results for reasonableness before continuing with planning. Ensure each 
participant is comfortable with the results of the consensus process; the 
results reflect a reasonable composite of the expert judgments involved 
and pass a collective “common sense” test. A faulty set of POC values 
will adversely affect the entire search.
Option 2 – NOT 
