Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
189 30 October 2012
Practice Labs
AERONAUTICAL SEARCH LABS
After completing labs, students will have considered a variety of search 
planning problems with varying degrees of complexity. Students should 
have experienced many of the common hazards in the available search 
planning and effort allocation methods, to the point that they are willing to 
use these methods in the field, yet still be wary and uncomfortable enough 
to keep questioning the results and trying to better understand the 
problems and solutions they encounter. 
Students must remember that everything in the Inland SAR Planning 
course and student guide is designed as guides, not as rules. Use them as 
starting points, then work to UNDERSTAND and IMPROVE.
The following pages contain several aeronautical scenarios requiring the 
allocation of limited SAR resources. A set of “school solutions” to the 
labs are printed behind each work sheet; however, since the school cannot 
predict which allocations students will experiment with, these are 
obviously not intended as the “right answers.” It is recommended that 
each student attempt to work a problem PRIOR to referring to its answer 
sheet.
These work sheets present a standardized methodology for allocating 
scarce resources; however, students are encouraged to experiment with 
other possibilities.
All Aeronautical Search exercises and labs use the “All Flight Types” 
Air Search Area Definition Tables.
Follow the line-by-line instructions for worksheets in student guide 
Appendix C, especially for Lab 3. Each scenario should have a blank 
worksheet and its corresponding answers on a separate sheet. However, 
many of the solution forms look very much alike. When checking your 
work, make sure you use the worksheet labeled for the right scenario!!
Objective
What is 
Provided
