Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
190 30 October 2012
Aeronautical Search Planning Exercise (from Lesson 12)
A Cessna 172, N7411, is reported overdue on a flight from Rapid City, 
SD, to Cheyenne, WY. The aircraft departed Rapid City at 0700L. ETA 
at Cheyenne was 0845L. Time is now 1200L. The only result of the FAA 
and AFRCC communications search is the radar and radio reports shown 
below. Overdue aircraft was not found at at any airport near the route of 
flight. Use the “All Flight Types” ASAD table to calculate POC values. 
Assume no jurisdictional borders, no large changes in sweep width, and no 
changes in time zones. Round up the number of tracks which the search 
aircraft will fly.
Complete sections A and B of the “Air Effort Allocation Worksheet 
(ASAD)” to plan your initial search effort. Determine the number of full 
search tracks each SRU can complete. Then complete section C to 
calculate POS for the variety of offsets pre-printed on the “Air Effort 
Allocation Worksheet”. Consider POS and the POC-POD trade-off 
possibilities before selecting which search option to select.
Situation
As a Class

