Practice Labs
GROUND SEARCH LABS
After completing labs, students will have considered a variety of search 
planning problems with varying degrees of complexity. Students should 
have experienced many of the common hazards in the available search 
planning and effort allocation methods, to the point that they may be 
willing to use these methods in the field, yet still be wary and 
uncomfortable enough to keep questioning the results and trying to better 
understand the problems and solutions they encounter. 
Students must remember that everything in the Inland SAR Planning 
course and student guide is designed as guides, not as rules. Use them as 
starting points, then work to UNDERSTAND and IMPROVE.
The following pages contain several ground scenarios requiring the 
allocation of limited SAR resources. Work sheets are provided for the 
ground SAR labs. 
A set of “school solutions” to the labs are printed behind each work sheet; 
however, since the school cannot predict which allocations students will 
experiment with, these are obviously not intended as the “right answers.” 
It is recommended that each student attempt to work a problem PRIOR to 
referring to its answer sheet.
These work sheets present a standardized methodology for allocating 
scarce resources; however, students are encouraged to experiment with 
other possibilities.
Each scenario should have a blank worksheet and its corresponding 
answers on a separate sheet. However, many of the solution forms look 
very much alike. When checking your work, make sure you use the 
worksheet labeled for the right scenario!!
