Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
208 31 May 2016
Ground Effort Allocation Exercise (from Lesson 17)
The initial hasty search has been completed along likely routes of travel, 
likely locations, and hazards. Investigation efforts are on-going. 
Unfortunately, no clues were produced by the initial hasty search or the 
investigation so far. The search leadership has decided to start area 
searching.
The search leadership team has discussed and selected reasonable 
scenarios for where the lost person has gone, defined the search area and 
search regions. They have held a consensus for POC and segmented
the regions as shown.
Search leadership plans to bring the searchers in along the north-south line 
between the segments and have them search outwards from the center, 
as shown by the arrows in the figure. With 60 searchers planned to be 
available, how would you intuitively allocate your resources? What is 
your reasoning and rationale?
On the “PSR Based Ground Effort Allocation Worksheet” handed out in 
class, complete lines A1 through A12 to calculate the PSR for each 
segment. What do those numbers mean to you? 
Note that PSR as calculated by the worksheet is not exactly the rate of 
increase in POS since most variables are in miles, but sweep width is in 
feet. Nevertheless, PSR as calculated is still proportional to the expected 
POS increase and the relative PSR values are still valid for rank-ordering 
purposes.
