Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
209 31 May 2016
Ground Effort Allocation Exercise (from Lesson 17)
Continue with the worksheet, testing your initial intuitive allocation of 
search effort. Check the results in terms of POS.
Section B allows planners to experiment with searcher allocations to 
determine the effects of alternative allocations. After considering the 
results of your intuitive allocation:
• Rank-order segments by PSR;
• Make an educated guess at the number of segments that can be 
reasonably searched with the number of searchers available;
• Assign an operationally reasonable number of searchers into the 
highest PSR segments;
• Calculate predicted POS and after-search PSR as though the 
searchers actually searched as assigned; and 
• Check for improvements.
After calculating the results for one search, now experiment with search 
effort allocations for a subsequent search. Consider PSR values when 
allocating search resources. Additionally, calculate POS and PSR values 
using “Time to Search” of four hours, which requires calculations based 
on “purposeful wandering”.
Worksheet 
Section B: 
Allocate Effort 
with PSR

