Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
218 31 May 2016
Ground Search Labs
Complete the “PSR-Based Effort Allocation Worksheet” for each of the 
search problems below. All of the information you will need is given. 
Investigate the POC/POD/POS options and other search considerations.
A blank worksheet is provided for each problem. The “answers” are 
printed after the blank worksheets. Since the school can’t predict the 
numbers of searchers you might place into each searched segment, our 
Section B numbers may vary from yours.
A detailed explanation of each line of the Worksheet is provided in
Appendix D of this Student Guide.
Make certain to check your answers against the correct answer sheet –
many look alike.
Desired maximum on-search time for all problems is 3-6 hours.
Search speed for ground search teams is 0.5 mph.
You are searching for a lost person and have narrowed your search area 
down to a single region 2.55 sq miles in size. There are 7 hours of 
daylight remaining. You have segmented your region as indicated in the 
table below. Since there is only one region, the total POC of 100% must 
be divided between the 3 segments. Sweep width was determined by a 
“rain dance” to be 50 ft sweep width in each segment. You have 105 grid 
searchers available this search period. 
SEARCH SEGMENT DATA
Segment Length Base Sweep Width
A1 1.60 mi 0.5 mi 50 ft
A2 1.45 mi 0.8 mi 50 ft
A3 1.95 mi 0.3 mi 50 ft
In the “School Solutions,” we first entered the desired POD on line B16, 
then worked backwards up to line B13 to determine the number of 
searchers required to achieve the desired POD, then down to lines B17-
B19 to determine the POS and the POS and PSR remaining if we were to 
search in that manner with those extra searchers. (See Student Guide, 
pages 172-173). Next, we experimented allocating the given number of 
searchers variously into the 3 segments. 
