A-1 30 October 2014
Appendix A
AIR SEARCH AREA DEFINITION TABLES (ASAD) TABLES
Background
In 2009, NASA commissioned a study to 
(amongst other tasks) perform an historical 
analysis of a missing aircraft’s route. The 
purpose of the Data Collection and Analysis 
for NASA World Wind Search and Rescue 
Visualization Program study was to perform 
data acquisition and analysis that aids in the 
development of an improved search 
management tool that blends results from an 
analysis of statistically significant past 
search data with aircraft radar track, terrain, 
and weather information.
This task of the NASA study, also known as 
the Air Search Area Definition (ASAD), 
collected, cleaned, and analyzed distress 
incidents of missing aircraft that resulted in 
search efforts and were recorded by the Air 
Force Rescue Coordination Center 
(AFRCC). The data collected from the 
AFRCC and augmented by National 
Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) 
Aviation Accident Reports numbers 262 
search incidents covering a time period from 
2002 to 2008.
This NASA study data is most likely to be 
useful in developing a reasonable search 
area during the early stages of a missing 
aircraft search. Search managers and 
planners can use the NASA study data to 
help determine where to search, even when 
radar data is sparse, non-existent, or not yet 
available. 
Use NASA data when all four of the 
following have been determined:
• A missing or overdue aircraft
• A point of origin or Last Known Point 
(LKP)
• An intended or expected route of flight
• A destination, distinct from the origin or 
LKP
Find the “Data Collection and Analysis for 
NASA World Wind Search and Rescue 
Visualization Program (2009)” on the 
National SAR Committee website 
(www.uscg.mil/nsarc).
Calculating POC
To calculate Probability of Containment for 
a search area based on a known LKP, 
intended route of flight, and destination 
using ASAD data:
1. Select correct table based on type of 
flight profile flown by the missing aircraft: 
All Flight Types, IFR, or VFR.
2. Select the offset distance to be evaluated.
3. Determine Probability of Offset (PO) 
value for distance offset from track to be 
searched. Values are based on the equal 
likelihood that the missing aircraft is either 
left or right of track.
4. Determine Probability Along Track (PT) 
value based on percentage of planned route 
to be searched. Percentages begin at LKP 
and increase toward intended destination i.e. 
first 10% of route, first 20% of route, etc. 
5. Calculate POC by multiplying the 
probability of offset by the probability along 
track:
𝑃𝑂𝐶 = 𝑃𝑂 𝑥 𝑃𝑇
If radar data is not available, the most 
powerful tool to help define a search area 
is route information.
-- 2009 NASA study

