Appendix B
AIR SEARCH SWEEP WIDTH TABLES
The US Coast Guard performed extensive experimentation during air 
searches on the visual detection for large aircraft (above 12,500 lbs), small 
aircraft (below 12,500 lbs), vehicles and people. This detection 
performance data is called Sweep Width (W), and it can be calculated at 
various search altitudes and meteorological visibilities. Additionally, the 
US Coast Guard found (through experimentation) that this uncorrected 
Sweep Width (Wu) required a correction factor for the key characteristic 
with the greatest impact on effective sweep width in the search 
environment: vegetation and terrain. The resulting Sweep Width tables 
can be found in the IAMSAR Manual, Vol II (2013), Appendix N. To 
calculate Sweep Width (using the tables on B-2 – B-3):
1. Enter the “Uncorrected Sweep Width for Visual Search” table for the 
specific type of search object using the planned search altitude and 
meteorological visibility to obtain the Uncorrected Sweep Width (Wu).
2. Find the right correction factor: analyze the environment which the 
search aircraft is planning to search, and closely match to one of the 
terrain descriptions in the Sweep Width Correction Factors for 
Vegetation and Terrain table.
3. To calculate the Corrected Sweep Width, multiply Uncorrected Sweep 
Width times the correction factor.
𝑊 = 𝑊𝑈 𝑥 𝑐𝑜𝑟𝑟𝑒𝑐𝑡𝑖𝑜𝑛 𝑓𝑎𝑐𝑡𝑜𝑟
The National Search and Rescue Supplement to the IAMSAR Manual also 
presents visual Sweep Width estimates for visual searches for a variety of 
Visual Distress Signaling Devices used in both daytime and nighttime. 
Sweep Width tables are found in the NSS (2000) Appendix G. Some 
available values for Sweep Width include:
• Day: mirrors (5nm),
• Night: Cyalume light stick (1nm), red pen-gun flare (8nm), handheld red flare (15nm, 500 candlepower).
How to Use 
Sweep Width 
tables
