C-4 30 October 2014
AIR EFFORT ALLOCATION WORKSHEET (ASAD) JOB AID
GENERAL: The AIR EFFORT ALLOCATION WORKSHEET is used to determine the total 
amount of search effort that several dissimilar SRUs can provide. The worksheet also aids in 
computing track spacing, probability of containment, probability of detection, and probability of 
success. Finally, the worksheet conveniently allows the user to determine the actual search 
segment dimensions for each available SRU. Worksheet inputs are based on DAYLIGHT, 
VISUAL SEARCH which does not continue beyond sunset.
NOTE: Three different conditions can exist for which this worksheet is designed:
1. SRU's can search the whole route of flight uninhibited, therefore the 
search area is segmented based on SRU capabilities; or
2. Jurisdictional boundaries exist which limit the operating areas for the 
SRUs, therefore the search area is segmented based on jurisdictional 
boundaries; or
3. Operational considerations dictate SRU operating areas, therefore the 
search area is segmented based on changes in terrain, sweep width, etc. 
along the route of flight. 
SECTION A: SEARCH AREA AND SUB-AREAS (ASAD)
LINE 1 “Length of Flight”
Use the distance in nautical miles (nm) along the probable route of flight from the last 
known position (LKP) to the destination. If restricted by jurisdictional boundaries or 
operational considerations, enter the length of each bounded segment in sequential 
columns, with the first column including the LKP and working sequentially toward 
the destination in subsequent columns.
LINE 2 “Length of Search Area”
Add 20 nm to the length of flight to adjust the primary search length for searching 10 
nm prior to departure/LKP and 10 nm beyond destination. If restricted by 
jurisdictional/operational boundaries, add 10 nm to only the sub-areas containing the 
LKP and destination. (10 nm chosen to encompass > 100% of the route probabilities).
SECTION B: EFFORT AND SEARCH SET-UP
NOTE: To ease later calculations, list sub-areas and segments in order from LKP through 
destination.
LINE 3 “Search Segment and SRU Designation”
Use common segment designators and SRU identifiers, such as tail numbers, to allow 
easy reference to segments. The designation system must be flexible enough to 
identify and track accomplishments as segments are re-searched and possibly 
subdivided throughout the search.

Inland SAR Planning Course Student Guide
C-5 30 October 2014
SECTION B: EFFORT AND SEARCH SET-UP
LINE 4 “Sweep Width (corrected)” -- the detector's (eyes) ability to detect the target in the 
environment.
Use the sweep width table from IAMSAR data included on page 2 of the worksheet if 
searching for a light aircraft. (If searching for a large aircraft, see IAMSAR Manual 
volume 2, appendix N or Student Guide Appendix B):
- Begin in the "Uncorrected Sweep Width for Visual Search for Missing Light 
Aircraft" table at the assigned altitude for the SRU. Move horizontally in the 
table to the column that intersects with the meteorological visibility in the search 
area. This is the uncorrected sweep width. 
- Next, in the "Sweep Width Correction Factors for Vegetation and Terrain (Visual 
Aerial Search for Light Aircraft)" table, determine the correction factor for the 
vegetation and/or terrain conditions in the search area. 
- Multiply the Uncorrected Sweep Width by the Sweep Width Correction Factor to 
determine the Corrected Sweep Width.
LINE 5a “Search Endurance – Fuel Limited”
Determine, to the nearest tenth of an hour, the total time the SRU will be able to 
remain on scene in its assigned segment, not counting transit time to and from the 
segment. 
Multiply times 0.85 to account for time on scene but not actively advancing the 
search pattern (estimated 15% time loss for turns, investigating sightings, etc.).
LINE 5b “Search Endurance – Daylight or Environment Limited”
Determine, to the nearest tenth of an hour, the number of hours between SRU arrival 
time in the segment (start of its search pattern) and sunset or when it will need to 
leave because of light or environmental conditions precluding effective search. 
Multiply times 0.85 to account for time on scene but not actively advancing the 
search pattern (estimated 15% time loss for turns, investigating sightings, etc.).
LINE 5c “Search Endurance – Observer or Operations Limited”
Determine, to the nearest tenth of an hour, the maximum number of hours you want 
the observers to be actively scanning in the search area. 
If the time you determine is for actual search time and does not include time resting 
during turns, enter this time on Line B5c. If the time you determine is for total time 
in the search area, multiply times 0.85 to account for time on scene but not actively 
scanning during turns, etc.).
LINE 6 “Search Endurance”
Enter the smallest of lines B5a, B5b, and B5c to represent the maximum time the 
SRU will be actively advancing the search pattern, even though it may be in the 
search segment longer (making turns, investigating sightings, etc.). Takes into 
account fuel, daylight, and observer limitations.

Inland SAR Planning Course Student Guide
C-6 30 October 2014
SECTION B: EFFORT AND SEARCH SET-UP
LINE 7 “Search Craft Speed”
Use the True Airspeed (TAS) the SRU will fly during the search. For parallel and 
creeping line searches, TAS will closely approximate the AVERAGE ground speed 
since wind effects should be somewhat balanced out by flying reciprocal search legs.
LINE 8 "SRU Mileage"
Multiply the Search Endurance (B6) by Search Craft Speed (B7). This provides the 
number of miles each SRU should be able to contribute on its search pattern.
LINE 9 "Total Mileage for Area or Sub-Area"
Add all line B8 values to determine total mileage available from all Search Craft. If 
restricted by jurisdictional boundaries, add up mileage values within each sub-area. 
This is the total effort in miles that all SRUs combined can contribute in their subareas.
LINE 10 “Track Portion Within Sub-Area”
Divide the mileage a particular SRU can contribute (B8) by the total contribution 
(B9) in the area/sub-area it will be operating within. Enter result to the nearest 
hundredth. This segments the search area according to the relative contributions of 
the SRUs in order to take best advantage of their capabilities.
LINE 11 “SRU Search Segment Length”
Multiply the length of the flight or sub-area (A2) by the track sub-area portion which 
the SRU can cover (B10). Enter result to the nearest whole number (nm). 
LINE 12 “Number of Tracks”
Divide SRU Mileage (B8) by SRU Search Segment Length (B11). Enter result to the 
nearest tenth. This is the number of legs (tracks) the SRU can fly along and parallel 
to the missing aircraft route of flight.
LINE B13 “Number of Full Tracks”
Round-off the values on B13 (Number of Tracks) to whole numbers. This fulfills the 
necessity that SRUs will search complete legs. NOTE: If rounding up, check to 
ensure the SRU will have sufficient endurance (fuel reserves, daylight, observer 
endurance, etc.) to search the extra mileage and time.

Inland SAR Planning Course Student Guide
C-7 30 October 2014
SECTION C: POS COMPARISONS
This section encourages experimentation to investigate the POS trade-offs between 
searching a larger area (higher POC) in less detail (lower POD) or a smaller area 
(lower POC) in more detail (higher POD).
This section assumes the entire length of the search area is searched, searching is 
centered on the track centerline, and all SRUs in all segments search the same number 
of tracks with the same spacing. If there are jurisdictional boundaries, consensusbased segments and POCs, or other operational reasons that invalidate these
assumptions, the offset, width, and POC values pre-printed on lines C14 and C15 
may be invalid; line them out as appropriate and replace them as described in the line 
remarks, below. In these cases, it is likely planners will need to use one worksheet 
column for each segment and a separate worksheet for each experiment.
LINE 14 “Offset”
A variety of offsets are provided on the worksheet, but the planner can substitute 
different ones.
Offset is the lateral distance from the track centerline the planner desires to use as a 
segment boundary. The air search area definition statistics use "offset" as the 
distance off track at which missing aircraft were found. The statistics do not 
differentiate between aircraft found left or right of course. Thus, the pre-printed 
offsets used here assume searching to an equal distance left and right of track. If 
searching is not centered on the track, replace the pre-printed offset value with the 
actual left and right distances to be searched and use section D to calculate POC 
values for line C19.
LINE 15 "Search Segment Width"
The pre-printed values assume an equal distance on each side of the expected track 
will be searched. If that is not the case, replace the pre-printed value with the actual 
width of the segment to be searched and use Section D to calculate the POC values 
for line C19.
LINE 16 “Track Spacing Required”
Divide the segment width (C15) by the number of full tracks the SRU can fly (B13). 
This is the track spacing that must be assigned in order to search the entire desired 
segment width, given the number of full tracks the SRU can fly. Scanners/observers 
must be instructed to search at least to the half-way point between tracks.
LINE 17 "Coverage"
Divide sweep width (B4) by track spacing (C16). Coverage is a measure of search 
quality or effectiveness. It relates searcher capability (sweep width) with searcher 
employment (track spacing) to determine how well the search area has been covered.

Inland SAR Planning Course Student Guide
C-8 30 October 2014
SECTION C: POS COMPARISONS
LINE 18 "Probability of Detection"
The probability of detecting the search object, if it is in the segment being searched.
Enter the bottom of the "POD vs. Coverage" graph on the second page of the 
worksheet, using the Coverage computed on line C17, and move vertically until 
intersecting the curve. Then, move horizontally to the left to read Probability of 
Detection for that search off the vertical axis of the “POD vs. Coverage” graph.
The mathematics behind the "POD vs. Coverage" curve require only that in any 
segment searched, the segment is searched essentially equally well throughout, 
minimizing gaps that would be significantly under-searched and searcher cross-over
that would be significantly over-searched. The equation for the exponential search 
curve is
C POD e
1 , 
where "C" is coverage and "e" is the base of the natural logarithms 
(~2.718281828459).
LINE 19 "Probability of Containment"
The probability the missing aircraft is in the segment being searched. 
If the entire length of flight from LKP to destination is being searched, use the 
Probability of Offset and Probability along Track charts for the missing aircraft’s 
flight plan type, found in Appendix A. 
If the entire length of flight is not being searched or you will not be searching 
equally on both sides of the missing aircraft’s intended track, enter the actual 
values as described for lines C14 and C15, then calculate POC using Section D of this 
worksheet.
If the planning staff has segmented the search area based on subjective/deductive 
evaluations and has used a consensus method to establish POC based on expert 
judgment (as opposed to using the ASAD statistics), enter the consensus POC values 
here on Line C19 and ensure the offset and width values on lines C14 and C15 are 
accurate.
LINE 20 "Probability of Success"
POD (C18) times POC (C19). The likelihood of finding the missing aircraft (based 
the assumptions of the ASAD POC statistics, the ICAO sweep width data, and SRU 
accuracy).

Inland SAR Planning Course Student Guide
C-9 30 October 2014
SECTION D: POC CALCULATIONS
Use this section to manually calculate Probability of Containment using the ASAD 
statistics when; 1) the entire length of the expected route of flight (from Line A2) is 
not searched; or 2) searching is not centered on the centerline of the expected track;
or 3) operational considerations have SRUs searching with different track spacing, 
segment widths, or sweep widths. In these cases, it is likely planners will need to use 
one worksheet column for each segment and a separate worksheet for each 
experiment.
Section D assumes the validity of the ASAD statistics that are based on the 2009 
NASA study establishing the percentages of missing aircraft found within 5nm 
offsets from the expected route of flight and 10-25% increments along the length of 
the expected route of flight. The tables are divided up based on type of flight plan 
and uses straight-line interpolation for offsets between those data points to provide a 
"best guess" estimate for search planning.
Do not use Section D or the ASAD statistics if the statistics are not valid for the 
search incident or if POC has been established through consensus. For example, 
ASAD statistics do not apply for a missing/overdue aircraft that was to depart from 
and return to the same airport, with no known itinerary or route for the flight.
LINE 21 "Segment Start Point"
The distance in nm from the LKP to the near end of the individual search segment. 
Note the distance is based on the LKP and does NOT include 10nm before the LKP. 
If the segment includes the LKP, use “0”, not “–10”: you are searching those extra 10 
miles because it is smart, the ASAD statistics back up this assumption. 
LINE 21a "Starting Point Percent Along Track"
Divide the starting point miles (D21) by the total length of the expected route of flight 
(total of line A1). Do not use the length of the search area from Line A2.
LINE 21b "Starting Point Probability Along Track"
The likelihood, according to the ASAD statistics, the missing aircraft is between the 
LKP and the starting point for the current segment.
Use the "Starting Point Percentage Along Track" from Line D21a to determine 
"Probability Along Track" for the type of flight plan (IFR, VFR, or all flight types)
from ASAD tables in Student Guide Appendix A. 
LINES 22, 22a, 22b "Segment Ending Point, EP Percent Along Track, and EP Probability 
Along Track"
Repeat the steps for lines D21, D21a, and D21b using the distance from the LKP to 
the far end of the individual search segment to determine the likelihood, according to 
the ASAD statistics, the missing aircraft is between the LKP and the far end of the 
segment.

Inland SAR Planning Course Student Guide
C-10 30 October 2014
SECTION D: POC CALCULATIONS
For a segment that includes the destination, for LINE D22 do not include the extra 10 
miles beyond the destination. For LINES D22a and 22b use the over 100% POC 
statistics from the ASAD tables in Appendix A of this Student Guide.
LINE 23 "Probability Along Track"
Subtract the Starting Point Probability Along Track (D21b) from the Ending Point 
Probability Along Track (D22b) to obtain the likelihood, assuming the ASAD 
statistics, of the missing aircraft being between the ends of the individual search 
segment. If segment start point is the LKP, DO NOT subtract start point PT UNLESS
you are not searching the LKP. Note: Probability Along Track does not account for 
the offset or distance from centerline; rather, it is the likelihood out to essentially 
infinity left and right of centerline.
LINE 24 "Left Border Offset"
Enter the nm from the track centerline to the left of course border desired for the 
search segment.
LINE 24a "Left Border Probability of Offset"
Use the "Left Border Offset" from Line D24 and the "Probability of Offset" tables in 
Appendix A of this Student Guide for the appropriate type of flight plan (IFR, VFR, 
All Flight Types) to determine Probability of Offset. Divide the table value by 2 to 
obtain the likelihood the missing aircraft is between the track centerline and the 
distance offset to the left border of the search segment.
LINES 25 and 25A"Right Border Offset” and “Right Border Probability of Offset"
Repeat steps for lines D24 and D24a using the offset value to the right side of 
centerline to obtain the likelihood, assuming the ASAD statistics, the missing aircraft 
is between the track centerline and the distance offset to the right border of the search 
segment.
LINE 26 "Probability of Offset"
If the left and right borders of the search segment are on the same side of the track 
centerline, calculate Probability of Offset by subtracting Poffset near border from Poffset far 
border: D25a – D24a
If the left and right borders of the search segment are on opposite sides of track 
centerline, calculate Probability of Offset by adding Poffset right border to Poffset left border: 
D25a + D24a

Inland SAR Planning Course Student Guide
C-11 30 October 2014
SECTION D: POC CALCULATIONS
Yields the likelihood, assuming the ASAD statistics, the missing aircraft is between 
the left and right borders of the individual search segment. Note: this does not 
account for the distance the aircraft may have traveled along track; rather, it is the 
likelihood out to essentially infinity in either direction along the expected route of 
flight.
LINE 27 "Probability of Containment"
Multiply the Probability Along Track (D23) times the Probability of Offset (D26) to 
obtain the likelihood, assuming the ASAD statistics, the missing aircraft is within the 
boundaries of the selected segment.
If multiplying percentages, divide the result by 100. For example, (12.5% * 39.6%) / 
100 = 4.95%.
If using decimals, multiply result by 100 to get POC as a percentage. For example, 
.125*.396 = .0495, .0495 * 100 = 4.95%.
Place this value in the appropriate columns on Line C19.

