Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
D-4 31 July 2015
PSR-BASED GROUND EFFORT ALLOCATION WORKSHEET 
GENERAL: The PSR-BASED GROUND EFFORT ALLOCATION WORKSHEET is used by 
search planners to determine how to most efficiently allocate the total amount of search effort
available. The worksheet aids in computing realistic track spacing, probability of containment, 
probability of detection, and probability of success. Unique to the ground search is the Probable 
Success Rate (PSR) – the instantaneous change in the success rate for the addition or subtraction 
of one searcher in a given area. The worksheet allows the planner to test search effort allocation 
options in various segments to compare search effort options against expected gain or loss in 
POS. Worksheet inputs are based on DAYLIGHT, VISUAL search, which does not continue 
beyond sunset. 
NOTE: This worksheet assumes an entire search segment is searched essentially equally 
well throughout.
The worksheet allows for varying methods of searcher employment to include: once-through 
sweep, multiple search tracks, and purposeful wandering. Depending on the strategy the original 
length and baseline dimensions of the segments might need to be reversed. The worksheet 
defines “length” as the direction of search and “baseline” as the dimension along which the 
searchers are spaced.
Once-Through Sweep: Calculate section A as written. “Time to Search Segment” (line 11) is 
calculated based on segment length and search speed. “Team Tracks” (line 11a) will default to 
one, therefore “Time in Search Segment” (line 11b) is by definition equal to “Time to Search 
Segment” (line 11). For the “Once-Though Sweep” option, “Searcher Spacing” on line 14 can 
use the simpler formula: S = (baseline x 5280)/number of searchers.
Multiple Team Tracks: “Time to Search Segment” (line 11) is either calculated as in the 
“Once-Through Sweep” option or is your estimate of desired maximum time on the pattern for 
the search team. “Team Tracks” (line 11a) is either the desired number of tracks or is calculated 
based on the entered desired maximum time on the pattern entered in line 11. “Searcher 
Spacing” (line 14) uses the longer equation: 
S = (segment area x 5280)/(time x speed x (searchers – 1)
“Searchers – 1” is used to account for flankers flagging their edge in one direction and then 
unflagging in the reverse, losing the effect of one searcher. If flankers will not be flagging, 
adjust the equation appropriately.
Wandering: A nominal spacing value can be derived for the case of teams wandering in the 
search segment. The essential assumption is the entire segment is searched essentially equally 
well throughout, with no large gaps and no excessive crossing of search paths. For purposeful 
wandering, “Time to Search Segment” (line 11) is your MINIMUM time on the search pattern 
for each searcher track. “Team Tracks” (line 11a) is not required. “Time in Search Segment” 
(line 11b) is initially the same as “Time to Search Segment” (line 11) --- the planner can increase 
this time as desired. “Searcher Spacing” (line 14) uses the longer equation:
S = (segment area x 5280)/(time x speed x searchers)
CAUTION: For purposeful wandering, the mathematics do not provide a check that the 
searchers can actually accomplish the desired search in the time allotted.

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
D-5 31 July 2015
SECTION A: REGION AND SEGMENT INFORMATION
LINE 1 “Region Designation”
National SAR School standard is alphabetical, in sequence (A, B, C …). Remember, 
this designation is for the REGION, not the SEGMENT. 
Note: If you have many segments within a region, consider using one worksheet per 
region. In any case, make sure to keep regions separated so there is no confusion 
further down the worksheet.
LINE 2 “Region Area” (square miles)
Measure the size of your region. Calculation based on length and width may not be 
as accurate as area-specific measurement methods (such as a dot area counter). This 
measurement should be in square miles. (Round to nearest hundredth). 
Consider measuring the area of all segments in the region, then summing to determine 
the region area.
LINE 3 “Region POC” (from consensus)
From your consensus, enter the Region POC for each area. Be sure to use a 
consistent format throughout the worksheets, either percentages or decimals. (If 
using decimals, round to nearest thousandth)
LINE 4 “Segment Designation”
National SAR School standard is numerical, in sequence, per region. This 
designation must be different from your Region Designation and a subset is often 
useful (for example A1, A2, A3, B1, B2, etc. for segments in Regions A and B).
LINE 5 “Segment Length” (miles)
Length is the dimension along the direction the searchers will search. Different styles 
of searching may require a different “side” of the segment to be chosen (single sweep,
or multiple tracks).
Measure the length in miles. (Round to nearest hundredth)
LINE 6 “Segment Baseline” (miles)
Measure the baseline length in miles. The baseline is the dimension used to line up 
the searchers and send them through the segment. (Round to nearest hundredth)
LINE 7 “Segment Area” (square miles)
Measure the segment area using a map tool. Calculating segment area from length 
and baseline works only with rectangular segments. (Round to nearest hundredth)
LINE 8 “Segment POC”
Divide Segment Area (A7) by the Region Area (A2), and then multiply by the Region 
POC (A3). (Round to nearest thousandth)

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
D-6 31 July 2015
SECTION A: REGION AND SEGMENT INFORMATION
LINE 9 “Sweep Width” (feet)
Enter the Sweep Width in feet, or as calculated from correlating Average Maximum 
Detection Range (AMDR) or Range of Detection (Rd) experiment data. (Round to 
nearest whole number)
LINE 10 “Searcher Speed” (miles per hour)
Enter the speed the searchers should use while actively searching. Tests to determine 
search speed in the local environment would be beneficial. (Round to nearest 
hundredth)
LINE 11 “Minimum Time to Search Segment” (hours)
This number is the minimum time it will take a searcher to traverse the segment from 
baseline to opposite end of the segment. Divide segment length (A5) by searcher 
speed (A10). (Round to nearest tenth)
LINE 11a “Team Tracks”
This is the number of “passes” a searcher will traverse through the segment. Multiply 
Time to Search Segment (A11) by Searcher Speed (A10), and then divide by Segment 
Length (A5). (Round to nearest whole number)
For a single pass through the segment, Team Tracks = 1. If searchers are tasked to
make more than one pass through the segment (as aircraft usually do), manually enter
the desired number of tracks. CAUTION: Time in Search Segment (A11b) will 
change if searchers are assigned multiple (more than one) tracks.
LINE 11b “Total Time in Search Segment” (hours)
This is the time a searcher is tasked to spend in the segment track, adjusted for full 
tracks. Divide Team Tracks (A11a) by Searcher Speed (A10), and then multiply by 
Segment Length (A5). (Round to nearest tenth).
For a single-pass through the segment, Total Time in Search Segment is the same as 
Minimum Time to Search Segment (Line 11). If searchers are tasked to search more 
than the Minimum Time to Search Segment (Line 11), manually enter the desired 
time. Total Time in Search Segment does not include time for breaks and 
repositioning. CAUTION: Total Time in Search Segment (Line 11b) cannot be less 
than the Minimum Time to Search Segment (Line 11).
LINE 12 “Probable Success Rate” (PSR)
PSR is the rate of increase in POS for adding one or more units of search effort. 
Multiply Searcher Speed (A10) times Sweep Width (A9) times Segment POC (A8), 
then divide by Segment Area (A7). (Round to nearest hundredth)

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
D-7 31 July 2015
SECTION B: EFFORT ALLOCATION EXPERIMENTATION
LINE 13 “Searchers Assigned to Segment”
For the high-PSR segments the leadership team believes can be searched with the 
number of searchers available, enter a reasonable number of searchers into each 
segment (based on good judgment).
LINE 14 “Searcher Spacing” (feet)
The distance between searchers spread evenly across the baseline. 
For parallel track searches, (Segment Baseline (A6) x 5280) ÷ # Searchers (B13) ÷ 
Team Tracks (A11a) converts the baseline into feet, divides it among the searchers, 
and then divides by the number of tracks. To adjust for the searching “lost” by a 
flanker flagging and unflagging the edge of the team track, use: # searchers (B13) 
minus one.
CAUTION: This equation can yield inaccurate spacing, coverage, POD, POS, and 
PSR when the baseline measurement is not reasonably aligned with the measured 
area. Check you measurements!
For a purposeful wandering-type search, [(Segment Area (A7) x 5280) ÷ (Team 
Tracks (A11b) x Searcher Speed (A10) x # Searchers (B13))] yields the “effective 
spacing” produced by searchers wandering about evenly throughout the segment for 
the assigned time. 
LINE 15 “Coverage”
For parallel track searches, divide Sweep Width (A9) by Searcher Spacing (B14). 
(Round to nearest hundredth)
For all other types of searches (i.e. purposeful wandering), compute the following: 
[(Searcher Speed (A10) x Time in Search Segment (A11b) x Number of Searchers 
(B13)) x (Sweep Width (A9) ÷ 5280)] ÷ Segment Area (A7)
LINE 16 “POD”
Calculate by formula: POD = 1-e
-Coverage (B15)
, or by using the Coverage-POD graph 
on the worksheet. (Round to nearest thousandth)
LINE 17 “POS”
Multiply Segment POC (A8) by POD (B16). (Round to the nearest thousandth)
LINE 18 “POC Remaining After Search”
The POC remaining in the segment after adjusting for the likelihood “searched out” 
by the planned search. Subtract POS (B17) from Segment POC (A8). (Round to 
nearest thousandth)

Inland SAR Planning Student Guide
D-8 31 July 2015
SECTION B: EFFORT ALLOCATION EXPERIMENTATION
LINE 19 “PSR After This Search”
The PSR of the segment after it is searched as planned. Shows the reduced PSR after 
a search, as compared to the PSR prior to the segment being searched (A12). 
Multiply Searcher Speed (A10) by Sweep Width (A9) by POC Remaining After the 
Search (B18). Divide this total by Segment Area (A7). (Round to nearest hundredth)
CHECK FOR POSSIBLE IMPROVEMENTS:
Check the after-search PSR values to determine if a higher POS might be achievable.
o If the after-search PSR of a segment searched is lower than for a segment not 
searched, it is being “over-searched” at the expense of expanding into new segments.
- Consider reallocating some searchers from segments with the lowest after-search 
PSR into additional segments.
o If the after-search PSR of the segments searched are not relatively equal to each 
other, some segments are being over-searched while others are being under-searched.
- Consider reallocating some searchers from segments with the lowest after-search 
PSR into segments with the highest after-search PSR.
o If the after-search PSR of a segment searched is still higher than for the pre-search 
PSR of another segment searched, the second segment is being over-searched at the 
other’s expense.
- It is possible too many segments are being attempted.
- Consider reallocating the searchers from the lower segment into the higher.
After reallocating searchers between segments, recalculate Section B, re-check the after-search 
PSR values, and re-check for high POS.
SELECT A REASONABLE ALLOCATION AND ASSIGN SEARCHERS
SUBSEQUENT SEARCHING:
Plan for the next search period in the same manner, making the following change on the 
worksheet:
o Replace Segment POC (A8) with POC Remaining (B18)
Recalculate current and subsequent periods if searchers return with different results (sweep 
width, spacing, speed, time, amount of the segment searched, etc.)

E-1 31 March 2016
Appendix E
SAR FORMULA REFERENCE SHEET
The formulas and equations in this appendix are those most frequently used by students in the 
Inland SAR Planning Course. Expanded information can be found in this Student Guide and the 
Land SAR Addendum to the National SAR Supplement. 
𝑷𝑶𝑪𝑨𝑺𝑨𝑫 = 𝑷𝒓𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒊𝒕𝒚 𝒐𝒇 𝑶𝒇𝒇𝒔𝒆𝒕 (𝑷𝑶) 𝒙 𝑷𝒓𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒃𝒊𝒍𝒊𝒕𝒚 𝑨𝒍𝒐𝒏𝒈 𝑻𝒓𝒂𝒄𝒌 (𝑷𝑻)
Air Search Area Definition (ASAD): a method of determining the POC for a missing aircraft using 
NASA statistical data relating the find location of missing aircraft to their intended route of flight
Probability of Offset (PO): probability the aircraft is within a given distance (left or right) from the 
centerline of the aircraft intended track.
Probability Along Track (PT): probability the aircraft is between the last know point and a point (as a 
percentage of intended route length) along the route of flight.
𝒑𝑫𝒆𝒏 = 𝑷𝑶𝑪𝒓𝒆𝒈𝒊𝒐𝒏
𝑨𝒓𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒆𝒈𝒊𝒐𝒏
Probability Density (pDen): Probability of Containment (POC) per unit area.
𝑷𝑶𝑪𝒔𝒆𝒈𝒎𝒆𝒏𝒕 = 𝑷𝑶𝑪𝒓𝒆𝒈𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝒙 𝑨𝒓𝒆𝒂𝒔𝒆𝒈𝒎𝒆𝒏𝒕
𝑨𝒓𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒆𝒈𝒊𝒐𝒏
Probability of Containment (POC): the probability that the search object is contained within the 
boundaries of an area, sub-area, [region, segment] or grid cell. (Also called Probability of Area (POA)). 
To calculate POC:
For missing aircraft: Use Air Search Area Definition data if the only clue is the intended route of 
flight; otherwise, use a Proportional Consensus. 
For missing persons/vehicle: Use a Proportional Consensus.
Segment POC: the proportion of the Region POC equal to the segment’s proportion of the region area.
= 𝒑𝑫𝒆𝒏 𝒙 𝑨𝒓𝒆𝒂𝒔𝒆𝒈𝒎𝒆𝒏𝒕
𝑷𝑶𝑺 = 𝑷𝑶𝑪 𝒙 𝑷𝑶𝑫
Probability of Success (POS): The probability of finding the search object with a particular search.

E-2 31 March 2016
SAR Formula Reference Sheet
𝑾 = 𝑾𝒖𝒏𝒄𝒐𝒓𝒓𝒆𝒄𝒕𝒆𝒅 𝒙 𝑪𝒐𝒓𝒓𝒆𝒄𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝑭𝒂𝒄𝒕𝒐𝒓
𝑬𝒇𝒇𝒐𝒓𝒕(𝒛) = 𝑻𝒓𝒂𝒄𝒌 𝑳𝒆𝒏𝒈𝒉𝒕(𝑻𝑳) 𝒙 𝑵𝒖𝒎𝒃𝒆𝒓 𝒐𝒇 𝑺𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒄𝒉𝒆𝒓𝒔(𝑵)
𝑬𝒇𝒇𝒐𝒓𝒕(𝒛) = 𝑺𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒄𝒉𝒆𝒓 𝑺𝒑𝒆𝒆𝒅(𝑽)𝒙 𝑺𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒄𝒉 𝑻𝒊𝒎𝒆(𝑻) 𝒙 𝑵𝒖𝒎𝒃𝒆𝒓 𝒐𝒇 𝑺𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒄𝒉𝒆𝒓𝒔(𝑵)
𝑨𝒓𝒆𝒂 𝑬𝒇𝒇𝒆𝒄𝒕𝒊𝒗𝒆𝒍𝒚 𝑺𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒄𝒉𝒆𝒅(𝒁) = 𝑬𝒇𝒇𝒐𝒓𝒕(𝒛) 𝒙 𝑺𝒘𝒆𝒆𝒑 𝑾𝒊𝒅𝒕𝒉(𝑾)
𝑪𝒐𝒗𝒆𝒓𝒂𝒈𝒆(𝑪) = 𝑨𝒓𝒆𝒂 𝑬𝒇𝒇𝒆𝒄𝒕𝒊𝒗𝒆𝒍𝒚 𝑺𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒄𝒉𝒆𝒅(𝒁)
𝑺𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒄𝒉 𝑨𝒓𝒆𝒂
= 𝑺𝒘𝒆𝒆𝒑 𝑾𝒊𝒅𝒕𝒉(𝑾) 𝒙 𝑬𝒇𝒇𝒐𝒓𝒕(𝒛)
