Inland SAR Planning Course Student Guide
Glossary-1 30 October 2014
Glossary
INLAND SAR PLANNING COURSE
Most terms in this Student Guide can be found in the Land SAR 
Addendum to the NSS, Glossary.
Terms are taken from the IAMSAR Manual, National SAR Supplement, 
or other sources as indicated in parentheses at the end of the definitions.
Terms specific to Cospas-Sarsat, ICS, or other systems will have 
“(Cospas-Sarsat),” “(ICS),” etc. after the term, as appropriate.
a priori probability distribution: the probability (before detection) that 
the target will be in any given part of the search region (Koopman:1980, 
20). Examples are the POCs generated through consensus or from 
historical or statistical data.
Area: the measure or number of square units (nm2, mi2, ft2, etc.) of a 
region, segment, or other portion of a surface. The only time the word 
“area” is used in this text to mean anything other than number of square 
units of a surface is in the context of the “search area” or of “sub-areas” of 
the search area. 
Awareness range: Distance at which a search scanner can first detect 
something different from its surroundings but not yet recognize it. 
(IAMSAR)
Bastard search: Those scenarios in which the search object is not really 
missing and is not in distress; for instance, visiting homes of friends or 
relatives, children hiding in their own rooms, hunters spending time at the 
local bar after the hunt, pilots who change their destinations, etc.
Beacon: Device operating on 121.5, 243, or 406 MHz intended solely for 
distress signaling. (NSS)
Composite position (Cospas-Sarsat): Position generated by the USMCC 
by combining data from two or more satellite passes over a beacon. Any 
ambiguity from previous satellite passes is resolved and solutions from 
different satellite passes merged to refine the position of the beacon. 
(NSS)
Definitions
Introduction

Inland SAR Planning Course Student Guide
Glossary-2 30 October 2014
Glossary (cont.)
Conflict of interest/unfair competition: Using federal-level facilities 
when commercial resources are available. Even though the commercial 
resources may charge fees for their services, law and policy prohibit use of 
federal-level facilities before capable commercial resources are notified 
and given the opportunity to respond to a mission.
Continuous data recording (CDR): Data extraction terminology 
associated with FAA ARTSIII/IIIA and E-ARTS tracking systems. (NSS)
Coordinated search pattern: Multi-unit pattern using vessel(s) and 
aircraft. (IAMSAR)
Coordinated universal time (UTC): International term for time at the 
prime meridian. (IAMSAR)
Coverage factor (C): The ratio of the search effort (Z) to the area 
searched (A). C = Z/A. 
Definite detection: an idealized search that detects all targets within a 
particular region and none outside (Koopman: 1980, p83).
Definite range law detector: an idealized sensor that detects all targets 
within a particular lateral range and none outside. Any detector is said to 
be “equivalent” (under stated conditions) with a particular definite range 
detector if each detects the same expected number of targets in a uniform 
random distribution (from Koopman: 1980). Sensors are said to be 
“equivalent” with a definite range detector having the same sweep width.
Detection: when used without qualification, detection means true 
detection with identification (Koopman:1980, p19).
Duty to act: a legal requirement to act or to perform an act in a certain 
manner or to refrain from acting; as opposed to a moral obligation. A duty 
to act may be established by law, policy, or one’s own actions.
Effective, or equivalent, area searched: the effective area covered by a 
search facility; it is equivalent to the area that would be cleared by a 
definite range law detector with the same sweep width operating under the 
same conditions; that is, which detects on average the same proportion of 
targets in a swarm of uniformly and randomly distributed ones as the 
actual sensor (Koopman: 1980, p 249). 
Engendered reliance: A duty to act created by causing or allowing 
others to expect or rely on one’s actions; based on the body of law holding 
that once a person, company, or agency makes a decision it must proceed 
with due care in the implementation of that decision. 
Definitions 
(cont.)

Inland SAR Planning Course Student Guide
Glossary-3 30 October 2014
Glossary (cont.)
Exponential law of random search: Detection property that does not 
require use of specific search detection functions, procedures, or 
assumptions about search conditions or navigational accuracies; unlike the 
restrictions of the inverse cube law of detection. It is useful for inland 
searches because of expected variations in terrain, vegetation cover, and 
search paths. Probability of detection is dependent on only coverage 
factor, which is dependent on only sweep width without regard to a 
specific detection function, making the law very flexible and valid for 
nearly any reasonable detection function and providing a lower bound for 
expected search performance (POD). (Koopman: 1980, p 71-78; 
Frost:1998, p 5-2 – 5-5) POD = 1 – e -c 
Fixed base operator (FBO): Commercial business located at an airport 
engaged in fuel sales, aircraft maintenance, hanger rental, etc. 
Function: a mathematical rule of correspondence: y is said to be a 
function of x [ y=f(x)] if for the determination of the value of y it is 
sufficient to give that of x. 
Hoax: Alert determined to result from any distress signal intended for 
deceptive purposes. (NSS)
Image (mirror image) (Cospas-Sarsat): Of the two positions associated 
with a single satellite pass, the one from which a signal is not emanating. 
(NSS)
Inverse cube law: detection property in which the probability of 
detection is proportional to the inverse of the cube of the lateral range. 
This law has been used in several forms to approximate actual detection 
capabilities under various conditions and is currently used in maritime 
search. (Koopman: 1980, p 59).
Lateral range: distance between the target and the observer at their point 
of closest approach (Koopman: 1980, p 31), in the inland environment 
with a stationary target it is generally measured as the perpendicular 
distance between the track of the sensor and the target. 
Management by objectives (ICS): A top-down management activity 
which involves a three-step process to achieve the incident goal. The steps 
are: establishing the incident objectives, selection of appropriate 
strategy(s) to achieve the objectives, and the tactical direction associated 
with the selected strategy. Tactical direction includes: selection of tactics, 
selection of resources, resource assignments, and performance monitoring.
Mission conclusion stage: A period during a SAR incident when SAR 
facilities return to their regular location and prepare for another mission. 
(NSS)
Definitions 
(cont.)

Inland SAR Planning Course Student Guide
Glossary-4 30 October 2014
Glossary (cont.)
Negligence, comparative: A legal doctrine by which acts of the opposing 
parties are compared to determine the liability of each party to the other, 
making each liable only for his or her percentage of fault. See also 
contributory negligence.
Negligence, contributory: A legal doctrine that says if the plaintiff in a 
civil action for negligence also was negligent, he or she cannot recover 
damages from the defendant for the defendant's negligence. Most 
jurisdictions have abandoned the doctrine of contributory negligence in 
favor of comparative negligence. 
Negligence, gross: The intentional failure to perform a manifest duty in 
reckless disregard of the consequences as affecting the life or property of 
another, such a gross want of care and regard for the rights of others as to 
justify the presumption of willfulness and wantonness. Willful and 
wanton: The actor has intentionally done an act of an unreasonable 
character in disregard of a risk known to himself or so obvious that they 
must be taken to have been aware of it, and so great as to make it highly 
probable that harm would follow.
Negligence, ordinary: A breach of the duty to act with that amount of 
care which a reasonably prudent person would use under the same or 
similar conditions. The omission of that care which a person of common 
prudence usually takes of his or her own concerns. Failure to exercise 
care of an ordinarily prudent person in the same situation. A want of that 
care and prudence that the great majority of mankind exercise under the 
same or similar circumstances or the creation of an unreasonable risk of 
harm toward a third person.
Objectives, incident (ICS): Statements of guidance and direction 
necessary for the selection of appropriate strategy(s), and the tactical 
direction of resources. Incident objectives are based on realistic 
expectations of what can be accomplished when all allocated resources 
have been effectively deployed. Incident objectives must be achievable 
and measurable, yet flexible enough to allow for strategic and tactical 
alternatives.
Plan: A method for achieving an end (Webster). A well thought out set 
of intended actions, from which one may freely deviate as the situation 
warrants.
Primary radar return: Radar signal energy reflected off of skin or 
surface of an aircraft. (NSS)
Definitions 
(cont.)

Inland SAR Planning Course Student Guide
Glossary-5 30 October 2014
Glossary (cont.)
Probability: “Probability,” as applied in common parlance to a surmise, 
indicates a perception of its “likelihood,” “reasonability to suppose,” 
“chance of being true,” … “degree of rational belief.” It always contains 
the implication that some knowledge exists bearing on the surmise, but not 
enough to determine its truth or falsity. Thus it is perfectly consistent for 
different people possessed of different knowledge to appraise it 
differently. Koppman:1980, p 277).
SAR airspace reservation: Temporary airspace reservation to prevent 
non-SAR aircraft from interfering with SAR operations. (IAMSAR)
Secondary radar return: A radio signal received from an aircraft 
equipped with an airborne radar beacon system. More commonly referred 
to as a transponder or beacon return. (NSS)
Situation report (SITREP): Reports, from the OSC to the SMC or the 
SMC to interested agencies, to keep informed of on scene conditions and 
mission progress. (IAMSAR)
Span of control (ICS): The supervisory ratio of from three-to-seven 
individuals, with five-to-one being established as optimum.
Tactical Direction (ICS): Direction given by the Operations Section 
Chief which includes the tactics appropriate for the selected strategy, the 
selection and assignment of resources, tactics implementation, and 
performance monitoring for each operational period.
Unfair competition/conflict of interest: Using federal-level facilities 
when commercial resources are available. Even though the commercial 
resources may charge fees for their services, law and policy prohibit use of 
federal-level facilities before capable commercial resources are notified 
and given the opportunity to respond to a mission.
Vicarious liability: Liability experience by way of another person; the 
liability of an organization, its officers, and supervisors for the acts or 
omissions of those whom they supervise.
Definitions 
(cont.)

